	Document(content="""Note: <div><div><div><div><div><p>Some students have requested extra references for the data science topics, particularly, those covered in the second half of the course, including regression, clustering, classification, and neural networks. Here are three textbook references, all with free PDF versions available online:</p></div></div></div></div><ul><li>G. James, D. Witten, T. Hastie, and R. Tibshirani, &#34;An Introduction to Statistical Learning,&#34; Springer, 2021.<br />Link: <a href='https://www.statlearning.com/' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>https://www.statlearning.com/</a> </li><li>T. Hastie, R. Tibshirani, and J. H. Friedman, &#34;The Elements of Statistical Learning,&#34; Springer, 2017.<br />Link: <a href='https://hastie.su.domains/ElemStatLearn/' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>https://hastie.su.domains/ElemStatLearn/</a></li><li>C. M. Bishop, &#34;Pattern Recognition and Machine Learning,&#34; Springer, 2006.<br />Link: <a href='https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/research/publication/pattern-recognition-machine-learning/' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/research/publication/pattern-recognition-machine-learning/</a></li></ul><div><div><div><div><p>All these books are great references. The first one has a more high-level and applied view while the other two are more detailed and theory-oriented. </p><p><br /><strong>Note:</strong> These extra references are completely optional and are provided for those of you who prefer to have a reference textbook to complement the course materials and gain a deeper understanding of the topics.</p></div></div></div></div></div><p></p>""", meta={'folders': ['other'], 'title': 'Extra data science references', 'timestamp': '2023-04-01T18:18:19Z', 'user': 'ks3l0aykohs3yd', 'tags': ['instructor-note', 'other', 'pin'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 300}),
