	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5c9zhn81nj%2F1cee0a8f208da35ffb5470d965fd02ed0bfa3af5d92b1048402e42fad5207ff5%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' width='219' height='78' /></p><p>How does this function above translate to this function below?</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5c9zhn81nj%2Feb89f17184bfc4529622dda4743272c36e09ae0f8fbe1f5296787e77373a97b2%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' width='408' height='86' /></p><p>I am also unable to understand how what s and m correlates to.</p> Answer: To clarify, you should know how to perform GD in general, not only for logistic regression. So, both examples are important in that regard.""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Logistic regression gradient ascent doubt', 'timestamp': '2023-05-05T15:04:50Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 140}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>How are the heights of the distributions for cluster 1 and 2 calculated?</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fksi8ka1ba1t6tv%2Fa4396988cb9d8534d1e1d28c242cb77f2c69a8b4a8fc5e0a9b8c6a076fc81262%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: You can calculate them by using the formula 0.4/sigma. This is not the height of the normalized PDF though. You have to multiply by the corresponding Gaussian weight so that the area under the PDF integrates to 1. """, meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Exam 3 Spring 2022 Q3) Gaussian Mixture Models (Calculating Heights)', 'timestamp': '2023-05-05T14:09:50Z', 'user': 'ksi8ka1ba1t6tv', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 136}),
	Document(content="""Question: When does K-mean clustering converge? It is when the mean is the same as the cluster values. Answer: K-Means clustering converges when the value of the sum of squared distances for an initialization stops changing after each iteration. When the center point stops moving for the cluster...""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'K-mean clustering', 'timestamp': '2023-05-05T13:52:28Z', 'user': 'ktnb839mwas1tt', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 108}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>How is cluster two&#39;s centroid calculated given cluster one&#39;s updated centroid?<img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fksi8ka1ba1t6tv%2F57cb7ed3f9c06d580e2a487f1d4335e1ef4874d38667a706cd17823bbb8432cf%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p><p></p> Answer: <p>sum of the values in the cluster divided by the number of items in the cluster. it isn&#39;t dependent on cluster 1. Only sum over 1 variable at a time<br />$$\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^N x_i$$</p><p></p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fksp1a90bcfq277%2Fed73363677698a139bc516c40a3c6ba31c80f5c0b562ffe341f60bffb0dab380%2FSpring2022Exam3-6.jpg' alt='Spring2022Exam3-6.jpgNaN' /></p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 Q2b', 'timestamp': '2023-05-05T13:34:36Z', 'user': 'ksi8ka1ba1t6tv', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 109}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5nwghln3f2%2Fc4fc239a0fe5961d35b8483e55e0cac30a94762fa64a3e266a22b963cfb73238%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' width='517' height='417' /></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5nwghln3f2%2Fb0c8d7e797d43b6e80faa23aa9616334b6593ad37e13be89223b85fa6c6a8d96%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' width='743' height='128' /></p><p>how does the solution for this match up with the given equation in the slides? why is the f(sum) = f(0) which is equal to 1/2?</p> Answer: The first term in the derivative is specific to the loss function used (which is different in the slides and in the exam).""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 2022 question 6 part B', 'timestamp': '2023-05-05T03:55:49Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 113}),
	Document(content="""Question: I am in Professor Ghasemi&#39;s, and on Brightspace, I still have a 0 for the course evaluation extra credit. Is this for everyone or is it just me? Answer: Course evaluation bonus has been updated on Brightspace. Thanks! """, meta={'folders': ['other'], 'title': 'Course Evaluation Extra Credit', 'timestamp': '2023-05-05T03:50:07Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['other', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 115}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5b8oexj1jg%2Fb2ade1bc38e223db793ed55036d1354041ad95ab2cf14a1f7e3240736ebacc52%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p><p>why doesn&#39;t delta0 include the negative sign?</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5b8oexj1jg%2F2af8b03ef77d92b8ad9ff0281f5134d77f459b344722af096fd627591cdf29ed%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p><p>while the delta in the other practice exam includes the negative</p> Answer: The partial derivative of the loss function with respect to $$f(w^Tx)$$ is going to give you $$-(y-f(w^Tx))^2$$ in the first example/picture (this is just chain rule). For the loss function in the second function that partial derivative is just -1 which is the first term in the expression for $$ \delta_0$$<div>Edit: Sorry for the misunderstanding - I think this is a matter of notation here. In the slides, $$ \delta_0$$ does not have the negative and for the weight update step, you  do $$ w^{t +1}= w^t + \alpha * \delta_0 * x_i $$. For the second example, while they include the negative for the $$\delta_0$$, their weight update step is $$ w^{t +1}= w^t - \alpha * \delta_0 * x_i $$. Note the change in sign here - you will essentially be doing the same process, numerically but it&#39;s just that for the second example, the notation was changed. Make sure you are consistent with the notation here - I would suggest that you go with the notation in the first example/in the slides.</div>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'spring 2022 q6', 'timestamp': '2023-05-05T02:28:05Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 118}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5nwghln3f2%2Ff514e144ffceab92aeecdae7518d9ccdd6b31691a0e57a222f1b4f560be31163%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p><p></p><p>how does the k affect the datapoint? is the k referring to the number of circles on the graph?</p> Answer: With Knn, you classify a point according to whichever class is the most present among the k nearest neighbors.""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 2022 question 1 D', 'timestamp': '2023-05-05T02:04:03Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 106}),
