	Document(content="""Question: How was the underlined line in the answers calculated/concluded?  Furthermore, why is P(X|G2) = 0 but P(X|G1) = 1<div><p></p><img src='https://piazza.com/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=attach%2Flcj9rez4czg6zj%2Fk4wvl7kbg507pf%2Fvqhciqqssdaj%2Fpublic_2023_05_03.jpeg' /><br /></div> Answer: This is because X is greater than greater than mean &#43; 3 standard deviations of cluster 2 or 9.2-2.5 &gt; 3 * 0.8 . In part b, it says that if that&#39;s the case the the probability is 0. Hence the P(G2) is 0 and P(G1) is 1""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 Exam 3: Q3 Part C', 'timestamp': '2023-05-03T22:13:17Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 131}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5b8oexj1jg%2F91a567176a31ea46ff43f20ecd7c5ffceb9988fe06017495c45c729cf8dacb21%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p><p>How can we conclude that option d is correct? What does the model have to do with the odds of buying a car?</p> Answer: <p></p><p>Refer to the image below for context - here, the coefficient for the number of kids feature is negative, which means that the odds will decrease - and for the other two features, the coefficients are positive, meaning the odds will increase. This is from the logistic regression slides.<img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fke80y12ngei1tx%2F67db75d7c9363b8c50adb4e3c20438aa5ff18be36c4dc1a695f16e7b8424074a%2FScreenshot_20230503_134919_Adobe_Acrobat.jpg' width='1130' height='826' alt='' /></p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'spring 2022 exam3 q5b', 'timestamp': '2023-05-03T14:31:54Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 130}),
