	Document(content="""Question: <p>Where did we get the orignial formula? Also, how did the transition from the first to second step? Is there a certain lecture slide that would help me?</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fl6maptmggzy7op%2F2e5c033bd09ab9b88bd39e45c72da6db90a705b0bf68e1434dd418d736f9a81c%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p> Answer: (Slide question resolved below.) To address the question at a high-level, the original formula is just the chain rule from your past calculus course.""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 Exam 3 6bii', 'timestamp': '2023-05-03T04:17:59Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 114}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Can anyone explain, why is Initialization 0 provide best clustering?</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb6igyqfbch%2F37bbe0d2fdd7720eaf58af4df58c5e7e5d5bec626795f26b8d3858ef419692df%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p> Answer: If you look at the last iteration (iteration 7), you can see that initialization 0 has the lowest value compared to the other initializations. The lower the squared distances to the cluster center the better the clustering is.<div><br /></div>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 2022 Q1 PART c', 'timestamp': '2023-05-03T03:36:05Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 116}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I was reviewing the notes and I think I found a typo in the logistic regression slides. The upper limit of the sum should be n not m. m is the dimension of each data point. Whereas n is the number of data points. Am I correct or did I miss something?</p><p></p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb6jzuz0ejk%2Fae6a900b7f8e7c54ce181f39d4c35fae743570af603dd1a65c79cf0d29a6f15d%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: Yes the upper limit of the summation should be n, not m.""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Typo in Logistic Regression slides', 'timestamp': '2023-05-02T21:22:03Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 110}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb3wm15ca2pa%2Fe2d21acef45a2aec4db8a3a8dfe1e0a4c5c59e6033c8ebe5b9999e3f83003238%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p><p>why is f(0) 1/2, if in part A we are told that the activation function is f(x)=x</p><p>wouldnt that make f(0) = 0?</p> Answer: If the activation function is f(x) = x, yes, f(0) = 0. In this case we are specifically using a sigmoid function, $$\frac{1}{1 + e^{-x}} $$, so when x=0, you get 1/2.""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'exam 3 fall 2022 q6b', 'timestamp': '2023-05-02T15:19:43Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 122}),
	Document(content="""Question: <img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5b8oexj1jg%2F54746b0c47822b285970634c8f1b54dc4c0c356bcf1eb9f5fa5d70a142f9b404%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' />Why should we use x as vertical 0,3,-1 instead of horizontal 0,3,-1. Doesn&#39;t that mean we need to transpose x. Vise versa, why is w transpose horizontal 1,2,6. Shouldn&#39;t it be vertical 1,2,6? Answer: sorry i asked a question after this person, but figured it out. """, meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'spring 2022 q6b', 'timestamp': '2023-05-02T15:09:05Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 107}),
	Document(content="""Question: could someone explain whats the difference between those two, mathematically and theoryically Answer: <p>p($$G_i$$| x) means the probability of $$G_i$$(I am assuming g means Gaussian) given x. This is the probability that the data point x comes from the Gaussian distribution $$G_i$$. This can be calculated using Bayes theorem. </p><p></p><p>p(x |$$G_i$$ ) means the probability of the data point x given Gaussian distribution $$G_i$$. This can be directly obtained from looking at the value of the PDF of the Gaussian at x. </p><p></p><p>I feel like my professor didn&#39;t explain Bayes theorem properly. Here is a good video I found for Bayes Theorem. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HZGCoVF3YvM</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'difference between P(g|x) and P(x|g)', 'timestamp': '2023-05-02T14:48:55Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 97}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5b8oexj1jg%2F48802587ae7bad0698a5ff32f3f5d12cbedcaba4611874ba45aa2143e87bc4de%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p><p>Is n_s the number of unique words in each class or just the number of words?</p> Answer: The total number of words in that class. So class S for the first one and class N for the second one.""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'lapalace smoothing', 'timestamp': '2023-05-02T13:58:09Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 95}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5b8oexj1jg%2F8bf90588a9f035a6463c632ff3fe55ba4f4145969151037b45deda3bae13550b%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p><p>Why hasn&#39;t the algorithm converged? After part b of updating the centroid, no points move to the other cluster. Doesn&#39;t that mean the algorithm has converged?</p> Answer: To check for convergence, you should compare if the centroid coordinates remain unchanged from the earlier step or not. If the centroid remains unchanged (that is, no points are moving), then the algorithm has converged.""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 Exam 3 Q2c', 'timestamp': '2023-05-02T03:57:03Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 107}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5b8oexj1jg%2Fc940759b66b22a2d890bea9388516976e4a012db9ef7da23e1a224488356b0d7%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p><p>Why do we have to call super().calculatedCoolDownWatt() instead of self.calculatedCoolDownWatt()?</p> Answer: It&#39;s because the method calculatedCoolDownWatt is from the parent class of NewClass. super() indicates that it belongs to the class that the current class inherits from. Alternatively, you can use self.calculateCoolDownWatt() as well.""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 Exam 3 Q1a', 'timestamp': '2023-05-02T03:37:54Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 93}),
	Document(content="""Question: Why are the heights of the gaussian distribution 0.25 and 0.20. I thought that the height was 0.4/(std dev), which would cause the heights to be 0.5 and 0.4. Also, how do we need to use the variance to find the exact width of the graph? Answer: As the student answer says, the heights of the distributions are scaled by the weights $$ \pi_1 $$ and $$ \pi_2$$. As for the width, you can use the fact that within 1$$\sigma$$ of the mean, there&#39;s 68% of the area of the distribution, within 2$$\sigma$$ of the mean there&#39;s 95% of the area of the distribution and so on to get an idea of how wide you should draw your graph. (So, if you have a small variance, your graph will be narrow, as you might expect from intuition)""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'spring 2022 exam 3 #3b', 'timestamp': '2023-05-02T02:19:38Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 116}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Can someone explain how they get the 0.5 in these equations? </p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb46l8gil3vd%2Fa968f26629e65063abe807728f178841703c9806ab2ccee46573fb38ac3e2730%2FScreenshot_2023-05-01_220759.png' width='1845' height='833' alt='' /></p> Answer: <p>Referring to the gradient ascent and logistic regression slidedeck, the gradient ascent equation is (for 1 iteration)</p><p>$$ \beta_j^{t+1} = \beta_j^t + \alpha * \sum_1^n {(y_i - f_{\beta}(x_i)) x_{ij}}$$</p><p>Here, $$\beta_j$$ is the the coefficient of jth feature (and $$\beta_0$$ is the constant in the regression), n is the number of datapoints, $$\alpha$$ is the step size, t - the iteration and f is the logistic regression equation. Note that $$x_{ij}$$ refers to the jth feature of the ith point.</p><p>So in this question, x has 2 features - the age ($$x_1$$)and the length of stay ($$x_2$$)</p><p>$$ f_{\beta}(x) = \frac{1}{1+exp(-(-3 + 0.1x_1 - 1*x_2))} $$</p><p>So, you know that in this case, $$ \beta_0 = -3, \beta_1 = 0.1$$ and$$ \beta_2 = -1$$. So in our case right now, we have only 1 points to consider, so we are going to have n = 1. Now for the gradient ascent,</p><p>For $$\beta_0$$ (this is the constant, so $$x_{ij}$$ = 1)we have - </p><p>$$ \beta_0^{t+1} = \beta_0^t + \alpha *  {(y - f_{\beta}(x)) * 1}$$</p><p>For $$\beta_1$$ we have - </p><p></p><p>$$ \beta_1^{t+1} = \beta_1^t + \alpha *  {(y - f_{\beta}(x)) x_{1}}$$</p><p>For $$\beta_2$$ we have - </p><p></p><p>$$ \beta_2^{t+1} = \beta_2^t + \alpha*  {(y - f_{\beta}(x)) x_{2}}$$</p><p>The logistic function is </p><p>$$ f_{\beta}(x) = \frac{1}{1+exp(-(-3 + 0.1x_1 - 1*x_2))} $$, which will evaluate to </p><p>$$ f_{\beta}(x) = \frac{1}{1+exp(-(-3 + 0.1*0 - 1*(-3)))} = 0.5 $$ when you consider the data point stated in the question (when the age is 0, and the length of stay is -3). The y (cancel/not cancel) is stated to be 1.</p><p>So our gradient ascent equation is now:</p><p>For $$\beta_0$$ (the constant term)we have - </p><p></p><p>$$ \beta_0^{t+1} = (-3) + \alpha *  {(1 - 0.5) * 1}$$</p><p>For $$\beta_1$$ (the age coefficient)we have - </p><p></p><p>$$ \beta_1^{t+1} = 0.1+ \alpha *  {(1 - 0.5) * 0}$$</p><p></p><p>For $$\beta_2$$ (the length of stay coefficient)we have - </p><p></p><p>$$ \beta_2^{t+1} = -1 + \alpha *  {(1 - 0.5) * (-3)}$$</p><p></p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 2022 Final 4C', 'timestamp': '2023-05-02T02:08:56Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 119}),
