	Document(content="""Question: When doing kmeans how do you know how many groups you should make and where the centers should be? I&#39;m kinda confused on this specifically im using it for path 1. Answer: <p>The number of clusters for k-means clustering, i.e., the value of k, is either clear from context, e.g., k = 2 if you want to interpret the clusters as 2 classes, or it needs to be determined using cross-validation techniques. In the latter case, you would need to try out different values of k and see which one gives the lowest validation error. </p><p></p><p>The centers (or &#34;centroids&#34;) of the clusters are determined by the algorithm. So, you do not need to know where the final centers are a priori. Of course, you do need to initialize the algorithm with some centers. This center initialization is arbitrary, e.g., randomly generate centers. Since the performance of the algorithm does depend on the initialization, it is often a good idea to try several initializations. Python libraries have inputs that allow you to control number of initializations, or even utilize more advanced initialization methods such as kmeans&#43;&#43; (kmeans&#43;&#43; will not be tested in your exam).</p>""", meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Kmeans question', 'timestamp': '2023-04-30T21:54:59Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 129}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Am I doing something wrong with my implementation of mse for it to be this high? I&#39;ve tried to normalize, but nothing has helped it go down. Here is my code.</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fke9a93fhmtv60v%2F0961a3a9254c843a6dea6e4ba9e83982ece3c2ddb91b96676164f6583349a0d6%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fke9a93fhmtv60v%2F20b0915c8cb63496f33d5571396b67cac26d023ecaaab28cfd3deb3f64f05ae8%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p> Answer: This is normal - the number of bicyclists has a high order of magnitude so, squaring it would have a high order of magnitude as well. The R2 score is a better measure of fit for linear regression models .<div><div><br /></div><div><br /></div></div>""", meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Any reason why my MSE is crazy high in my implementation', 'timestamp': '2023-04-30T21:34:22Z', 'user': 'ke9a93fhmtv60v', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 10}),
