	Document(content="""Question: <p>How did we get the squared term for $$\delta$$?</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fksi8k0dd7bh6fe%2Fde641556d737d5dc1a3d0435aaa0cb4ed24d3c3a41fc12e7c90c0f5a3bb8daeb%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' width='617' height='427' /></p><p></p><p>In the slides, it isn&#39;t squared:</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fksi8k0dd7bh6fe%2F630de044363f81f8a4b38db272290ea2d5f118a73d189edec43fde2424416d02%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' width='605' height='337' /></p> Answer: When you take the partial derivative of the loss function with respect to f(sum) , you would get squared term.""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 Exam 3- Q6bii', 'timestamp': '2023-04-30T18:53:57Z', 'user': 'ksi8k0dd7bh6fe', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 124}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>How did we get the $$\beta$$ equations?</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fksi8k0dd7bh6fe%2F0dcbc7af9f90d5fd2ab0f3ff065ac90d1fc7dd2fa1bece407ad500ea2753a24d%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' width='652' height='446' /></p> Answer: <p>The equations for gradient descent are in the logistic regression slide deck. Specifically, for 1 iteration -</p><div>$$ \beta_j^{t+1} = \beta_j^t - \alpha \frac{\partial {l(\beta_j)}}{\partial {\beta_j}} $$ for gradient ascent where $$ \alpha $$ is the step size and t is the iteration number and l is the loss function.</div><div>You are essentially trying to minimize the loss function and find the optimal value of the coefficients for logistic regression using this method.</div>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 Exam 3- Q5a', 'timestamp': '2023-04-30T18:25:02Z', 'user': 'ksi8k0dd7bh6fe', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 135}),
