	Document(content="""Question: <p>Can anyone explain what are we doing here?</p><p>Thanks.</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb6igyqfbch%2F00cfc0f407bc95c4e2f184c5a95784cb1b0d8f2162b5422b94875ced9fb21d9b%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p> Answer: L(x) is given to you, so to find the partial derivative$$\frac{\partial L(x)}{\partial w_j}$$ we need to take the partial derivative. L(x) is given as $$y - f(x)$$ so we take that partial derivative. dy is 0 so ignore that, so we have to do a derivative operation. (there is a derivative identity here, I call it derivative of the outside times derivative of the inside), so you get $$\frac{\partial f(w^T x)}{\partial w^T x}$$ and the derivative of the inside $$\frac{\partial w^T x}{\partial w_j}$$. technically, you don&#39;t need the first term with L(x) but that will give you the -1 term.so the equation becomes $$\frac{\partial f(w^T x)}{\partial w^T x}\frac{\partial w^T x}{\partial w_j}$$ which is $$\frac{\partial f(w^T x)}{\partial w^T x} = f(w^T x)(1-f(w^T x))$$ and $$\frac{\partial w^T x}{\partial w_j} = x_j$$. that gives you the first equation. Gradient descent starts at 0 and calculates the delta step so $$\nabla \frac{L(x)}{w_j}$$ at the 0th step is $$\delta_0$$ which is your step in the $$L(x)/w_j $$ direction. So a more formal way of writing the GD algo is $$ w-\alpha (\nabla \frac{L(x)}{w_j})*x$$ (make sure you actually calculate the dot product to see that it is zero) $$w^T x$$ which is $$1*2 + 2*2 + (-2*3) = 0$$.""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 2022 exam 3 doubt', 'timestamp': '2023-04-30T04:28:28Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 141}),
	Document(content="""Question: For the miniproject, I implemented about 8 or 9 different models and multiple iterations for the analysis,  such as linear, logistic, gradient boosting, XGBoost, regression, and support vector, kNN, and random forest classifiers. I also implemented a neural network. However, many of these models did not perform as well as others, and I only ended up affirming/denying the questions in path 2 based on linear regression and the random forest classifier. However, I mention and have visuals on the performance of all the other models in my report. Many of those are not in the script for the miniproject, and many of them were overwritten with new implementations once I retrieved an accuracy measure/graph to use in the report. Am I expected to submit them, or should I only submit the final two models I settled on for my conclusions?I asked a T.A. and Instructor about this and they said to only submit the final two models I used to finalize my answer, I just want further confirmation. Answer: Yes - submit the models that you used to draw your conclusions/finalise your answers.""", meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'What code should I submit?', 'timestamp': '2023-04-29T22:22:47Z', 'user': 'ktnb6mjuvqb13k', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 23}),
	Document(content="""Note: <p>Homework 10 has been graded and grades have been released for all sections. To view your feedback, please go to your Homework 10 repository on GitHub, click the drop-down menu under &#39;main&#39; --&gt; click &#39;Tags&#39; --&gt; click &#39;graded&#39; <br /><br />You will find a file named grading_output.txt in your repository, which contains the output of the grading script specifying the test cases you passed and the points you received for each test case.</p><p>Please note that homeworks are generally graded based on the number of test cases passed. <br /><br /></p><p>If you believe there has been an error in grading, you can send a regrade request to <a href='mailto:ece20875.purdue.university@gmail.com' target='_new' rel='noopener noreferrer'>ece20875.purdue.university@gmail.com</a>. You have one week from the day grades are posted to Brightspace to request a regrade. Please include the following information in your email:<br /><br />1. Link to your homework&#39;s GitHub repository <br />2. Section Number<br />3. Grading item (e.g., homework 10).<br />4. Purdue email (if not sent from a Purdue email)<br />5. Your reasoning or explanation for a regrade, with specific details and justification pointing to the README.<br /><br /></p><p>When submitting an email for a homework regrade request please do the following:</p><p>   1. Have a separate email for each HW<br />   2. Have the subject line be the following: HW# regrade request<br /><br />It is of utmost importance to understand that any request for a regrade must adhere to the given format. Heavily deviating from the provided guidelines may result in the request not being addressed at all.<br /><br />As usual, feel free to post on Piazza with any additional questions :-)</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw10'], 'title': 'Homework 10 Grades Released!', 'timestamp': '2023-04-29T21:07:28Z', 'user': 'kskmx82xa2s4ad', 'tags': ['hw10', 'instructor-note'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 110}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I am trying to use logistic regression for problem 3 in path 2 but I am getting a very low accuracy score. Is there something I am missing? My code is below.</p><p></p><pre>&#39;&#39;&#39;Problem 3: Can you use this data to predict what day (Monday to Sunday) is today based on the number of bicyclists on the bridges?&#39;&#39;&#39;print(&#39;Problem 3: ----------------&#39;)#print(dataset_2[&#39;Day&#39;].values)for day in dataset_2[&#39;Day&#39;].values:    if day == &#39;Monday&#39;:        dataset_2[&#39;Day&#39;] = dataset_2[&#39;Day&#39;].replace(&#39;Monday&#39;, 0, regex=True)    elif day == &#39;Tuesday&#39;:        dataset_2[&#39;Day&#39;] = dataset_2[&#39;Day&#39;].replace(&#39;Tuesday&#39;, 1, regex=True)    elif day == &#39;Wednesday&#39;:        dataset_2[&#39;Day&#39;] = dataset_2[&#39;Day&#39;].replace(&#39;Wednesday&#39;, 2, regex=True)    elif day == &#39;Thursday&#39;:        dataset_2[&#39;Day&#39;] = dataset_2[&#39;Day&#39;].replace(&#39;Thursday&#39;, 3, regex=True)    elif day == &#39;Friday&#39;:        dataset_2[&#39;Day&#39;] = dataset_2[&#39;Day&#39;].replace(&#39;Friday&#39;, 4, regex=True)    elif day == &#39;Saturday&#39;:        dataset_2[&#39;Day&#39;] = dataset_2[&#39;Day&#39;].replace(&#39;Saturday&#39;, 5, regex=True)    elif day == &#39;Sunday&#39;:        dataset_2[&#39;Day&#39;] = dataset_2[&#39;Day&#39;].replace(&#39;Sunday&#39;, 6, regex=True)#print(dataset_2[&#39;Day&#39;].values)X = dataset_2[[&#39;Total&#39;]].valuesy = dataset_2[&#39;Day&#39;].valuesX_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=0)logreg = LogisticRegression()logreg.fit(X_train, y_train)print(&#39;Coefficients of trained model:&#39;, logreg.coef_)print(&#39;Intercept of trained model:&#39;, logreg.intercept_)y_pred = logreg.predict(X_test)acc_score = metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)print(&#39;Accuracy Score:&#39;, acc_score)Here is the output:Problem 3: ----------------Coefficients of trained model: [[ 1.14212503e-05] [ 7.30796222e-06] [ 3.51087935e-06] [ 1.41510119e-06] [-2.47537468e-06] [-1.31674387e-05] [-8.01237975e-06]]Intercept of trained model: [ 1.20268248e-10 -1.04798681e-09 -2.91201421e-09 -1.42126335e-09  3.70673437e-10  2.00567332e-09  2.88464936e-09]Accuracy Score: 0.046511627906976744</pre><p></p> Answer: I would recommend you use all the bridges as your features (that is your logistic regression will use $$ \frac{1}{1 + exp(-(w_1B_1 + w_2B_2 + w_3B_3 + w_4B_4 + c))}$$ instead of $$\frac{1}{1+exp(-(w_0T + c))} $$ where B1, B2, B3, B4 are thenunber of cyclists on the  bridges and T is the total number of bicyclists. In other words, your X will be dataset[&#39;Williamsburg Bridge&#39;, &#39;Brooklyn Bridge&#39;, ...,] and so on""", meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Project Path 2 Part 3 Logistic Regression', 'timestamp': '2023-04-29T20:41:50Z', 'user': 'ktnb4yplxsk7g3', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 12}),
	Document(content="""Question: For that question I am trying to use Naive Bayer classifier to make a model to predict which day is in a week by given total traffic number of that day. In order to do that, i set list of total traffic number as x and list of week day as y. Which model should I use in this question? GuassianNb or multinominalNb? Answer: <p>I also tried that approach with mixed results, but I&#39;d take a look at using the individual bridge numbers and multiple different features rather than the total number of riders of all of them as a single feature.</p><p></p><p>Also I used GaussianNB.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Project path2 step 3', 'timestamp': '2023-04-29T18:39:49Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 124}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I&#39;m looking at the Introduction to Neural Networks slides right now. I&#39;m on the page titled &#34;Multi-layer NN Mathematical Form&#34; and I&#39;m having trouble understanding the four steps. </p><p></p><p>My current interpretation is this: </p><p>1. you can find the individual outputs of each neuron in a layer by taking the dot product of the inputs and their weights</p><p>2. you can find the outputs of whole layers by doing matrix multiplication of the weights and the inputs for the whole layer at a time (example of this by hand?)</p><p>3. with each individual output you have, you then apply the activation function to the output at each layer</p><p></p><p>I&#39;m stuck on step 2, and i&#39;m not sure if my overall interpretation is correct.</p> Answer: at the end of the day, neural nets are just solving a linear system of equations (i.e. y = Ax &#43;b)so the weights and inputs become$$\begin{bmatrix} z_1 \\z_2\end{bmatrix}= \begin{bmatrix}W_1  \\W_2  \end{bmatrix}^T\begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\x_2\end{bmatrix}+ \begin{bmatrix} b_1 \\b_2\end{bmatrix}$$b is also there and is called the bias and is set similarly to what we have learned in class (line fitting). for an MLP the A matrix is a vector, but for a CNN the matrix is 2D (3D for r,g,b) images. For the final weights, the matrix is usually transformed into a vector for multiplication, but the weights are still &#34;3D&#34; where they correspond to a pixel(s) on the 2D image (R,G,B). The activation function is just f(x). like sin(x) or exp(x) (these aren&#39;t used for the activation function, but gives intuition)""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Deep NN Math', 'timestamp': '2023-04-29T18:25:20Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 112}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Hi,</p><p></p><p>I have a question about path 2 part 2 of the mini project. I tried to use ridge regression to try and find a model to relate weather and the number of cyclists. However, I am getting a ridiculously high MSE (14734737.954218388) and there seems to be no relation. I took an approach similar to hw7. Is it ok to conclude that there is no way to predict the number of cyclists based on weather or should I look for a better model?</p><p></p><p>Thanks.</p> Answer: The high MSE can also be due to the fact that the order of magnitude of the numbers is somewhere in the order of 10^4 - so squaring higher order numbers leads to a high MSE. You can try evaluating the r^2 score of your linear regression using model.score(x_test, y_test) (where model is your linear regression model).""", meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Question about Mini Project Path 2 Part 2', 'timestamp': '2023-04-29T09:52:03Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 13}),
