	Document(content="""Question: For part 3 my model is getting an accuracy score of 44%. I am trying different methods to improve this but I wanted to know if its fine if I come to the conclusion that there is no strong correlation or if I have to find some model that&#39;s better Answer: Ideally it shouldn&#39;t be that low or that&#39;s atleast in my case. I would recheck all the parameters that are being used for different functions since that&#39;s where most of the things go wrong. You can also try plotting your results to see if the plotted labels actually match with ur accuracy score. If nothing works, your best bet would be to create a pvt post for your code or ask a TA for help. """, meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Project Path 2 part 3', 'timestamp': '2023-04-28T03:33:59Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 129}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I was wondering if this was a valid analysis method to follow, since it wasn&#39;t discussed in class and is a bit rudimentary for path 2 problem 1.</p><p></p><p dir='ltr'>It follows that the best way to determine the answer is to find the two bridges with the most similar traffic patterns and only apply a sensor to one of these two in order to approximate the overall traffic.</p><p><b> </b></p><p dir='ltr'>To do this, we can first create bridge pairs. For simplicity, Brooklyn Bridge will be labeled as bridge 1, Manhattan Bridge will be labeled as bridge 2, Williamsburg Bridge will be labeled as bridge 3, and Queensboro Bridge will be labeled as bridge 4. These pairs are listed below:</p><p><b> </b></p><ul><li dir='ltr'><p dir='ltr'>Bridges 1 and 2</p></li><li dir='ltr'><p dir='ltr'>Bridges 1 and 3</p></li><li dir='ltr'><p dir='ltr'>Bridges 1 and 4</p></li><li dir='ltr'><p dir='ltr'>Bridges 2 and 3</p></li><li dir='ltr'><p dir='ltr'>Bridges 2 and 4</p></li><li dir='ltr'><p dir='ltr'>Bridges 3 and 4</p></li></ul><p><b> </b></p><p dir='ltr'>For each bridge pair, we can calculate the difference in bike traffic for each day, and compute the average difference in bike traffic by summing the differences and dividing by the total number of data points. The pair of bridges with the lowest average difference can be considered as being the most similar, and the bridge with the greater average traffic will be fitted with a sensor, along with the two bridges that were not included in the pair.</p> Answer: That looks like a valid approach, seems like you are using MSE to evaluate the models, maybe try normalizing the data first. Just make sure to explain your method reasoning and findings in your report clearly.""", meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Valid Analysis Method', 'timestamp': '2023-04-28T01:30:12Z', 'user': 'ktnb6iilrfbcn', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 12}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Why would $$\mu_{1}$$ change more than $$\mu_{2}$$?</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fksi8k0dd7bh6fe%2F00137a8a0e55dddaf6e30b08f6497d68e0aa5b31c31d9f2bf8f4a6eac89f8732%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' width='767' height='267' /></p> Answer: <p>Because 9.2 belongs to cluster 1 and thus change cluster 1&#39;s mean</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5b8oexj1jg%2F1299edafc8a265cdda0806717994cfb8e3a8ae8ab5b172e78c8a52b3ffad2095%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p><p>Since mean is updated by multiplying gamma and x, we know that gamma for cluster two, which is the P(G2|x) calculated from part c, is 0, x wouldn&#39;t even affect cluster 2&#39;s mean.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'S2022 Exam 3- Q3d', 'timestamp': '2023-04-27T23:44:15Z', 'user': 'ksi8k0dd7bh6fe', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 105}),
