	Document(content="""Question: <p>The github for the formal project asks us to use a format with 4 sections like this, with one section just about the authors and path and the others delving into the actual data:</p><p>&#34;</p><ul dir='auto'><li>A section with the names of the team members (maximum of two), your Purdue username(s), and the path (1 or 2 or 3) you have taken.</li><li>A section describing the dataset you are working with.</li><li>A section describing the analyses you chose to use for each analysis question (with a paragraph or two justifying why you chose that analysis and what you expect the analysis to tell you).</li><li>A section (or more) describing the results of each analysis, and what your answers to the questions are based on your results. Visual aids are helpful here, if necessary to back up your conclusions. Note that it is OK if you do not get &#34;positive&#34; answers from your analysis, but you must explain why that might be</li></ul><p>However, these do not line up one-to-one with the PDF on gradescope, which tells us to include 4 sections titled Dataset Description, Method, Results, and Analysis. Which of these formats should we use? If we should use the gradescope PDF format, how should we specifically break up the information between &#34;Results&#34; and &#34;Analysis&#34;?</p> Answer: You can separate results and analysis into two sections if desired.  Generally, following what is in the Readme should cover any structural requirements.""", meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Mini Project Format', 'timestamp': '2023-04-27T01:00:01Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 134}),
