	Document(content="""Question: Are the questions to be answered in Path 2 independent? For example, Q1 says we only have the budget to install sensors on 3 of the 4 bridges, so should we only use the data from the 3/4 bridges that we picked? Or should we use the total data from all 4 bridges?  Answer: The questions are independent of each other - you can use the data from all the 4 bridges to answer other questions.""", meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Path 2 Independent Questions?', 'timestamp': '2023-04-25T19:20:11Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 148}),
	Document(content="""Question: Why do we evaluate our models based on the entire dataset instead of just the testing data for steps 3-6 (specifically step 5), but then when we poison the data we are now evaluating it based on just the testing data? Is this how the README was meant to be interpreted? If so, I don&#39;t understand why we would even bother evaluating the prediction accuracy on the entire dataset in the first place and not just the testing data. What is even the point of making us evaluate the entire dataset when we have trained the models on 60% of the set, it seems like it would make much more sense to just predict and evaluate on the testing data which the model has not seen.  Answer: According to step 3 of the readme:<br /><br />Get the predicted values of the model with the <strong>Test data, <br /><br /></strong>The test data is not poisoned. However, the data that is used to train the model is. What we want to do and observe is to see how the models do when they are trained on poisoned data and then evaluated on the same test data that was used in previous tests. Then you can draw conclusions on how the models responded with this added noise during the training process. """, meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Mini Project path 3 confusion', 'timestamp': '2023-04-25T19:19:05Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 124}),
