	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fksi8jx1mt7c69i%2F502ff3cfea8774d25c8227dc41faf7c4b4206801201a4adda8b9e800455883cb%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p><p></p><p>the line for part 1 gives me this error: TypeError: dataset_searcher() missing 2 required positional arguments: &#39;images&#39; and &#39;labels&#39;. Are there any arguments that are missing or do we have to add them ourselves?</p> Answer: You have to put images and labels as additional arguments into the function. """, meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Possibly missing info for path3', 'timestamp': '2023-04-22T23:38:13Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 120}),
	Document(content="""Question: I&#39;m a bit confused about how the dataset_searcher() function works. Is the output a list that have a corresponding image to the number list and the label be the same as the number list but in np array form? Also the input of the dataset_searcher() in later code is a class_number, how would the parameters of it be 3 parts? Answer: The dataset searcher goes through a list of numbers like 2,0,8,7,5 and then finds an image (it can be as simple as just finding the first image) whose label corresponds with the number 2 (or 0 or 8, etc.). Then you will return both the images and their corresponding labels (hint, the corresponding labels should match the input argument to the function)""", meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Project path 3 questions about dataset_searcher() input and outputs', 'timestamp': '2023-04-22T21:52:34Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 14}),
