	Document(content="""Question: <p>I am working in the final project and chose path 2 (the one with the bikes). For the third problem, I decided to use clustering and naive bayes. These are my results.</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fl6maptmggzy7op%2F4612146809d0ab07fd29735989538ae52912697b2bf41fe72d9e733e51c7d4c3%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p><p></p><p>My AUROC scores are higher than my accuracy scores. Would this be sufficient to use in the project report? I am not sure if this is reasonable. I was thinking that I could compare the different methods and state that Naive Bayes works the best. Does these results look reasonable? I have more confusion matricies, but I commented them out for this picture. Thank you</p> Answer: <p>Your methods and results look reasonable to me - as for the conclusions you can draw - you can think about the original question - <strong>can</strong> you predict the day from the number of cyclists? In your project report, you can document your usage of these methods as well as the results that you have obtained along with the accuracy of these methods.</p><p>While you can state that the Naive Bayes classifier works the best, it is also important to ask yourself - is an accuracy of 20.9% sufficient to predict the day from the number of cyclists? If you think that is a reasonable accuracy, you can justify why you can use the Naive Bayes method to predict days from cyclists. If that is an accuracy you think is not reasonable, you can also say that you cannot predict what day it is just from the number of cyclists alone (with justification, of course!).</p>""", meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Final Project Path 2', 'timestamp': '2023-04-21T14:53:11Z', 'user': 'l6maptmggzy7op', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 12}),
