	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fk81v37lankw24g%2Ffb59626856cc284b50c02e909c95a9d0103088d339e5d69f49ca6277cc25522a%2FScreenshot_2023-04-20_at_0.33.55.png' alt='Screenshot_2023-04-20_at_0.33.55.pngNaN' width='1031' height='533' /></p><p></p><p>I think I&#39;m getting the right numbers as a result. But I&#39;m not getting the matrix as [[] [] [] ] but as [[] , [] , [] , []].</p><p>Would this be a problem?</p><p>Also, after printing until the 5-neighbors result, the processing time is really long, about 25 seconds. It is fast until the 5-neighbors result but takes 25 seconds more to print the rest. Is there a way to reduce the time or will the time not affect the grade?</p> Answer: The time won’t affect the grade but the formatting of the confusion matrix will. It should look like the README.<div>To add to this - it seems like your confusion matrix is a list of lists and not a numpy matrix - you should convert your confusion matrix to be a numpy array by using np.array().</div>""", meta={'folders': ['hw10'], 'title': 'confusion matrix format and time taken to print', 'timestamp': '2023-04-20T04:37:27Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw10', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 13}),
	Document(content="""Question: I am currently sitting at a 77/90 which equates to around an 85%. Does this mean I am getting around a B in the class? Answer: <p>While our policy is not to release the exact cutoffs for different letter grades, we can make the following worst-case guarantees on the mapping from your final number grade (after weighting the assignments, exams, and project) to letter grade:</p><p>A-range: &gt;90</p><p>B-range: &gt;80</p><p>C-range: &gt;70</p><p>D-range: &gt;60</p><p>Note that these are worst case, i.e., your actual letter grade will be greater than or equal to that given by these ranges. Different cutoffs might be used to benefit you depending on the grade distribution and other various factors. Hope this helps!</p>""", meta={'folders': ['logistics'], 'title': 'Python Grades', 'timestamp': '2023-04-19T22:46:30Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['logistics', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 15}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Hi, I need a partner for the project, if anyone wants to not work alone email me. bgolko@purdue.edu</p><p></p> Answer: You can also use @5 to search for teammates!""", meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Need partner for project', 'timestamp': '2023-04-19T21:25:05Z', 'user': 'ktnb6bov5ub71o', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 155}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I have started writing the code for the mini project and ran into some conceptual problems, specifically for question 1 and 2 of path 2.</p><p></p><p>For question 1, I had thought to approach it by preforming linear regression for each bridge data with the total number of cyclists as the target value and then preforming hypothesis testing on the coefficient associated for each bridge in their respective model and the bridge with the lowest P value would be the one that should not receive a sensor. However the z values that I am getting are very high which leads to a p value of 0 for all the bridges so I think i implementing something wrong. This is my code below.</p><p></p><pre>X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.1, shuffle=False)regr = Ridge(fit_intercept=True,alpha=0)regr.fit(X_train,y_train)coef = regr.coef_[0][0]pred = regr.predict(X_test)r2 = r2_score(y_test,pred).round(4)standard_error = calc_std_error(X_train,y_train,regr)z_score = coef / (standard_error)p_value = 2*norm.cdf(-abs(z_score))p_values.append(p_value)def calc_std_error(X,y,model):    N = len(X)    mean = np.mean(X)        pred = np.array(model.predict(X))    pred = np.reshape(pred,(1,N))[0]    y = np.reshape(y,(1,N))[0]    X = np.reshape(X,(1,N))[0]    numerator = 0    for i in range(N):        numerator &#43;= (pred[i] - y[i])**2    numerator /= (N-2)    numerator = numerator ** 0.5    denominator = 0    for i in range(N):        denominator &#43;= (X[i] - mean)**2    denominator = denominator ** 0.5    std_error = numerator /denominator    return std_error</pre><p></p><p>I have implemented the hypothesis testing and standard error formula based on the ones given in the slides. I also thought that another way to approach this is to just get the r^2 value, based on the test data, for each bridge model and the lowest one would be the one to not get a sensor but I do not know if that is accepatable or not.</p><p></p><p>For question 2 I simply did lasso  ridge regression based on the specified features with the target features at varying lambda and found the lamda model with the smallest test mse and called it the best model. What I discovered however is the smaller the lambda I gave to the range of the lamda, the lowest one always was chosen as the best lambda which doesn&#39;t make sense as small lamda indicate over fitting. So is it plausible that no matter how small a lambda I input that it repeatedly gets lower and lower test mse?</p> Answer: hm that is a good find and a good point. To determine which bridges to install sensors on, I would recommend taking a more simple approach such as knowing sensors should be installed on those with more traffic, so possibly normalizing the data and calculating according to MSE. For part two I would recommend ignoring the extreme cases and trying to linear or ridge regression to find any sort of relationship. Remember there is a lot of room for error, so make sure to just include these explanations in your final project report.""", meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Path 2 question 1 and 2 Inquiry', 'timestamp': '2023-04-19T19:26:04Z', 'user': 'kz5ooutiquc22c', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 14}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I visited office hours and the TA advised me to make a private piazza post, as we could not solve the issue.</p><p></p><p>I am working on Project Path 2 with a partner and we both have an issue with line 81 in the csv file while working on part 2. Here is our code block for part 2.</p><p></p><p>The error is in line 38: Invalid Literal for int() with base 10: &#34;18,096&#34;</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb7jjapv36vi%2F8ace2e1c13a67ed94cbb103a8e2e6bde5cc6a843fc0bb2e9bc3073a88f527830%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p> Answer: This seems to be caused by the presence of commas for some numbers in the CSV file. To replace/remove the commas, I would suggest you look at the top answer in this link - https://stackoverflow.com/questions/56947333/how-to-remove-commas-from-all-the-column-in-pandas-at-once<div><br /></div><div>To remove it for a particular column (let&#39;s say Total), you have to do:</div><div>df[&#39;Total&#39;] = df[&#39;Total&#39;].replace(&#39;,&#39;,&#39;&#39;, regex=True)</div><div><br /></div><div>This replaces all instances of a comma in the Total column with an empty string</div><div><br /></div>""", meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Issue with one specific line in csv file', 'timestamp': '2023-04-19T19:25:53Z', 'user': 'ktnb7jjapv36vi', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 12}),
