	Document(content="""Question: <p>Are y_true and y_pred not lists of ints in the confusion matrix function? I am trying to use the values in the lists as indices but I get the following error:<br /><br />IndexError: only integers, slices (`:`), ellipsis (`...`), numpy.newaxis (`None`) and integer or boolean arrays are valid indices</p><p></p><p>The function works exactly as intended when I test it separately by passing in a list of ints, where each int represents the class number.</p><p></p><p>What exactly is stored in y_true and y_pred?</p> Answer: We won&#39;t be able to make any comments unless we see your code.""", meta={'folders': ['hw10'], 'title': 'y_true and y_pred for confusion matrix', 'timestamp': '2023-04-15T20:48:51Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw10', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 155}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>How should I get started on confusion matrix? Can anyone suggest?</p><p>Thanks,</p> Answer: <md>The confusion matrix basically shows the number of correct versus 'confused' guesses made by your model. The matrix `M` will have a row for each true class label and a column for each predicted class label, with each cell representing the number of samples that were predicted as a certain class and actually belong to a certain class.For example, if `y_pred` is `[1, 0, 1, 2]`, y_true is `[0, 1, 1, 2]`, and `num_class` is 3, then the resulting confusion matrix `M will be:``` [[0., 1., 0.],  [1., 1., 0.],  [0., 0., 1.]]```Interpreting this, the cell in the first row and second column represents the number of samples that were predicted as class 1 (column) when they actually belong to class 0 (row), which is 1.EDIT: You may need to transpose the resulting matrix to match the README.</md>""", meta={'folders': ['hw10'], 'title': 'Confusion matrix', 'timestamp': '2023-04-15T17:35:22Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw10', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 166}),
