	Document(content="""Question: <p>I am getting the correct values for the clusters but before that 5 empty lists are printed as follows </p><pre>[][][][][]Cluster: 4 points and center = [0.075, 2.8]   [-0.5  3. ]   [0.3 4.5]   [0.5 2.5]   [0.  1.2]Cluster: 3 points and center = [9.666666666666666, -4.166666666666667]   [ 8. -3.]   [10. -5.]   [11.  -4.5]</pre><p>Is this ok to submit with or do I have an error in my code?</p> Answer: <md>I think for grading purposes you’ll want to fix this. The `main` function should only print the cluster values, so you probably want to see if you have any residual print statements anywhere.</md>""", meta={'folders': ['hw9'], 'title': 'Empty Lists Being Printed When Running kmeans.py', 'timestamp': '2023-04-12T02:41:46Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw9', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 121}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I started planning how I am going to answer the questions proposed for path 2 of the project and I have a methodology to obtain the answer of each question. However, before I start coding and implementing the solution, I wanted to make sure that my plan makes sense.  </p><p></p><p>So for the first question, </p><ul dir='auto'><li>You want to install sensors on the bridges to estimate overall traffic across all the bridges. But you only have enough budget to install sensors on three of the four bridges. Which bridges should you install the sensors on to get the best prediction of overall traffic?</li></ul><p>I understood the question to imply that they want the best 3 bridges that would offer the most reliable data or otherwise the data that is closest to the population parameters. So I thought that hypothesis testing would make sense and to see the z score of each bridge and compare them to each other. The bridges with the z score closest to the center of the gaussian distribution would be the most reliable. Assuming the population mean is the average of the mean of all bridges and same goes for the population variance.</p><p></p><p>For the second question,</p><ul><li>The city administration is cracking down on helmet laws, and wants to deploy police officers on days with high traffic to hand out citations. Can they use the next day&#39;s weather forecast(low/high temperature and precipitation) to predict the total number of bicyclists that day?</li></ul><p>I thought the best way to answer this question was to preform linear regression  using k-folds method with varying lambda and computing the average test MSE for each lambda and to see if the best model has a high enough r^2 score to be considered a valid estimator of the target value using the features mentioned.</p><p></p><p>Lastly for the third question,</p><ul dir='auto'><li>Can you use this data to predict what <em>day</em> (Monday to Sunday) is today based on the number of bicyclists on the bridges?</li></ul><p>Again in a similar method to question 2, after converting the days of the week to numerical integer representation, apply linear regression using kfolds method with varying lambda and see if the best models r^2 value is good enough to say that the target value, the day of the week, can be predicted with the features, the total number of cyclists on the bridge.</p><p></p><p>Does this all sound like it would work or is there some flaw in the way I am applying any of the principles?</p> Answer: <p>For the final project, there are no benchmark-correct solutions, but your implementation should be not trivial. You can actually analyze if your solutions work. For example, in the first question, do you think your assumption is too strong? If you do a hypo test, what is the Null hypo? For the second question, a regression could be a good starting point. However, you really have to start to work on it to see what kind of regression gives you a good result. For the third one, you can try regression, but is there any other way that seems more appropriate (you only have 7 days, right)?</p>""", meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Approach to Path 2', 'timestamp': '2023-04-10T22:51:44Z', 'user': 'kz5ooutiquc22c', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 17}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I am confused on how we can have a final project due during dead week (&#34;quiet week&#34;) and have a final exam during finals week? I thought they changed it so it was one or the other? And that if you have a final exam you cannot have work due during dead week? </p> Answer: <p>I&#39;d guess the alternative was likely cutting a week off how long you have to work on the final project and making it due the 21st or 23rd. If I were you I would just treat it as if it was due the 21st and then have dead week to work if you don&#39;t get it done. I&#39;ve also never heard of this rule you are talking about and the attached rule is the closest I could find with no stipulation on things/projects assigned <em>before</em> dead week.</p><p></p><ol start='4'><li>The final examination period is intended for the end-of-semester examination. No examination or quiz may be given during the week (three days in summer session) preceding the final examination period of the semester (examinations for laboratory, intensive, or minicourses excluded). It will be the responsibility of the department head or, where appropriate, the school head to ensure that none of the departmental or school faculty use the week (three days in summer session) preceding the final examination period to administer an examination.</li></ol>""", meta={'folders': ['logistics'], 'title': 'Final Project &amp; Final Exam', 'timestamp': '2023-04-10T18:01:48Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['logistics', 'student'], 'likes': 6, 'views': 190}),
