	Document(content="""Question: Why z score for 96% two side confidence interval is 2.05 not 1.75? Answer: <p>The area of both the sides is 0.04. The area of the right hand side is 0.02 (0.04/2). 1 - 0.02 = 0.98. The tscore corresponding to this area is 2.05. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 2022 exam 2 question 1a', 'timestamp': '2023-04-05T18:27:20Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 149}),
	Document(content="""Question: If in an regression question, lambda dropped with degree unchanged, would parameters for x increase?  Answer: <p>lambda just scales how important the parameters for x are. if lambda was 100, then a coefficient of 1 would be given a weight of 100 when computing the minimizing score thing. if lambda was 0, then any coefficient would be given a weight of 0, and only minimizing the model error would matter. so if lambda was lowered, and degree was unchanged, the parameters for x could be larger and retain the same minimized score. I show you the minimize thing below:</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb4n74agk61e%2F72d3900912018f123f6c1988e396f09f0e90582bd14e9ba9980020acdb3e08d7%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Relationship of lambda and beta', 'timestamp': '2023-04-05T16:47:16Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 133}),
