	Document(content="""Question: Could someone explain how to calculate that feature matrix X? Answer: <md>Also to answer the follow-up questions below:Linear regression fits a linear function of the input features. Polynomial regression fits a polynomial. To solve the polynomial regression problem, we create higher-order features so the problem can be solved through linear regression on those higher-order features. But you are still solving the polynomial regression problem.</md>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 exam2 question 5a', 'timestamp': '2023-04-05T13:50:09Z', 'user': 'k83r1oihjvd2uq', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 129}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p dir='ltr'>What is the meaning of this equation? Where do the values 1041/1032 come from and why would you divide by 2?</p><p dir='ltr'><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5gx345d2ba%2Fd3d894df805725c1c102ef63b9a201db99fd635486f38cbf592988d7963d57a0%2Fimage.jpeg' alt='image.jpegNaN' /></p> Answer: <p>2 is the number of data points you are comparing to the hypothesized value. The first data point is 1037 and the second one is 1030. The two values you are referencing come from earlier in the problem and are the &#34;hypothesized values&#34;.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 q5e', 'timestamp': '2023-04-05T13:39:22Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 105}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>How do you know to use the 10/100 and 20/400 values?</p> Answer: <p>The problems states to calculate the predicted stock price for the two testing observations, which are listed above in the table given for the problem. You would need to perform standard normalization for both data points to solve the problem from there.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 q5d', 'timestamp': '2023-04-05T13:34:48Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 97}),
	Document(content="""Question: Could someone explain why we should choose a and b ? Answer: <p>regularization reduces the magnitude of the coefficient towards 0 or keeps it the same. In this case, x1 being reduced to -1.5 or stays at 8, whichis bringing the coefficient closer to 0. The other 2 options increase its magnitude.  </p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022exam 2 question 3b', 'timestamp': '2023-04-05T13:08:30Z', 'user': 'k83r1oihjvd2uq', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 126}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Can someone please how to solve this?</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb4k37vlk5k5%2F17d88238dde872179412af25222ae8cbe27ee05866510d631fd767909bc19be0%2FScreen_Shot_2023-04-05_at_12.34.27_AM.png' width='384' height='175' alt='' /></p> Answer: <md>ok</md>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Exam 2 Spring 2022, Question 5b', 'timestamp': '2023-04-05T04:35:45Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 114}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb60yugxr5ja%2Ff7f7b428f669269999b118bf2b9ba82a9d164bd0983efc2a5ebc1ff225cbdbe6%2FScreen_Shot_2023-04-05_at_12.34.26_AM.png' alt='Screen_Shot_2023-04-05_at_12.34.26_AM.pngNaN' /></p><p>Why does 1000T2 work, and not robot0B9?</p> Answer: the * implies that it needs to be a lowercase letter 0 or more times (therefore optional). The very last part of the expression says that you need to have a digit between 0 and 8, so 9 would  fail. """, meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'F22 Q2a', 'timestamp': '2023-04-05T04:35:08Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 108}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb60yugxr5ja%2F0de04611f5fde8d5b7d212ee6e8cf93d25673a66bb7d9e2ad729e899c1ba89bd%2FScreen_Shot_2023-04-05_at_12.21.27_AM.png' alt='Screen_Shot_2023-04-05_at_12.21.27_AM.pngNaN' /></p><p>Why is it document A, if document A and D have the same frequency of learning? Moreover, if we are looking for the highest term frequency score, why is not document B?</p> Answer: <p>Term frequency is frequency of term divided by all terms in that document. for B this is 5/25 = 0.2, for A this is 2/4 = 0.5, for D this is 2/26. A is a landslide winner.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'S22 Q4d', 'timestamp': '2023-04-05T04:22:07Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 96}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>could someone explain how to result in this matrix? where does the -2,1,6 come from?<img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5gx345d2ba%2Fafd0fa26eecfdeb9ae316725a05475d69bc55786c4b86c53fdaf32c27373f25b%2FScreen_Shot_2023-04-04_at_11.09.29_PM.png' alt='Screen_Shot_2023-04-04_at_11.09.29_PM.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <p>that first matrix is X transposed. the second matrix is the normalized feature matrix X you shoulda found in a previous part. the [-2 1 6] went from the first column to the first row after X was transposed. second column became second row, third column became third row.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'spring 2022 exam 2 q5c', 'timestamp': '2023-04-05T03:10:40Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 102}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>xT is just the flip of the original matrix?</p> Answer: <p>the transpose of that matrix yes, thinking of it as flip is okay too.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'fall 2022 q2', 'timestamp': '2023-04-05T02:43:11Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 107}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fjzhjvtza66q373%2Fac0261a2c4a8b1fd4e86d82e9ecc4c8d0ad263502e99773e8c3e86b544fc5554%2FScreen_Shot_2023-04-04_at_10.27.03_PM.png' width='1224' height='1646' alt='' /></p><p></p><p>Can anyone explain these questions and why they are the case? I think I am a bit confused in confidential interval</p><p>Also I could not really find information in the lecture note.</p> Answer: <p>A confidence interval is a range around a sample statistic that gives you the values of the population parameter for which the sample statistic would not be surprising. Think of it as doing the opposite of hypothesis testing. 1 - C gives you the p-value. You use the p-value to calculate the z-score and you use the z-score to formulate lower and upper bounds of the confidence interval.</p><p></p><p>It is just saying that if you did hypothesis testing assuming one of the values inside the confidence interval as the population parameter, you would get a p-value that would be greater than or equal to 1 - C. It doesn&#39;t really tell you a lot in my opinion.</p><p></p><p>For the second question, if you decrease the percentage, you would increase the p - value, which would decrease the z-score, which would result in a narrower confidence interval.  </p><p></p><p>For the third question, the same thing as the second question but they also change the n and sigma. So, in that case, you need to know by how much do n and sigma change to know how the c.i. range changes. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 Q1b', 'timestamp': '2023-04-05T02:29:25Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 99}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>What does each component of the equation represent? how do you then apply it to the matrix?<img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5gx345d2ba%2Fb127bab6c291cdf41581db77ba9f0322e7e6eeb7f380b591a252cac00b69b538%2FScreen_Shot_2023-04-04_at_10.19.01_PM.png' alt='Screen_Shot_2023-04-04_at_10.19.01_PM.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <p>Xm represents the mth column of the feature matrix</p><p><span style='text-decoration:underline'>Xm</span> represents the mean of the mth column of the feature matrix.</p><p>Sm represents the standard deviation of the mth column of the feature matrix. </p><p></p><p>In this question, they tell you all the values. All you have to do is subtract the mean of the column from every column and divide the result by the column standard deviation. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'spring 2022 exam 2 q5b', 'timestamp': '2023-04-05T02:19:54Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 83}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Can someone explain how to solve this question? How were the values in the matrix determined?<img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5gx345d2ba%2Fa460e3d22be75ce8958d643d08d81a690e3977b80fc678b026bf3d97fa401705%2FScreen_Shot_2023-04-04_at_9.42.00_PM.png' alt='Screen_Shot_2023-04-04_at_9.42.00_PM.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: Because this is the feature matrix X - The first column is xi^2. The second column is xi. The third column is the intercept. So for example, the first row is as follows: x1^2 = 100, x1 = 10, b = 1.""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'spring 2022 exam 2 q5b', 'timestamp': '2023-04-05T01:42:45Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 88}),
