	Document(content="""Question: Will we be expected to know any z-score values?<div><br /></div><div>For example, is there the possibility we are asked to determine a 90% confidence interval with only the sample size, mean, and s.d. And we must estimate the z-score?</div> Answer: <p>If there is a question about z-scores, unless it is trivial such as the 3 sigma rule as was asked in previous exams, you will be given a table to compute z-scores from. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Exam 2: z-score', 'timestamp': '2023-04-05T00:40:03Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 109}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>For the avgDistance function in the first part of the homework, I am trying th find the distance between the center point and the points from self.points, but I only have the coordinates for the center and the self.points is stored in a point type. I was trying to use the formula given in the first part of the homework, but I cannot do the equation with iterations because of the point types. I cannot figure out how to convert these points to a list. Do you know how I would approach this problem? Thank you</p> Answer: <p>If you look at the definition of the Point class, you would find the coordinate of a Point object as its attributes (properties). Also, you may be able to find out an available, useful method (I mean a function that is an &#34;attribute&#34; of a class) of the class objects, which can be used to solve this question easily.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw9'], 'title': 'HW9 Question Cluster', 'timestamp': '2023-04-05T00:17:29Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw9', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 141}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>If we change choice (b) to &#34;We are 80% confident that the population mean is contained in the calculated confidence interval&#34;, will it be correct?</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5b8oexj1jg%2F2b0e65623c274a28fce9cc0d93412d149e1735dc272b833b9f1e4bb2fcf452d9%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <p>&#34;80% confident&#34; is not a well-defined statement. You have to specify what that means in the probability theory language as is done in the question. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'confidence interval interpretation', 'timestamp': '2023-04-05T00:09:26Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 95}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I am confused why are we assigning self.exam1, self.exam2, self.final = 0. Can anyone explain?</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb6igyqfbch%2Fcdc018b91c50eed5f6ff5001c1f9036e2cd2a0b296f337c8474c47615b15adbf%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p> Answer: <p>The question clarifies that none of the external code should be instantiating variables in the object, which means you need to define these variables inside the __init__ function before they&#39;re modified. Because we see only 1 value being passed into __init__ we know that we don&#39;t have any values to initialize the score variables to, so 0 is a standard choice for a default value.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 exam Q6', 'timestamp': '2023-04-05T00:01:32Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 103}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb3vlkh772ks%2F06e71bcac4163ba53f30ffa97278f5760aac33384765fb62b7658c57f4218215%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p><p>Why isn&#39;t b a correct answer for this question? Even plugging it in to an online regex simulator it matches all of the given strings.</p> Answer: <p>I believe the key word is &#34;match&#34; and is implying that it would find a match for the entire string. b does not have a match for the entire string, just the first word, because it has nothing to match the empty space character</p><p></p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 Q2b', 'timestamp': '2023-04-04T23:19:43Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 96}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>The 4 regexes, regression, ngrams, and objects power points are a good coverage of the exam content correct?</p> Answer: <p>Yes, in addition to this, the relevant slides about confidence intervals and t-distribution and t-tests should provide you with sufficient coverage of the exam content. You can also use the previous semesters&#39; examinations. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Clarification on powerpoint slides', 'timestamp': '2023-04-04T20:25:19Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 98}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Do both members in a group need to fill out the google form for the mini project?</p> Answer: <p>One of you (the team lead who will also push the code and submit the writeup) needs to fill out the Google form.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'final project groups', 'timestamp': '2023-04-04T19:59:54Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 142}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>This is the formula for computing confidence interval for z-test.</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5b8oexj1jg%2Fc7744c69223e9fe8cf767a6c30a354ab7060763d89254f4e90eefdffa1902183%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p><p>If instead we use a t-test, would I just simply replace z-score with t-score and $$\sigma$$ with s where s is the sample std?</p> Answer: Yea""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 't-test confidence interval', 'timestamp': '2023-04-04T19:13:04Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 104}),
	Document(content="""Question: This questions asks “assume we require that a3&gt;a2&gt;a1&gt;a0, which dataset would this polynomial fit best?” <div><br /></div><div>Why is the answer Dataset 3. I assume because this dataset takes the best fit shape of a third degree polynomial, but I’d like to understand this problem deeper. </div><div><br /></div><div>If for example they said “assume we require a2&gt;a3&gt;a1&gt;a0” would the best fit data set be one that matches a second degree polynomial?</div> Answer: If a3&gt;a2&gt;a1&gt;a0, that means the cubic coefficient will be greatest, so you would look for a dataset that appears most cubic. <div><br /></div><div>Now, if we knew a3&lt;a2&lt;.1, and that a1&gt;a0&gt;100, we’d probably have a good idea we are looking for a linear dataset, because the cubic/quadratic coefficients are so much lower. </div><div><br /></div><div>If we were told a2&gt;a3&gt;a1&gt;a0, we wouldn’t know quite as much, because higher degree coefficients naturally have more impact — 2x^3 &#43; 3x^2 will look somewhat cubic. Here, we’d be looking for a dataset that is not linear or uniform, and is probably kind of cubic.</div>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 2022 Exam 2 Q4A', 'timestamp': '2023-04-04T18:42:06Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 115}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I understand that during cross validation, we fit the model k times if there are k-fold. But at the end, which model do we choose? The one with the lowest test MSE? The slides didn&#39;t specifically point which one we should pick.</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5b8oexj1jg%2F0cf399da41c946f2ea3aa47114d4492d0fce839c10dea796ed725bd43ecb126c%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <p>The purpose of cross-validation is not to pick one model out of the k models; it is to test how good the method you are using is. The performance of the model from cross validation will be the average MSE of the k different models that you have trained in the cross validation process. Once the validation process is done, there is no need for any of these k models because the purpose of cross validation is to get an idea of how good a particular method is.  <br />Here&#39;s an example - let&#39;s say you have two different methods you are using to solve a problem - let&#39;s say one is a linear regression model and the other is a neural network. One of the ways you can do to determine which method is better is you can do a k-fold cross validation of both the linear regression model and the neural network method. Whichever method yields a lower average MSE is the one that we can call a beter method. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Which model to choose using cross validation?', 'timestamp': '2023-04-04T18:12:07Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 98}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Question 4 asks about k-fold cross-validation and LOO cross-validation. Do you know where I can find these on the lecture slides? Will this be on the exam this semester?</p> Answer: <p>They should be in the regression slides/notes. It would be fair game for this exam since this topic is covered under regression. Because the exam is open notes I would recommend you print out the lecture slides or create a study guide you can quickly peak at when asked questions like these. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 2022 Exam 2 Question 4', 'timestamp': '2023-04-04T17:01:23Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 113}),
	Document(content="""Question: How could MSE equal to 7? According to equations for MSE = 1/2(Y hat-y)^2, I think It equals to 21/2. Could someone please help me for how to solve that problem? Answer: MSE = $$\frac{1}{n} \sum_1^n (\hat{y}-y)^2$$ so its 21/n where n is 3. So its 21/3""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'For fall2022 exam2 question 3 partB', 'timestamp': '2023-04-04T15:00:25Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 116}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb57ll3pzvw%2F72edf06b549fd9db4670d227511ae2277403486f7a6f6ec4e4b92bc2f15b0321%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' width='393' height='228' /></p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb57ll3pzvw%2F1d2d9ba243e547227c0a1488e0bc63bdeafa9c15d1693caf20bf4969dbf565da%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' width='638' height='456' /></p><p></p><p>For this question, why do we have to initialize a add function? I know that the two calculation functions are required per the description as well as the self initialization function, but I&#39;m not sure why add is required since it doesn&#39;t seem to be used for anything.</p> Answer: <p>The add function is used in the line grade_total = i &#43; grade_total. Notice that i is a Student object, so you need to define what&#39;s added when you&#39;re doing this computation. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 Exam 2 Question 6', 'timestamp': '2023-04-04T04:07:56Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 117}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Are we allowed to use different features like date for the second part where it says:</p><div><div>The city administration is cracking down on helmet laws, and wants to deploy police officers on days with high traffic to hand out citations.</div><div> Can they use the next day&#39;s weather forecast(low/high temperature and precipitation) to predict the total number of bicyclists that day?<br /><br />Are we only allowed to use those 4 columns: temp low, temp high, precipitation, total,</div></div> Answer: <p>You could use those four given columns to answer the question and then add onto your explanation using your findings from testing your model with different features.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Path 2 part 2 available features', 'timestamp': '2023-04-04T03:28:57Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 137}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb57ll3pzvw%2F2f0a767ca17605aa0ef552085637fbb016f72161dee97cbdfac69306fa6a7af4%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' width='645' height='275' /></p><p>I understand why b is an answer because they have the same terms and the same signs. By that logic I&#39;m also able to rule out C and D because of the terms and signs. I&#39;m unsure on why A is applicable since the terms are different for the x1 term.</p> Answer: <p>The student&#39;s answer is a good thought to solve the problem. Let me raise one more question: why? The goal of Regularization is to avoid overfitting. If you have larger coefficients, you may expect the graph to go up and down, which is a phenomenon of overfitting.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 Exam 2 Question 3b', 'timestamp': '2023-04-04T02:31:01Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 103}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>How different should we expect this exam to be compared to the ones released on brightspace? I know that we can&#39;t get a concrete answer but knowing a baseline would be nice so we all can get a gauge of how confident we feel after going through the practice exams.</p> Answer: <div>This is not a question we can answer with much detail as I explained in my section as well. But just to make sure we are all on the same page, I think it is reasonable to expect some questions to be similar and some questions to be different.</div><div></div><div>In general, I would avoid using past exam performance to decide if I understood a concept, which is prone to overfitting, and instead carefully go over lectures. </div><div></div><div>In section 3, we discussed what one can use to verify a deep understanding of a concept. Some things I recommend:</div><div>- Can you teach/explain the concept with its details to your friend/classmates?</div><div>- Can you code it up without looking up the algorithms/syntax/functions?</div><div>- Can you solve homework/exam questions without resorting to any written notes or to solutions?</div><div>- Imagine you are the instructor. What question would you prepare to test students&#39; understanding of each topic? This is the hardest one but I strongly suggest trying this. You cannot come up with a novel question without deeply understanding a concept. Questions identical to past midterms with numbers changed obviously do not count.</div><div></div><div>Hope this helps!</div><div>- MK</div>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Exam 2 Difference compared to the Practice Exams', 'timestamp': '2023-04-04T01:23:19Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 121}),
	Document(content="""Note: <p>Just a reminder that if you have a scheduling conflict/approved absence from the exam, you need to get approval from your instructor to be able to take the makeup exam. <br /><br />After you have received approval, you can forward that approval to jtoberma@purdue.edu (myself) and he will coordinate your makeup exam. <br /><br /></p><p>Jason Toberman (GTA</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Exam 2 Make-up', 'timestamp': '2023-04-03T22:03:14Z', 'user': 'kskmxecspaq4i1', 'tags': ['exam', 'instructor-note'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 119}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Can someone explain why the third one is also a match? </p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb6lxjfnn105%2F095e60182a9a04467cf5fa0d289f57891d77a756a0d7f507be7495b26b0abeba%2FScreenshot_2023-04-03_at_2.09.31_PM.png' alt='Screenshot_2023-04-03_at_2.09.31_PM.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <md>The third regex actually won't match the first string as given. This is because `[\.edu]` matches '.', 'e', 'd', or 'u' individually, but not '.edu' as a whole. Either the answer key is wrong or the `[]` are a typo.However, assuming `[\.edu]` should actually be `(\.edu)`, the third regex works as follows:*   The first part of the email address contains one or more lowercase letters (`[a-z]+`).*   The second part of the email address may contain zero or more digits (`[0-9]*`).*   The third part of the email address contains one or more upper/lowercase letters or hyphens (`[a-zA-Z\-]+`).*   The fourth part of the email address may contain the digit 2 (the `?` means the 2 is optional).*   The fifth part of the email address contains the `@` symbol.*   The sixth part of the email address contains one or more letters (both lowercase and uppercase) followed by a period (.) and the string “edu”.All of the email addresses match these criteria.EDIT: The reason `[a-z]+` and `[a-zA-Z\-]+` BOTH match is due to the `+` operator being “lazy but docile,” meaning it will match as much as possible, but reduce the length of its match to allow a future operator to find a match. Therefore `[a-z]+` won’t match the entirety of “darthvader” by itself, it also allows `[a-zA-Z\-]+` to match the string.</md>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 2022 Q2B', 'timestamp': '2023-04-03T18:10:00Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 120}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>If we have methods that were not taught in class that we think would best first solving the different problems presented in the mini project, can we use them? Like using decision tree, gradient boosting, splitting criterion, correlation coefficient matrix, and such.</p> Answer: Yes Absolutely!<div>In that case you are also recommended to show the performance on the models taught in the class as baselines.</div>""", meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Approaches to solving with different models', 'timestamp': '2023-04-03T17:13:58Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 140}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Can anyone explain how p-value = 0.001? I thought it should be 0.003 (1-0.997).</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb6igyqfbch%2Fae31ea82f176f0a0baf2700d9419f87bd5275660d8df25cbecc2e7dcdf9a9642%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p> Answer: <md>The answer key is incorrect (Professor Ghasemi noted this in lecture). It should be 0.003.</md>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 2022 Q6 Part C', 'timestamp': '2023-04-03T14:40:52Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 111}),
	Document(content="""Note: <p>Hello Everyone!<br /><br />We have received reports from some of our team leads indicating that they are unable to add collaborators to their GitHub repositories. Upon investigating the issue, we discovered that the &#34;add collaborators&#34; option is unavailable in their account settings. Granting access to this feature would require admin privileges, which we are unable to provide.<br /><br /></p><p>We understand that collaboration is a crucial aspect of any project, and we sincerely apologize for any inconvenience this may have caused. However, please be aware that adding team members to the team leader&#39;s repository was always an optional step.<br /><br /></p><p>As a result, we encourage you to explore alternative methods for collaborating with your team members. Numerous tools are available, such as email, instant messaging, and file-sharing services, to facilitate collaboration. One suggestion would be to create a separate personal GitHub repository for the mini-project, allowing you to work collaboratively. At the end of the project, you can push all your code and reports to the original assignment repository.<br /><br /></p><p>Once again, we apologize for this inconvenience and appreciate your understanding.<br /><br />Best,<br />Gaurav</p>""", meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Issue with Adding Collaborators on GitHub', 'timestamp': '2023-04-03T03:42:03Z', 'user': 'kskmx82xa2s4ad', 'tags': ['instructor-note', 'project'], 'likes': 3, 'views': 159}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I am confused why Zc at 96% confidence interval is taken 2.05. Can anyone explain?</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb6igyqfbch%2F4d1f71c5dea7ede78b644320e4e821340196f21a1c0cf0bdcbe027e12463c4c3%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb6igyqfbch%2Fdcd0ec93ba50cfe73d5ea307479e659f73073bdf738b9e626dbfd12b4dca7d12%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p><p></p><p></p> Answer: <p></p><p></p><p>So you want a 96 percent confidence interval. There is 4% left and thus 2% left on each side because it is a two-tailed confidence interval. You are doing a two-tailed test so you choose 2.05 because it would leave 2% left on both sides.</p><p></p><p>So in short you want 96%, whats left? 4% is left. Divide by 2 because two sided = 2%, so look for the value that corresponds with 98% or .98</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 2022 Q1', 'timestamp': '2023-04-03T03:30:56Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 112}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>For (b) what equation do we use to normalize the matrix?</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fjzhjvtza66q373%2F08175843c5e4c1e244420324d6518136a30c8b842e783e67ba4c7a82627102e0%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p><p></p><p>For (d), why are we getting $$x_{4}$$ and $$x^{2}_{4}$$. I don&#39;t understand what we are doing to get $$\widehat{y}$$</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fjzhjvtza66q373%2Fd04f1edb1e6b5602ff54a7e5d35922f41ad57da3b906e5427dcba16a2b2c9ce0%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <p>For b, the green note is the exact equation you&#39;re applying for normalization. Just do this step for all terms in x_i and x^2_i, and you&#39;ll get the normalized matrix. For d, since we know y = a_1 * x^2_i &#43; a_2 * x_i &#43; b, and we get a1, a2, and b from beta after training dataset, so we need to find xi and x^2_i and apply them separately for finding y4 and y5. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'spring 2022 Q5', 'timestamp': '2023-04-03T02:57:15Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 99}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>How do we get &#34;good&#34; as a output from this code?</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fjzhjvtza66q373%2F4d2e97c257b3004f278e6107cb60864d1107bd2cd7aff8ffb50fef4c14175d04%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <p>See discussion below</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 2022 part c', 'timestamp': '2023-04-03T02:29:08Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 97}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I don&#39;t think you can add collaborators to the github repository since we do not exactly own it and it is private. The settings button does not exist on the repository for the miniproject so we cannot access the button to add. </p> Answer: <p>Thanks for letting us know about this issue. In that case, unfortunately, the team members would need to find out some other way to collaborate on their project.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Adding collaborators', 'timestamp': '2023-04-03T02:19:08Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 126}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5b8oexj1jg%2F5acebe29fac57c883983e7c2bb016adb00d5602736fbe52ea10a27be74c91a83%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' />For this question, I am just curious on why MSE train is greater than MSE test for all cases. Isn&#39;t the model trained on the training data? And since the model never see the testing data before, my inital thought is that MSE on testing data should be greater than training because the model is trained on the training data. But it isn&#39;t the case here.</p> Answer: <p>Interesting observation. The training and testing MSEs have no direct correlations, because the ways of sampling may be different. Of course, we expect the training data to have higher accuracy. However, if you have a sample bias, for example, you may have a test result with a lower MSE.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'MSE on training data and testing data', 'timestamp': '2023-04-03T02:02:58Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 83}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Can anyone explain what is happening here by using .sub?</p><p></p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fjzhjvtza66q373%2F07b9f63f7fb64dfab5cf406503882e23b3a9e5d89f7652b7c8ff344d38ae0fd1%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <p>The regex pattern is &#39;hello (\w*)&#39;. When you do p.sub(r&#39;goodbye \1&#39;, &#39;well hello ece&#39;). this is what happens:</p><p></p><ul><li>First, the match in the string we want to do substitution in is &#39;hello ece&#39;. Here, group 0 is &#39;hello ece&#39; while group 1 (corresponding to \w*) is &#39;ece&#39;.</li><li>Second, the substitution function substitutes the match in the string with &#39;goodbye \1&#39; (which in this case is &#39;goodbye ece&#39;.</li><li>Putting all of this together, the final output will be &#39;well goodbye ece&#39;.</li></ul><p>For the second example, p.sub(r&#39;\1 goodbye \1&#39;, &#39;well hello X&#39;), here is what happens: </p><ul><li>First, the match in the string we want to do substitution in is &#39;hello X&#39;. Here, group 0 is &#39;hello X&#39; while group 1 (corresponding to \w*) is &#39;X&#39;.</li><li>Second, the substitution function substitutes all the matches in the string with &#39;\1 goodbye \1&#39; (which in this case is &#39;X goodbye X&#39;.</li><li>Putting all of this together, the final output will be &#39;well X goodbye X&#39;.</li></ul><p></p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'how to use .sub', 'timestamp': '2023-04-03T01:36:04Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 92}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Is it possible to work with a student from another section for the mini project?</p> Answer: <p>@445 says;</p><blockquote><p>There are three possible paths to choose from, and you may work with one partner (from the same section) if you wish.</p></blockquote><p>So probably not.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Working with a student from another section', 'timestamp': '2023-04-02T22:52:51Z', 'user': 'ktnb839mwas1tt', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 140}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Can someone explain this regex substitution? </p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb6lxjfnn105%2Fc364c3f70fa752406f14cb3d2ce46c649d5f1cf5e2c1504014a49321dfd8b699%2FScreenshot_2023-04-02_at_4.53.56_PM.png' alt='Screenshot_2023-04-02_at_4.53.56_PM.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <p>the first group ([aeiou]&#43;) detects a or e or i or u 1 or more times, so it detects &#39;ea&#39;.</p><p>the second group ([^aeiou]&#43;) detects anything but aeiou 1 or more times, so it detects &#39;t&#39;.</p><p>Then, &#39;\2\1&#39; means replace whatever is detected with whatever is detected in group 2 followed by whatever is detected in group 1. Since &#39;t&#39; is detected in group 2 and &#39;ea&#39; is detected in group 1, The whole thing will be replaced with &#39;tea&#39;</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2020 Exam 2 Q2d', 'timestamp': '2023-04-02T20:54:41Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 103}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>What does the \. do? What happens if I remove the \ in front of the .?<img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb4k37vlk5k5%2F5030107cb43c92e431ed85445d2b314eaba704c81ba471c4a17fb1aee4c717e3%2FScreen_Shot_2023-03-29_at_8.56.43_PM.png' /></p> Answer: <p>For any characters with a regex functionality (e.g. &#43; * []), we need a \ to indicate it is a character.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 exam 2 Q2a', 'timestamp': '2023-04-02T20:48:24Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 90}),
	Document(content="""Question: <img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb6mjuvqb13k%2Fc490c7953e9195bedd7ec894fb91e0487bb6b32a7c46d8348be295ec57c9b19e%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' />How are these answers reached? Answer: <p>Regularization decreases the magnitudes of the coefficients </p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Sp22 Exam 2 Q3b', 'timestamp': '2023-04-02T20:46:53Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 93}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I am not sure now we are getting the equation below</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fjzhjvtza66q373%2Fad12182bd8b8d359db6a42e335dc38a150cfb56e708f6abea3ad15b9909d1ca6%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <p>First, you may think about the relation between $$\hat y$$ and $$\tilde y$$. By definition of normalization, $$\tilde y$$ = $$|\hat y - M|/S$$. How this affects a coefficient? How about an intercept? Remember that intercept is also a y value, so consider the offset M.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 2022 Q6 Part D', 'timestamp': '2023-04-02T20:46:48Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 94}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Can anyone explain this? I am having a hard time understanding how we get out the output of &#34;good by using re.compile(pat)&#34;</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fjzhjvtza66q373%2Ff3138ced9afe24f7439e056f4c964045d1b87f30bc352234da2c63b8a3025a22%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <p>Essentially you want to search the string for a pattern that matches the re.compile portion. In this case, it is looking for the phrase &#34;_____ is _______&#34;, where the second blank is the superpower group. There is only one instance that matches this in the string and so the superpower would be &#34;good&#34;. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 2022 Q2 part c', 'timestamp': '2023-04-02T19:05:15Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 91}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Why is it not $$X = \begin{bmatrix} 40\\ 20 \end{bmatrix}$$ ?</p><p>How did we get extra $$\begin{bmatrix} 1\\ 1 \end{bmatrix}$$ in the matrix?</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fjzhjvtza66q373%2F2f3cd0012e50280c90f034545db161ea72c67c2929c878dbcebd2f3aedf70b87%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <p>Essentially, you want a system such as $$ y = Ax$$, where y is a vector and A is a matrix or vector, depending on the dimension of x. Let&#39;s only look at one entry of this system, $$y_{i} = a_{ij} x_i + b_i$$. Looks familiar. However, we do not $$b$$ in this system. How can we achieve this? We put it in the matrix $$A$$. Rewrite this equation as $$y_{i} = a_{i1} x_{i1} + a_{i2}x_{i2}$$, where $$a_{i2}x_{i2} = b_i$$ and $$a_{i2} = b_i$$</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 2022 Q3A1', 'timestamp': '2023-04-02T19:02:00Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 106}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>What is the difference between testing and validation data? What are their different uses, and when do we use them?</p> Answer: <p>The validation set is part of the training set. When we do a train-test split, we can do another split on the training set called the training-validation split. The validation set is used to adjust the hyperparameters of a model like the ridge regression parameter lambda. You might argue that we can adjust the hyperparameters using the testing set. But, this would make the testing set as the training set because you are using it to train the model to perform better. So, that&#39;s why we have a validation set. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'testing vs validation data', 'timestamp': '2023-04-02T12:08:57Z', 'user': 'ksi8k0dd7bh6fe', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 77}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fksi8jx1mt7c69i%2F24b3bee791af62da2f121f6f9a80631d394d1902482455cc4a6d8f409af77038%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' width='494' height='237' /></p><p>In this question, why would the third regex be the right answer. Wouldn&#39;t [\.edu] mean that only one of either e, d, u, or &#39;.&#39; could be used? Thanks in advance.</p> Answer: <p>Notice that a match does not need to cover the entire string. If there is a substring matching the requested pattern, there will be a valid match.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'fall 2022  question 2 part B', 'timestamp': '2023-04-02T06:03:50Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 90}),
