	Document(content="""Question: <p>Will homework 9 or any part of it be assessed or prevalent to what&#39;s on exam 2?</p> Answer: <p>Homework 9 is about two topics: &#34;Object and Classes&#34; and &#34;Clustering.&#34; Clustering will not be assessed in Exam 2; however, objects and classes will be. So, looking at Problem 1 which has components related to objects and classes may be helpful for this exam.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw9'], 'title': 'Homework 9 Content on Exam 2', 'timestamp': '2023-04-01T19:46:27Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw9', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 121}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Why is the used Z-value in the answer key 1.28? Shouldn&#39;t it be 0.85 as the C.I. is 80%? 1.28 corresponds to a C.I. of 90%.</p> Answer: <p>It is because if you want an 80% confidence interval, you essentially want the middle 80% of the distribution. That means that there is 10% of the distribution left on each side. This is a two-tailed test so you would choose a z-value of 1.28, as that leaves 10% left on the right side of the distribution (as seen in the table), and logically that means a z-value of -1.28 would leave 10% on the left side of the distribution. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 Exam 2 Q1a', 'timestamp': '2023-04-01T18:48:08Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 107}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Hi, I am an exchange student and I am a bit lost about this kind of things. I have experienced some issues installing some libraries on my computer, is there somewhere someone can help me to fix it?</p> Answer: <p>The best way at this point, I&#39;ll say, is to try if you can log in to eceprog with your career account. As long as you can use eceprog, everything is installed on that. And you could use the Thinlinc web/client or SSH to access it.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['other'], 'title': 'Itap help', 'timestamp': '2023-04-01T17:58:49Z', 'user': 'lcrzmj6nzh1w6', 'tags': ['other', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 84}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I am just wondering how the homework will be graded. Will the graders look in detail at the code and award or take away credit for the code? For example, if I failed some outputs but my code was &#34;close&#34; to the answer, I might be awarded partial credit for that problem?</p> Answer: im wondering the same thing because my output 1 printed the regexed language alone not the filepath:  """, meta={'folders': ['hw8'], 'title': 'Homework grading question', 'timestamp': '2023-04-01T03:10:24Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw8', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 95}),
	Document(content="""Note: <p>Hello Everyone,</p><p>The final project has been released on GitHub Classroom and is due on April 30, 2023, 11:59 pm ET. This project is designed to put your knowledge of data analysis to use, where you will be given a dataset and asked to draw conclusions from it. You will need to understand what the data is showing you, design the analyses you need, justify those choices, draw conclusions from running the analyses, and explain why they do (or do not) make sense.<br /><br /></p><p>Mini Project: <a href='https://classroom.github.com/a/SM8Fi8N8' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>https://classroom.github.com/a/SM8Fi8N8</a><br /><br /></p><p>There are three possible paths to choose from, and you may work with one partner (from the same section) if you wish. Working with a partner is optional and will not impact how the project is graded. If you decide to work with a partner, please remember that only one of the two members, i.e., the team-lead, needs to submit the completed code and PDF report. To collaboratively work on this project, the team-lead could add the other member as a collaborator to his/her repository, however, that is completely optional.<br /><br /></p><p>Also, please make sure to fill out this form (<a href='https://forms.gle/ytT2u8eGukddJ9XA9' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>https://forms.gle/ytT2u8eGukddJ9XA9</a>) and follow the instructions given in the project description on GitHub Classroom.<br /><br />To look for teammates you could use the &#34;Search for Teammates!&#34; post on Piazza :<br /><a href='/class/lcj9rez4czg6zj/post/5' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>https://piazza.com/class/lcj9rez4czg6zj/post/5</a></p><p></p><div><div><div><p>In a week&#39;s time, you will have the Mini Project submission portal live on Gradescope.</p></div></div></div><p></p><p>If you have any questions or need further clarification, please feel free to come to office hours to brainstorm or use Piazza to discuss with your peers.<br /><br /></p><p>Best of luck with your final project!<br /><br /></p><p>Regards,<br />Gaurav Patel</p>""", meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Mini Project Released!', 'timestamp': '2023-04-01T02:38:14Z', 'user': 'kskmx82xa2s4ad', 'tags': ['instructor-note', 'pin', 'project'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 341}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I&#39;m not sure how but I checked everything before idf function and all of them are calculated right. But for the idf result I got slightly different result. I recalculated everything manually and couldn&#39;t find out how I got it wrong. In the 6th index I got -9.54ish instead of zero as the docword has 16&#43;2 on 6th index. Though in the testcase result in README it&#39;s 0.</p> Answer: <p>Hey! It&#39;s hard to comment on your bug unless we see your code.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw8'], 'title': 'HW8 Q2 different answer with the testcase', 'timestamp': '2023-04-01T02:25:01Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw8', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 12}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>For the result docword matrix, I&#39;m not quite sure how it works. For the second brackets in the matrix why are they strings even though I stored time of occurrence in there? Also I somehow need more clarification on the dimension of the np array. The docword matrix is a 2D matrix right? Then in the building tf matrix part why would we need the newaxis command?</p> Answer: <p>For the first question, you may initialize the matrix in a wrong way, e.g. using np.array() rather than np.zeors(). The doc matrix is 2 dimensional. For the newaxis, you have to understand what object is this index used for: (np.sum(docword,axis=1)[:,np.newaxis]). The sum of docword, a 2D matrix, is a 1D array. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw8'], 'title': 'HW8 Q2 bulid_doc_word_matrix result', 'timestamp': '2023-04-01T00:53:22Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw8', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 13}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Hi,</p><p>For building the doc word matrix, I&#39;m not sure if it&#39;s only asking us to build a matrix with a specific dimension but without any values in it or we should include the frequency of occurrence of the ngrams?</p> Answer: <p>It should include the ngrams that show up in the documents.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw8'], 'title': 'HW8 Q2 part 1 build_doc_word_matrix', 'timestamp': '2023-04-01T00:31:48Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw8', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 10}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Does the order matter in kmeans.py<br />For example if the expected output is:</p><p></p><pre>Cluster: 4 points and center = [0.075 2.8  ]   [0.3 4.5]   [0.  1.2]   [0.5 2.5]   [-0.5  3. ]Cluster: 3 points and center = [ 9.66666667 -4.16666667]   [ 8. -3.]   [10. -5.]   [11.  -4.5]</pre><p><br />and the output i am getting is:</p><pre>Cluster: 4 points and center = [0.075, 2.8]   [-0.5  3. ]   [0.5 2.5]   [0.  1.2]   [0.3 4.5]Cluster: 3 points and center = [9.666666666666666, -4.166666666666667]   [ 8. -3.]   [11.  -4.5]   [10. -5.]</pre><p>is it acceptable?<br /><br /><kbd>and the comma between center?</kbd></p> Answer: <p>No. &#34;Note, the order of the points in each cluster doesn&#39;t matter (neither does the order of clusters), all that&#39;s important is that each cluster contains the correct points.&#34;</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw9'], 'title': 'kmeans order', 'timestamp': '2023-03-31T23:34:19Z', 'user': 'k80ltc9fklk327', 'tags': ['hw9', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 135}),
