	Document(content="""Question: <p>I am confused on how to implement find_distinctive words. My general structure is to sort the tfidf values for each document. From there, I pull the largest values from the sorted index and retrieve the words at each of the indexes. However this is giving me outputs that do not match those provided in the example code. I think this may be due to duplicate tfidf values but I am unsure how to change my sorting method to match the given output. The rest of my code has been tested and works as intended.</p><pre>distinctive_words = {}    tfidf = build_tfidf_matrix(docword)    # find the smallest 4 values for each row    for row in range(docword.shape[0]):        tfidf_row = tfidf[row, :]        sorted_idx = numpy.argsort(tfidf_row)        sorted_idx = list(sorted_idx)  # convert to a list        num = len(ngramlist)        print(&#34;num value: &#34;, num)        word1 = ngramlist[sorted_idx.index(num - 1)]        word2 = ngramlist[sorted_idx.index(num - 2)]        word3 = ngramlist[sorted_idx.index(num - 3)]        # add the 4 values to the key in distinctive_words        key = doclist[row]        distinctive_words[key] = [word1, word2, word3]</pre> Answer: <p>Resolved: found the issue</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw8'], 'title': 'Stuck on find_distinctive_words', 'timestamp': '2023-03-29T19:10:50Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw8', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 13}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I am getting this output for find_distinctive_words:</p><p>{&#39;lecs\\1_vidText.txt&#39;: [&#39;econ&#39;, &#39;seco&#39;, &#39;pers&#39;], &#39;lecs\\2_vidText.txt&#39;: [&#39;uter&#39;, &#39;oint&#39;, &#39;oute&#39;]}</p><p>I do not understand what I am doing wrong since i am getting some of the correct values.  Can anyone help?  I have sorted my ngramlist in build_doc_word_matrix and as far as i can tell, all my outputs are correct for the previous steps.</p> Answer: <p>We can comment unless we see your code/approach. Please come to office hours to get this resolved.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw8'], 'title': 'hw 8_2 find_distinctive_words', 'timestamp': '2023-03-29T18:05:58Z', 'user': 'k8255378iju3qa', 'tags': ['hw8', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 162}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb576kzkcsp%2F9e992297053a512a6eb63eaa6eb8e2b8ac31f138851ec215029d4436d63f57c8%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' width='410' height='181' /></p><p></p><p>And when I try to update it shows:</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb576kzkcsp%2Fce7970098b8ca7eeeb906f3d0259859188edd92de0ffd9ff7b8dcf5c8c614520%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' width='454' height='151' /></p><p></p><p>And then when I run the bottom command to upgrade it shows the same error as above. </p><p></p><p>I have no idea where to start to resolve this and have been trying to figure out for a long while. </p> Answer: <p>Try pip install --user numpy --upgrade instead </p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'I keep getting numpy errors but it won&#39;t let me update', 'timestamp': '2023-03-29T16:30:07Z', 'user': 'ktnb576kzkcsp', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 11}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>For Part 2 in the build_word_doc matrix, what should the format of ngramlist be? Is it just a long list of all the ngrams that occur across all files or does the structure resemble something like:<br />ngramlist[file_num][all_ngrams_in_file]</p> Answer: <p>ngramlist should be a sorted list of all the ngrams that occur across all the files.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw8'], 'title': 'HW8 Part 2 Q.1 Clarification', 'timestamp': '2023-03-29T16:29:05Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw8', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 150}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>The idf array is supposed to be a 1D array, but the code given to us is attempting to access idf[0][0:10]. When I print idf[0:10], I get all the correct values.<br /><br />But since the code is trying to access the second dimension in a one dimensional array, Python throws an error. I&#39;m not sure how to fix this issue. Should we intentionally store the information in 2D format even though it&#39;s only 1D?<br /><br />So if the data was [1,2,3], we should do [[1,2,3]] instead?</p> Answer: <md>The IDF array is still a 1D numpy array, specifically a row vector. You don’t need to change that. Regarding their syntax… when you access `idf[0]`, you are retrieving the first (and only) row of the `idf` array, which is a 1D array. So, `idf[0][0:10]` accesses the single existing row, and then the first 10 elements of that row.Basically, you can define the array initially like `idf = np.zeros((1, number_of_columns))` to meet their specifications as a 1D row vector.</md>""", meta={'folders': ['hw8'], 'title': 'idf Array', 'timestamp': '2023-03-29T16:11:33Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw8', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 151}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb576kzkcsp%2F9934712c4da1eebcc4e40aa823840c936d03245f6f36c92419f65df74f120ba0%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' width='601' height='273' /></p><p>I dont know why, but VS code stopped letting me push. So then, I re-did the ssh key several times, still did not let me. Then, I deleted hw7 and tried to re clone, but it&#39;s just not letting me. I don&#39;t know how to resolve this. </p><p></p> Answer: <p>GitHub just changed their RSA SSH key a while back - follow directions on this website <a href='https://github.blog/2023-03-23-we-updated-our-rsa-ssh-host-key/' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>https://github.blog/2023-03-23-we-updated-our-rsa-ssh-host-key/</a> to resolve the issue.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'Git hub not letting me clone or push', 'timestamp': '2023-03-29T15:50:02Z', 'user': 'ktnb576kzkcsp', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 12}),
