	Document(content="""Note: <p><br />The objective of the function is to return a dictionary that includes the top-N most frequent  n-grams in the file, represented as (n-gram, count) pairs.<br /><br />This can be approached by first creating a frequency dictionary of all n-grams in the file, and then sort this dictionary in a high-to-low order based on the values (i.e., frequencies). In the case of n-grams with identical frequencies, it is necessary to apply the same policy (high-to-low) to sort them. having done with the sorting then you can pick the top-N most frequent n-grams (high-to-low).<br /><br />For e.g.<br />if we have the n_grams, &#34;ight&#34;, &#34; rig&#34;, &#34;righ&#34;, and if you sort this the output would be &#34; rig&#34;, &#34;ight&#34;, &#34;righ&#34; (if sorted low-to-high) or &#34;righ&#34;, &#34;ight&#34;, &#34; rig&#34; (if sorted high-to-low).<br /><br />See the following screenshot as a demonstration:<br /><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkskmx82xa2s4ad%2F5e89b473f279371c336f957547eb601ad62cb29b9a2526bc1209882882c05049%2FScreenshot_from_2023-03-27_15-33-35.png' alt='' width='654' height='168' /><br /><br />You need to have your keys (n-grams) sorted as done in the second case, in the screenshot.<br /><br /></p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw8'], 'title': 'top_N_common Clarity', 'timestamp': '2023-03-28T18:44:12Z', 'user': 'kskmx82xa2s4ad', 'tags': ['hw8', 'instructor-note'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 168}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Hi there,</p><p></p><p>Today, I went to office hours for help. The friendly TA told me to ask a GTA for this problem.</p><p></p><p>For problem 1, in the <code>get_dict</code> function, the last if statement before the return line is what I believe to be hard coding. My code works for the provided test case for problems 1 and 2, but I am worried that the last if statement of this function will not work for other test cases. Is there another way to complete the function or is it okay?</p><p></p><p>---------------------------------------</p><p><code>def get_dict(filename, n):<br />    # 1. get lines and combine them to a set of keys<br />    lines = get_formatted_text(filename)<br />    string_all = &#34;&#34;.join(lines)<br />    ngrams = get_ngrams(string_all, n)<br /><br />    # 2. use the set to initialize a dict<br />    ngram_dict = dict.fromkeys(ngrams, 0)<br /><br />    # 3. update the values of the dict<br />    for word in ngrams:<br />        ngram_dict[word] &#43;= 1<br />        <br />    if(&#39;____&#39; in ngram_dict):<br />        del ngram_dict[&#39;____&#39;]<br /><br />    return ngram_dict</code></p><p></p> Answer: <p>string_all = &#34;&#34;.join(lines), is incorrect, this statement will not allow a space between the line in lines. <br /><br />Better to use:<br />string_all = &#34; &#34;.join(lines), notice the empty string that signifies space.<br /><br />I can&#39;t guarantee if this hard-coding would pass the final test-cases.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw8'], 'title': 'Hw08 possible hard coding', 'timestamp': '2023-03-28T18:16:32Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw8', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 12}),
