	Document(content="""Question: <p>What should be the axes be labeled for these graphs respectively?</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb4k37vlk5k5%2Fbabd398bfc2c4aad2a350a3df5ae92c566633ab104521fa158d44069e3e32e6e%2FScreen_Shot_2023-03-24_at_10.44.16_AM.png' width='517' height='85' alt='' /></p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb4k37vlk5k5%2Fc90e73de252a97f2369dc04769aa763194223162a0130442f99e6ceb461b5a37%2FScreen_Shot_2023-03-24_at_10.44.45_AM.png' width='491' height='73' alt='' /></p> Answer: <p>You can have the y axis labelled as the price of stock and x axis, time since you are trying to predict the stock price the next day from the stock price of the previous day.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'Question for hw 7', 'timestamp': '2023-03-24T14:46:17Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 108}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Do we need to submit aything to the &#34;Github Code Submission&#34; Tab on the HW 7 Gradescope Submission module, or is that just there for grading purposes?<img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fksi8ka1ba1t6tv%2Fbc49cd2b21f114240fdcdb12b501f8fac83232486940c62757b9b45522ac5baf%2FScreen_Shot_2023-03-24_at_10.05.59_AM.png' alt='Screen_Shot_2023-03-24_at_10.05.59_AM.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <p>The code just has to be pushed to GitHub. No submission of code is needed in gradescope. Please include the first page in the writeup containing your details (GitHub username) for the GitHub code submission part.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'HW 7 Gradescope Submission', 'timestamp': '2023-03-24T14:10:17Z', 'user': 'ksi8ka1ba1t6tv', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 127}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I am having issues trying to understand problem 1 part 1. I have configured a matrix with the given list x that increments its number of columns to d&#43;1, being one of them enterely 1´s and the others the first x, the second x^2, the third x^3...x^d. </p><p>I also keep y matrix constant and then perform the Beta=(X.T@X)^(-1)@X.T@Y. But my output is not even similar to the one of the example.</p><p>Can you help me to know where is my mistake?</p><p>Thanks,</p><p>Luis</p> Answer: <p>Without your code, we cannot really pinpoint the issue. I would check your feature matrix function again using small examples (like lists with 2 or 3 elements) and a small degree (like fitting it to degree 2 or degree 3). We can also help you out in office hours (online or in-person) from 5 pm to 8 pm today.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'Hw7', 'timestamp': '2023-03-24T04:02:09Z', 'user': 'lcrzmj6nzh1w6', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 10}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><a href='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb576kzkcsp%2F82865282031c4b98d1d0c5cc8976261ecb8b0af3424fd617d58984ce634b6517%2Fpolyfit' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>polyfit</a></p><p></p><p>I have attached my polyfit file to this post and was hoping that someone could give me guidance on how to solve my error. I feel as if I am solving the first couple of steps right, so I am unsure of what to change, but when I run the test case for problem 1 of d = [2,4] i get these numbers:</p><p>y_hat(x_2)<br />[-301.85353265 -351.82666279   92.8706668 ]<br />****************<br />y_hat(x_4)<br />[ -5108.44911086 -10195.27414135   -319.91904305    -34.21469268<br />     98.28175167]</p><p></p><p>when i should be getting: <img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb576kzkcsp%2F449d68ca649765e597dc32dff056e5704ea90b7e13d6a392da63c19f625934b0%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' width='546' height='142' /></p> Answer: <p>I think it&#39;s because when you construct your feature matrix this line: <br />    for i in degrees: <br />should be for i in range(xlen)</p><p>since you are constructing a feature matrix that has d &#43; 1 columns and n rows, where n is the number of samples.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'Test case values are wildly different and I don&#39;t know why', 'timestamp': '2023-03-24T01:26:14Z', 'user': 'ktnb576kzkcsp', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 14}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fl8au962mr8x6og%2F63589884b930462aa98b54ceb3db780027a6fc54ff44465ecd4420bcab192199%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p><p></p><p>Why am I getting this error with the sklearn module?</p><p>I ran both of these as well: </p><p>$ pip install scikit-learn</p><p>$ pip install panda</p> Answer: <p>I ran both of these as well: </p><p>$ pip install scikit-learn</p><p>$ pip install panda</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'Problem with sklearn imports', 'timestamp': '2023-03-24T00:21:59Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 124}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Could someone point me in the right direction to solving for the Mean Squared Error? I&#39;m not quite sure how we are supposed to use X, y, and the model parameter to calculate the MSE. Any help would be appreciated.</p> Answer: <p>you would want to use parameters &#34;model&#34; and &#34;X&#34; to find the predicted y. So now with predicted y and the actual y (from the parameter), you can calculate MSE using MSE formula</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'HW7 Problem 2.5 Error Function', 'timestamp': '2023-03-24T00:08:29Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 107}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>In the written portion of the assignment, when filling out the coefficients of the regression models, can we leave them in the form of, for example, 1.2904E(-3)x^5, aka including the E for scientific notation, and also to what decimal point should we round to?</p> Answer: <p>We expect at least 3 decimal places (your answer is supposed to be correct up to 3 decimal places)</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'Format of Coefficients', 'timestamp': '2023-03-23T19:37:58Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 123}),
