	Document(content="""Question: <p>I am trying to install modules on VS Code. I am on the scholar cluster and am unable to successfully install the modules. I have tried using &#34;python3 -m pip install pip --user --upgrade&#34; and then installing. However, I still run into the error in the image below. Can anyone who has installed these modules on scholar cluster tell me what terminal commands I need to use?<img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb87dwfuw2be%2Feae3914c684d9391a5785304c3437b54df473d5f7b8143e663a021cc86e2cfc4%2FScreenshot_2023-03-22_at_9.29.31_PM.png' width='1190' height='336' alt='' /></p> Answer: <p>You can try eceprog. It usually works.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'No module error', 'timestamp': '2023-03-23T01:34:36Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 115}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>There was a previous post asking how to calculate the MSE for the Polyfit part 3 . What equation might  I use</p><div><div> currently I&#39;m using &#34;mse = np.mean((y-y_new) ** 2&#34; This doesn&#39;t seem to be working. Can I justify my asnwer purely based off of it possibly being a result of overfitting?</div></div> Answer: <p>so you should be able to just use your feature matrix and the model to get the expected value. Mse can work but it should serve more as a second check. try finding the predicted y value using np.dot, with the parameters using your feature matrix</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'MSE for Part 3 Problem 1 Right Up', 'timestamp': '2023-03-22T22:41:38Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 11}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I continue to get the error because my alpha value of lambda is infinite. Does anyone know how to fix this?</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb3vgafp62kb%2F6431ae71fdf4194d1b526e04fa210c4a6c837f420bfbb93ea4c369c01f22af4f%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <p>I ran into the same problem and its definitely because of the get_lambda_range function. I&#39;m assuming you called the logspace function like I did and wrote</p><p></p><pre>lmbda = np.logspace(start=1e-1, stop=1e3, num=51)</pre><p>but that wont work. Thats because logspace takes the power value for the start and end parameters. For example, if you wanted to get an array of numbers in log space for the base 10 from 10^2 to 10^5 you would write the code </p><p></p><pre>lmbda = np.logspace(start=2, stop=5)</pre><p> instead of </p><pre>lmbda = np.logspace(start=1e2, stop=1e5)</pre>""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'Ridge Error', 'timestamp': '2023-03-22T18:08:47Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 136}),
