	Document(content="""Question: <p>I understand what standard normalization does, but what is the practical use of it? Why should we apply standard normalization before doing regression? Is there any other reason to use standard normalization other than helping us to compare the coefficients of the regression model (say if I don&#39;t really care about the weights of the feature, is there any other use)? </p> Answer: <p>For the purposes of this class, the main use of normalization for regression is to put all explanatory variables in the same scale for interpretation purposes. If you chose not to do this, you would still get a valid regression model for prediction purposes. In fact, normalization does not change the Pearson correlation coefficient between explanatory variables at all.</p><p></p><p><strong>Supplementary 1:</strong> Beyond interpretation, normalization can sometimes have the benefit of improved numerical stability when you try to compute regression coefficients. Computers use floating point arithmetic to represent real numbers, so numbers that are very large or very small are not well-represented in the floating point system. Normalization can sometimes avoid this. This stability effect becomes much more important when training large-scale machine learning models, such as deep neural networks, where normalization is essential to avoid &#34;internal covariate shift&#34; during training.</p><p></p><p><strong>Supplementary 2: </strong>Another issue that comes up in high-dimensional regression problems is that of &#34;approximate multi-collinearity&#34;. This refers to situations where certain explanatory variables are almost perfectly explained by linear combinations of other variables. More advanced variants of normalization/standardization, such as &#34;principal component analysis&#34; (PCA), can be used before running regression to partially mitigate this issue. In fact, this flavor of regression has its own name--principal component regression (PCR).</p><p></p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'What is the purpose of standard normalization', 'timestamp': '2023-03-21T19:03:54Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 127}),
	Document(content="""Note: <p>This note contains useful information on Exam 2, in the form of FAQ. Check here periodically for updates.<br /><br /><strong>When/where is the exam?</strong><br />Wednesday, April 5, 6:30-7:35 PM in <strong>four different rooms</strong>, as explained below: </p><ul><li>WALC 1055 --- Section 1 (Instructor: Mahsa Ghasemi)</li><li>FRNY G140 --- Section 2 (Instructor: Qiang Qiu)</li><li>BHEE 170 --- Section 3 (Instructor: Murat Kocaoglu)</li><li>ME 1061 --- Section 4 (Instructor: Anuran Makur)</li></ul><p>We will check the collected exams to make sure you were in the correct room. </p><p><strong><br />Is the exam coordinated for all four sections?</strong><br />Yes.</p><p><strong><br />What will be on the exam?</strong><br />There will be about 6 questions, covering weeks 6-12 of the course. Some questions will be on Python coding (either writing code segments or interpreting output of code), and others will be on data science. You can expect questions covering the following topics:</p><p></p><ul><li>Confidence intervals</li><li>Student’s t-distribution and t-tests</li><li>Regular expressions in Python</li><li>Linear regression, least squares equations, and evaluation metrics</li><li>Regularization and ridge regression</li><li>Cross validation</li><li>n-grams and tf-idf</li><li>Objects and classes</li></ul><p><strong><br />What is the format/procedure of the exam?</strong></p><p>You will take this exam on printed paper with a pen/pencil, on an exam packet that we will provide to you. Your completed exam will be scanned and uploaded to Gradescope, which we will use for grading and returning the exams to you. We will be leveraging Purdue’s Instructional Data Processing to have your exams uploaded. As a result, <strong>it is critical that you follow the exact template we have provided in the exam packet</strong>. This includes (1) writing all of your work on the exact sheet of paper provided for each question, and (2) writing your name and PUID at the top of every question. To facilitate this, the first 5 minutes of the exam will be used solely to fill out your name/ID on each page.</p><p><strong><br />What materials am I allowed to bring?</strong><br />Computers/tablets/calculators/electronic devices are not allowed, but other than that, the exam is open notes. You may bring hard copies of anything on Brightspace and may bring handwritten notes. You can also bring printed notes, e.g., a printed copy of a notebook you created or a PDF of notes you created. You are also allowed to bring a reference book (such as a Python reference book); however, we discourage this because we expect that looking anything up in a book might waste a lot of your time and negatively affect your overall performance.</p><p><strong><br />What is the best way to study for the exam?</strong><br />Go through all the lecture notes thoroughly. Then make sure you are comfortable with how to do the homeworks that have been assigned so far. Finally, take the practice exams posted on Brightspace.</p><p><br />One suggestion is to create your own summary sheet / crib sheet that summarizes and synthesizes the lecture notes and/or homeworks. Often by creating something rather than merely looking at the notes, you will gain a deeper understanding of the material.</p><p><strong><br />Will you take off points for syntax errors?</strong><br />If the syntax error is trivial (e.g. missing a colon at the end of an if statement), we will only assess a minor penalty. If the syntax error is significant (e.g., you write a for loop without the “in” keyword or write a C-based for loop instead of Python for loop), we may assess more penalty because this may show a fundamental lack of understanding of the syntax.</p><p><strong><br />What if I have a DRC accommodation?</strong><br />Please schedule an exam with the DRC Testing Center, and email the instructor for your section if you have any questions. All other details will remain the same.</p><p></p><p><strong>Note: </strong>Students have until <strong>11:55 PM seven days before an exam</strong> to submit a request to the DRC Testing Center. <br /><br /><strong>Additional Note: </strong>The students need to submit all <strong>final exam</strong> requests to the DRC Testing Center before <strong>11:55 PM on April 7</strong>. </p><p><strong><br />Any other logistics to be aware of?</strong><br />There are not assigned seats during the exam, but you should leave one seat between you and the people on either side of you. <strong>Please try to arrive 10-15 min early</strong> to have enough time to find an appropriate seat. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Exam 2: FAQ', 'timestamp': '2023-03-21T18:32:55Z', 'user': 'ks3l0aykohs3yd', 'tags': ['exam', 'instructor-note', 'pin'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 379}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fl6maptmggzy7op%2F50c30e2afa4d4d6554b7001a9ea7c977aa23c9e5ac65814385c398ee52b34459%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p><p>Is this graph correct for question 1? I am not sure if it is incorrect because there is a label at the top that says &#34;1e6&#34;. How would I fix this issue? Thank you</p> Answer: <p>Resolved</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'HW 7 Q1 Graph', 'timestamp': '2023-03-21T15:29:03Z', 'user': 'l6maptmggzy7op', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 8}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>My model seems to be correct, but my y_hat and y are not being plotted correctly. May someone help me understand what may be the cause of this?</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fksi8ka1ba1t6tv%2F9af37d8b0540f009f20f799733337a85b7f6fed628829906368dd0a75d6a1d42%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <p>One issue is that the sets of values given for the horizontal axis are not the same for $$y$$ and $$\hat{y}$$, since one does not go beyond 2000 while the other one goes beyond 10000. You may want to check what is passed to the plotting command to see why the values over the horizontal axis are different.<br /><br />Also, the ranges for $$y$$ and $$\hat{y}$$ are significantly different, which means $$\hat{y}$$ is not correctly computed (or plotted). This may be caused by an issue in the normalization procedure. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'HW7: Trouble Plotting y_hat and y vs X', 'timestamp': '2023-03-21T14:36:34Z', 'user': 'ke4p3bj2nya42o', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 14}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Is it an issue that my plot will only show when running my code in the interactive window in VS code? I am using Windows Subsystem for Linux and it has to come to my attention that it is a fundamental issue of WSL that it can&#39;t display UI. The only way I can see my plot is in an interactive window.</p> Answer: <p>As long as you have the code to plot it in your final submission, it should be okay since this is an issue on the WSL side of things. Also, you can save your plots (using plt.savefig) instead for your convenience. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'Plot only shows in interactive window', 'timestamp': '2023-03-20T18:20:08Z', 'user': 'ktnb7nhk4kp7gh', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 138}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>What do we do in the case where X.T @ X is non-invertible when solving for B? Are we expected to make use of NumPy&#39;s in-built Moore-Penrose pseudoinverse function? </p> Answer: <p>You might be running into the same issue as: <a href='/class/lcj9rez4czg6zj/post/307' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>https://piazza.com/class/lcj9rez4czg6zj/post/307</a> </p><p>Did you double-check that you constructed the feature matrix correctly? This was the issue in the previous post.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'Problem 1: X.T @ X Non-Invertible Case', 'timestamp': '2023-03-20T16:26:26Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 154}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I am trying to initialize a zero matrix and i used the following function for problem 1 when creating the feature matrix:</p><p></p><p>X = np.zeros(len(x), (d&#43;1))</p><p></p><p>I keep getting the following error:</p><p></p><p>&#34;cannot interpret &#39;2&#39; as a data type&#34;.</p><p></p><p>Do you know what could be causing this issue? Thank you</p><p></p><p></p> Answer: <p>Resolved sorry, I had to add in another set of parenthesies</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw7', 'hw3'], 'title': 'Initialize a zero matrix', 'timestamp': '2023-03-20T14:26:38Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 12}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I am working on problem 3 of HW 7. When I run my Python file through terminal in VScode, nothing comes up. I have the plt.show() line in my code but still nothing comes up. How should I display the graph to screen?</p> Answer: <p>Well, SSH has no image transmission though. (More precisely, you are connecting to the terminal, not the graph window.) The best way you can do is just to log in ececomp with Thinlinc via a web browser using the link: desktop.ececomp.ecn.purdue.edu </p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'How to display graph in ececomp?', 'timestamp': '2023-03-19T23:29:50Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 147}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Hi,</p><p>I&#39;m not quite sure about what the 1E^-1 and 1E^3 stand for. Is it e^-1 to e^3 or 1*10^-1 to 1*10^3? I&#39;m confused since there&#39;s a comment down in the main function saying that lambda should be [1,3000].</p> Answer: <p>$$ 1E-1 $$ stands for $$ 1 \times 10^{-1} $$ and $$ 1E3 $$ stands for $$ 1 \times 10^{3} $$. The comment is for testing purposes so you could uncomment that line and verify your results - in a previous semester, the testing values we gave were [1, 3000] and this semester you would be using  <code>lmbda = [1, 100, 1200, 3000]</code>to verify your results as given below. To generate your actual results you would have to use the given range of lambda that is returned from the function get_lambda_range(). I hope that cleared it up. <img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fke80y12ngei1tx%2Feec2d466214ea60e270214056fe28eedd636007da57705746cc946a15890ec6c%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'Confusion on question 2 part 3 lambda value', 'timestamp': '2023-03-19T18:13:46Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 12}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I was trying to plot the fitted models but when I try to run the code, I get this error. Can anyone help me with this?</p><p>Thanks.</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb6igyqfbch%2Fa023629eeb4bcaa7bb50f69a4cd747a7a7c6464ff28cc2733970cfcd4fdc7f52%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p> Answer: If the error occurs on the sum line, perhaps something there is resulting in a bigger than expected value — I would look at degree_of_x.""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'getting error in HW7 Problem1', 'timestamp': '2023-03-18T13:45:48Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 155}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I wrote this code for these two functions but I am getting error with the code for least squares function. Kindly help me with that.</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb6igyqfbch%2F756369376a3cb98b102c6561ae1771aff92b2057f63d0b7b8ffa4cce82a3c24c%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb6igyqfbch%2Fd84d8dd155656ccd0d00c8d2bdfc93f7869cfbb9846eab327fd18f166ddf9b7d%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: np.matmul can multiply only two matrices at a time.""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'Error in problem1', 'timestamp': '2023-03-18T00:25:17Z', 'user': 'ktnb6igyqfbch', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 13}),
