	Document(content="""Question: <p>What is the numerical c value the problem 1 writeup asks us to find? And how can we calculate this value? For context, the question asks: <em>Discuss relationship of data and insert numerical value of c calculated from best regression</em></p> Answer: <p>It is asking you to identify the best degree for proper fitting, so you just need to state the degree and explain your answer.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'Numerical C Value', 'timestamp': '2023-03-14T20:34:28Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 132}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Why is there a determinant of zero, causing an error in the np inverse function, when I take the feature matrix X and perform the operation X.T @ X, but there is not when I do X @ X.T. In the formula, the part in parentheses is X^(T) X, so I assumed it is necessary to perform the operation X.T @ X but that does not work. Is X @ X.T fine, and if so why is the formula written that way?</p> Answer: <p>I am not sure which problem you are referring to, so I&#39;ll answer the question in general. X^T X is usually not equal to X X^T, so the least-squares formula only works with X^T X (assuming the rows of the matrix are sample feature vectors followed by 1). The derivation of the formula is given in the regression slides, so I suggest you take a closer look at that to understand it. Since a matrix is non-singular (i.e., inverse exists) if and only if its determinant is non-zero, you must be in a situation where X^T X is singular. If you have come across a least-squares regression problem where X^T X is singular, then the closed-form formula in the slides will not work, and you need to use more advanced methods like pseudo-inversion to get a solution. However, none of this necessarily implies that X X^T must be singular.</p><p></p><p>Recall from the slides that X^T X is non-singular if and only if the columns of X are linearly independent. On the other hand, we can infer from the slides that X X^T is non-singular if and only if the rows of X are linearly independent. It is possible to have matrices X with: 1) linearly <strong>in</strong>dependent columns and linearly dependent rows, 2) linearly <strong>in</strong>dependent rows and linearly dependent columns, 3) linearly <strong>in</strong>dependent rows and linearly <strong>in</strong>dependent columns, and 4) linearly dependent rows and linearly dependent columns. (You should try to construct examples to convince yourself.) Hence, we can have matrices X satisfying four possibilities, respectively: 1) X^T X is non-singular and X X^T is singular, 2) X^T X is singular and X X^T is non-singular, 3) X^T X and X X^T are both non-singular, and 4) X^T X and X X^T are both singular.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'Matrix Algebra', 'timestamp': '2023-03-12T02:05:59Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 151}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>For some reason, I am getting the correct output for the main function in polyfit.py but the output is backward. can I leave it as is or should I try to flip it to face the right way?</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkdrxdw4keg166%2Fbe60ae87fabd7e1fa0f4cee6c9f94d97a101c9a69ad054f3bef24ab97d12e398%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkdrxdw4keg166%2F804057b3bf1ca003b1b07c53845a5c57f45b17c3c45c385371c21159dae6bc22%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p> Answer: Check to see if the first column of your feature matrix has the x value raised to the highest degree and the column has x raised to 0. """, meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'Output for polyfit.py', 'timestamp': '2023-03-11T01:56:03Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 147}),
