	Document(content="""Question: <p>For the polyfit problem, I believe I have graphed all of the regression functions properly and calculated their respective MSE values properly. Polynomials of degree 3 and higher are clearly better fits than the quadratic or the linear, but the MSE is somehow lower for the quadratic and the linear. If I take the absolute value of the error rather than squaring it that seems to fix the issue, but this is not what we were taught in class. Should I just say 3 is the best fit by inspection despite the higher MSE value?</p> Answer: If one graph seems to fit much better, but another has a lower MSE, I suspect you have an error in your calculation of the MSE values.<div><br /></div><div>When explaining which functions fit the data better, you should likely not solely rely on MSE, but it might well be worth mentioning.</div>""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'Lowest MSE', 'timestamp': '2023-03-10T23:52:48Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 133}),
