	Document(content="""Question: <p>I&#39;m unsure if this is correct, but some of my fitted models for Problem 1 of HW 7 are practically identical, and thus overlap on the generated plot. It is not very apparent which model is technically the most accurate, but since they are all roughly similar, should I use the lowest degree model? Or do I need to write a function to calculate the smallest error, and thus the best model for the data?</p><p></p><p>Also, it is difficult to see the overlapping models in the plot. Is it okay to submit the plot this way? The model plot lines are there, they are just difficult to see.</p> Answer: <p>If you are having difficulty seeing overlapping lines, you can try modifying the line thicknesses or other attributes using Matplotlib.</p><div><div></div><div>If you find that multiple models all do a good job of fitting the data, you would want to choose the model most useful in future estimations. Material covered in lectures and on the slides might be helpful for this.</div></div><div></div><div>In order to choose the best model, you would want the model that fits the data best visually, has the lowest MSE and also the lowest degree. You want to avoid both overfitting and underfitting. The slides should say more about this.</div>""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'Fitted Models Overlap', 'timestamp': '2023-03-08T19:59:47Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 156}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I am confused on what exactly the feature matrix is:</p><p>I understand it has the coefficients its format should be</p><p></p><p>matrix = [# samples][degrees &#43; 1]</p><p></p><p>but I am do not understand the purpose of the feature matrix is or how we would calculate the values in it.</p><p></p> Answer: <p>Given samples $$x_1, x_2, x_3, ... , x_n $$ and their corresponding $$ y_1, y_2, ... , y_n $$ and let&#39;s say you want to fit it to a polynomial of degree $$ d $$. Let&#39;s say this polynomial of best fit is $$ y = a_d x^d + a_{d-1} x^{d-1} + ... + a_0$$. The feature matrix is used to find the coefficients $$ a_d, a_{d-1}, a_{d-2}, ..., a_0 $$. <br /><br />In this case the feature matrix will be:<br />$$ X = \begin{bmatrix}  {x_1}^d & {x_1}^{d-1} & {x_1}^{d-2} ... &x_1& 1  \\  {x_2}^d & {x_2}^{d-1} & {x_2}^{d-2} ... &x_2& 1 \\  &...  &  &  \\  &  &  &  \\ {x_n}^d & {x_n}^{d-1} & {x_n}^{d-2} ... &x_n& 1 \\ \end{bmatrix} $$</p><p>The coefficients will then be: <br /><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fke80y12ngei1tx%2Fe63b79114218158776b93cc1e8aeb1959191164e93292bd4a0d0018d9a733978%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /><br />Here X is the feature matrix, and $$ y = \begin{bmatrix} {y_1}\\ {y_2}\\ {y_3}\\ ... \\ \\ {y_n} \\ \end{bmatrix} $$, $$ \beta = \begin{bmatrix} {a_d}\\ {a_{d-1}}\\ {a_{d-2}}\\ ... \\ \\ {a_0} \\ \end{bmatrix} $$. <br /><br />Let&#39;s consider this example for the feature matrix: <br />[$$x_1, x_2, x_3 $$] = [1,2,3] and let&#39;s say the polynomial we want to fit it to is quadratic (the degree, d,  is 2). Then the feature matrix will be: <br />$$ X = \begin{bmatrix}  1^2 & 1^1 & 1^0 \\  2^2& 2^1 & 2^0   \\  3^2&3^1  &3^0   \\ \end{bmatrix} $$</p><p></p><p></p><p>The feature matrix should have the size (# of datapoints) x (degree &#43; 1). Each row of the feature matrix corresponds to one point of data from x, and each column corresponds to a certain degree value, starting at the highest degree and going to 0, so the last column of the feature matrix is filled with all 1&#39;s. </p><p></p><p>CAVEAT: The formula for $$\beta$$ above only holds when the columns of the feature matrix $$X$$ are linearly independent. To ensure this, we must have that $$ d + 1 \leq n$$ and at least $$d +1$$ of the explanatory variable samples $$x_1,\dots,x_n$$ are distinct.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'Feature Matrix', 'timestamp': '2023-03-08T18:50:34Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 161}),
