	Document(content="""Question: <p>After taking exam 1, I am extremely frustrated with the fairness of this course. I have been able to proficiently complete each coding assignment while also attending and comprehending each lecture. I studied an extreme amount only to prepare for a test that was drastically different and difficult. I’m usually not one to complain, but I believe that this exam will skew our final grades enough to misrepresent our knowledge. I really believe that this exam should be analyzed by course coordinators. Let me know how we can expect this to affect our final grade.</p> Answer: <p>I agree. I was genuinely interested in this class as nearly every concept applies to machine learning, from data sampling to NumPy usage, and it&#39;s a field that greatly interests me. I was also very engaged in this class, spending a fair amount of time each week reviewing lectured topics, not to mention doing well on the homework. I felt great and well prepared for yesterday&#39;s exam, as I had studied more than any exam I&#39;d ever taken beforehand, given that I had something of a passion for this class. The exam was more than deceptive and poorly tested our knowledge of all content learned the past 6 weeks. Barely any topics were covered, and I feel swindled. My image of this course has shifted negatively and I don&#39;t know if I can continue to maintain the positive attitude I held toward it the past 6 weeks.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Exam Frustrations and Concerns', 'timestamp': '2023-02-23T06:11:08Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 28, 'views': 294}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Is the class on Thursday (02/23) canceled since this is a class just after Exam 1? </p> Answer: No""", meta={'folders': ['logistics'], 'title': 'Class Canceled After Exam 1?', 'timestamp': '2023-02-23T05:34:03Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['logistics', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 272}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I&#39;m not sure about everyone else, but I felt relatively discouraged after taking the exam tonight. Its content seemed radically different than that content covered in lecture, homeworks, and practice exams given to us to prepare for the exam. As someone who spent significant time studying and preparing I feel that much of my time was wasted since I would likely have done just as poorly had I not prepared or practiced at all with the lecture and practice material provided to us. I am really discouraged by this take away because exams should test students&#39; abilities to understand and apply material, not their ability to make stuff up to try and receive partial credit on questions that they are completely unfamiliar with. </p><p></p><p>I am not usually one to post about frustration, and usually would wait a day before providing negative feedback on an experience, but was in part wondering if others in the class felt the same or similar to myself. Please let me know. I hope that future exams are more reflective of the content that students are comfortable with from both lectures and homework, and that we may feel more adequately prepared for it. </p><p></p><p>I spent 12&#43; hours studying for this exam, which included reviewing all previous lecture slides, most related colab notebooks from demonstrations, watching supplemental videos on topics, going through practice exams, and reviewing topics with TAs during office hours. I made sure I understood every topic to the depth of the previous exams, and expected a layout consistent with the previous two exams, which I breezed through. The layout of this exam was horrendously different. Around 2 of the questions in the previous exams were fill in the blanks or multiple choice, the next 2 or 3 were simple scripts with some more niche topics i.e. list comprehension, and the last 1 or 2 were graphing/testing process questions. We had no multiple choice or fill in the blanks (i.e. what is the output if...), the short scripts were far more complex in logic, and there were barely any actual graphing/testing/sampling questions. Questions 5 and 6 were entirely out of the scope of anything taught to us, aside from the basic concepts. Having an entire multi-part question based around a niche function was an atrocious decision, and not consistent with topics covered in lecture. If we were expected to know the map() function so well, there should have been a lecture dedicated to that function alone. This exam horribly tested our knowledge of the past 6 weeks&#39; content. Previous exams covered nearly every topic to a decent extent; this exam covered very few topics complexly to an indescribable extent.</p> Answer: <p>Yep, that was ridiculous. Not only was the content way conceptually harder, but the format was also less conducive for a 1 hour exam. There were hardly any multiple choice, unlike the previous exams, and way too many write code/justify answer questions.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Post Exam 1 Thoughts', 'timestamp': '2023-02-23T01:09:50Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 94, 'views': 321}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>What content can be brought in as notes for the exam?</p> Answer: <p>anything printed</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Open note exam', 'timestamp': '2023-02-22T21:33:21Z', 'user': 'l6zrkd3ef6m17e', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 246}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb523h7f14k%2Fd1b6b6bde227ec081d5b21b092f841526a7fc1c48d276f9fd877a1f0ccb4a3f9%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p><p>How did they calculate the variance to be 3/50? The formula I see for variance when the CLT theorem applies is sigma squared/n.</p> Answer: <p>I believe it is because the variance you have calculated is already squared. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 Question 5c', 'timestamp': '2023-02-22T19:48:06Z', 'user': 'ktnb523h7f14k', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 3, 'views': 178}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>According to the lecture slide, I see two different descriptions for list comprehension.</p><p></p><p>first one is [output expression for item in iterable if condition]</p><p>second one is [output expression if-else clause for item in iterable condition(s) on iterable]</p><p></p><p>when should I use the second one?</p> Answer: <p>It may be good to answer this with examples.</p><p>[x for x in [1,2,3,4] if x &gt; 1] gives you [2,3,4];</p><p>[True  if x &gt; 1 else False for x in [1,2,3,4]] gives you [False, True, True, True].</p><p>In general, the iteration part is the same. In the first case, you are doing a selection like a filter. In the second, you are doing a &#34;switching.&#34; You may notice that the length of the returned list is different from that of the iterable, while the length is the same in the second case.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'List comprehension question', 'timestamp': '2023-02-22T17:40:58Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 188}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Can we use a Ti-30Xa calculator for the exam? Some of the sampling and histogram calculations require doing math operations with decimals.</p> Answer: Calculators are not allowed, and the exam is designed with this in mind.""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'One-line calculator', 'timestamp': '2023-02-22T05:30:13Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 206}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>My code cant open the file path because it cannot find it for some reason. </p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fl44zwahaj7u1yc%2F2a87b241ad858295d875e6a46d9a35c2f47a61c2f53a7940cad20c56a7aef04e%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: Cd into the hw5 folder""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'No such file', 'timestamp': '2023-02-22T04:25:47Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 135}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Could someone explain how this function works? What does the if statement serve for, and why is there &#39;none&#39; at the end of the action in the if statement. </p><p></p><p>Thank you!<img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fl8au962mr8x6og%2Ffbbe16c9e6739a0cdf9ed900252fb820ae416db0c7fd1988e88eef940f11f157%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <p>So you&#39;re trying to assign each English word in a tuple to a codeword in a separate list. First, you initialize an empty dictionary, and then the for loop iterates through the indexes of the English word list and checks whether the current index is bigger than the entire codewords list. If it is, there is no codeword you can assign to the English word so you assign &#39;none&#39; . If the index is less than the length of the codewords list then you can just assign that codeword to the English word in the dictionary, secret_language[current English word] = current codeword. In short, you need this if statement in case the codeword list is shorter than your English list. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 2022 Q2B (ii)', 'timestamp': '2023-02-22T01:41:39Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 162}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>For question 6c, how does the 68-95-99.7% rule coorespond to finding the p-value. Thank you</p> Answer: <p>The p-value is the area under the tails above the &#43;z-score and below the -z-score for a two-tailed z-test. The 68-95-99.7% rule says that 68% of the area under the bell curve is in the middle 2 standard deviations of the curve (&#43;/- 1 standard deviation, between z= -1 and z = 1), 95% of the area is in the middle 4 standard deviations of the curve (&#43;/- 2 standard deviations, between z = -2 and z = 2), and 99.7% of the area is in the middle 6 standard deviations of the curve (&#43;/- 3 standard deviations, between  z = -3 and z = 3).</p><p></p><p>If z = 3, the area under the bell curve that is above z = 3 (z  &gt; 3) would be 0.003, so the p-value for a 1-sided z-test would by 0.003. For a two-sided test, if z = 3, you would want to find the area of the normal distribution where z &lt; - 3 and z &gt; 3.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 Practice Exam 6c', 'timestamp': '2023-02-21T22:00:57Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 179}),
	Document(content="""Question: I really don&#39;t get what this question is doing. I saw that X = -Y means that the realization of Y is the negative of the realization of X. But what does that mean? Does that mean that if X happens, Y doesn&#39;t happen, and if X doesn&#39;t happen, Y happens? Answer: <p>Informally, a random variable is as a mathematical object that can take different values with different probabilities depending on the outcome of a statistical experiment. There is no notion of a random variable &#34;happening&#34;. In probability theory, &#34;events&#34; can happen or not happen. Random variables are merely useful constructs (technically, functions from the sample space to real numbers) to define collections of numerical events to which we can assign probabilities. </p><p></p><p>But all the abstractness aside, let me try to explain this with an example. Let X be a random variable which represents the outcome of a dice throw. Then, X can take the possible values {1,2,3,4,5,6}, and X takes each of these values with probability 1/6. When the dice is thrown (i.e., the statistical experiment is run), we see a particular &#34;realization&#34; of the random variable, e.g., {X = 4} if the dice came out 4. This means that the event {X = 4} happened. The probability of this event is P(X = 4) = 1/6, and such probabilities make up the PMF of the random variable (because the random variable is discrete in this example). When we define Y = -X, we are constructing a new random variable Y which takes the possible values {-1,-2,-3,-4,-5,-6}, and in particular, {Y = -j} if and only if {X = j} for j = 1,2,3,4,5,6. This means that when X has realization 4 (i.e., the event {X = 4} occurs), Y has realization -4 (i.e., the event {Y = -4} also occurs). Moreover, the probability P(Y = -4) = P(X = 4) = 1/6. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW5, Q1B', 'timestamp': '2023-02-21T19:52:04Z', 'user': 'klh98pfz6y127s', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 133}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Based on this slide, we can calculate the mean and variance of the sampling distribution if we repeat the experiment many times. We can form a graph made out of all the means collected. </p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5b8oexj1jg%2F6d2f294a7670e09eeea758d19325142e50d149fee9faf01057306d075a9a33d8%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' width='565' height='320' /></p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p>However, this question, which only conduct the experiment once, uses the same method to find mean and variance. Shouldn&#39;t we conduct the experiment many times in order to form the sampling distribution of the mean and calculate its parameter? How can we form the sampling distribution of the mean with only one experiment/one mean?</p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5b8oexj1jg%2F3ce74ef1fbbe2154f047432ef6abff33976368fe50ca1e425a5b129f659c14fd%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' width='752' height='199' /></p><p></p><p></p> Answer: <p> According to the central limit theorem, we know that the overall sampling distribution of the sample mean approaches a normal distribution when the number of samples tends to infinity. Because there are 50 samples (50&gt;= 30), we can use CLT.</p><p></p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 Q5c', 'timestamp': '2023-02-21T15:15:52Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 151}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb7hcvqm46hd%2F42394ae3aa65569a76d5aaa17ca1fd300c6565a1f2f3b9f32947b23cbceb05bc%2FScreen_Shot_2023-02-20_at_10.19.54_PM' width='842' height='402' alt='' /></p><p>Can someone help me understand this problem? I don&#39;t get how to find q(.) or p(.). I also don&#39;t understand the summation, why does it start at x &lt; 0, and where does it end?</p> Answer: <p>The summation is carried out for all x &lt; 0. So It ends when x &gt;= 0.</p><p></p><p>Realize that for a uniform distribution, all events have the same probability of occurring. So given the set of 4 payoffs, each payoff should have a probability of 1/4 or 0.25. This is q(x) for any x in the context of the problem.</p><p></p><p>The values for p(x) come from the previous parts of the problem.</p><p></p><p>Thus (0.20-0.25) &#43; (0.40-0.25) represents the sum, which is 0.10. Since 0.10 &gt; 0.05, they have violated the limitations of the GIA.</p><p></p><p></p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 Q3d', 'timestamp': '2023-02-21T03:21:58Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 146}),
	Document(content="""Note: <p>Hi<br /><br />Just a reminder that if you have a scheduling conflict/approved absence from the exam, you need to get approval from your instructor to be able to take the makeup exam. After you have received approval, you can forward that approval to jtoberma@purdue.edu (myself) and he will coordinate your makeup exam. <br /><br />Jason Toberman </p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Make-up Exam 1', 'timestamp': '2023-02-20T16:29:42Z', 'user': 'kskmxecspaq4i1', 'tags': ['exam', 'instructor-note'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 176}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>To my understanding, we are trying to make the z-score bigger to make the null hypothesis less probable. You can increase n or decrease variance to make z-bigger. However, if you increase n doesn&#39;t that make xbar approach the true mean because of the central limit theorem which would make the null hypothesis more probable? In that case, wouldn&#39;t decreasing n mean there is a greater chance xbar is farther away from mu?</p> Answer: <p>This is a great question. For the purposes of the Fall 22 exam, the question implicitly assumes that all other parameters are held constant when a particular parameter is changed. So, xbar is held constant as n is increased. In this case, the z-score would indeed increase with larger n since the standard error reduces. This explains the official solution, and this is what you should assume unless explicitly stated otherwise.</p><p></p><p>On the other hand, your observation is also partly correct. If we do not fix xbar, then as n increases, xbar tends to the population mean mu (due to the law of large numbers). However, this does not allow us to easily conclude that the null hypothesis is more or less probable, because both |xbar - mu| and the standard error are decreasing as n increases, so it is not obvious what happens to the z-score based solely on the formula for z-score. In fact, |xbar - mu| is technically a random variable, so one needs to carefully define what &#34;decreasing&#34; even means in this scenario. If you go through the exercise of rigorously doing the calculations, you&#39;ll see that in some &#34;average&#34; sense, |xbar - mu| decays at the &#34;same rate&#34; as the standard error. This is precisely why we can even have a central limit theorem where the Z-variable is normally distributed with mean 0 and variance 1. We of course do not expect you to know the derivation of the central limit theorem, but I thought I&#39;d shed some light on the matter since it was such a nice question.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 22 Q6 Part E', 'timestamp': '2023-02-20T14:35:23Z', 'user': 'ktnb8hggszq3im', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 140}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>How is the answer item_2? I thought it should be item_3 as this is the only list that has length not less than 5.</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb6igyqfbch%2Fb90cad047781b6235d92a2aba7f4031ec781688951626954ab292e80dfd09834%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p> Answer: item_3 is a set, and since sets cannot have repeated values, the line that tries to add 16 to item_3 doesn’t do anything because item_3 already has 16 in it. So, item_3 only has 4 items. """, meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 22 Q2 Part C', 'timestamp': '2023-02-20T05:05:37Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 126}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Do we have to know Bayesian or Frequentist approaches to probability for the exam?</p> Answer: <p>You are responsible to know about Bayesian vs frequentist philosophy to the extent that they are covered in the slides. The mechanics of calculating probabilities remain the same under both frameworks (at least in the context of this class), and you certainly need to know the basics of this.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Exam Content', 'timestamp': '2023-02-20T04:31:36Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 183}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>My program is returning a z-score of -1.7602, when the answer should be -1.7594. I&#39;m not sure why, I haven&#39;t rounded any variables in my program and my answers to the other variables are correct. Any ideas?<br /><br />update: I switched to using numpy functions instead of manually calculating things and that fixed all rounding issues.</p> Answer: <p><br />Glad switching to numpy worked for you!</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW5 Problem2 Question 2, testcase standard score mismatch', 'timestamp': '2023-02-20T03:09:52Z', 'user': 'ktnb7c2eqqn5ky', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 137}),
	Document(content="""Question: For example would num= round(num,4) in Python, be a correct rounded number? Answer: <p>It would be the right rounded number; alternatively you can also use formatting (<a href='https://docs.python.org/3/tutorial/inputoutput.html' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>https://docs.python.org/3/tutorial/inputoutput.html</a>) like so - </p><p></p><pre>print(f&#39;The rounded number is {num:.4f}&#39;)</pre><p>Make sure you don&#39;t round any values while calculating any quantities!</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Could I assume the value round by round() function is correct ?', 'timestamp': '2023-02-20T01:24:47Z', 'user': 'k83r1oihjvd2uq', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 139}),
