	Document(content="""Question: <p>I cannot figure out how to make the actual confidence interval. I have Mean, error and score but i cant figure out how to make the interval correctly</p> Answer: <p>The confidence interval should be of the format: (x - score * SE, x &#43; score * SE). x = mean, score = t or z-score, SE= standard error</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Confidence interval hwk 5 part 3', 'timestamp': '2023-02-19T23:52:07Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 110}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>We need u to calculate or z or t value, but we are given u. Am i missing something?</p> Answer: <p>In order to find the z or t score for a confidence interval, you do not need the population mean. You can use the stats.norm.ppf or stats.t.ppf function and the confidence level to find the standard score. This slide should help. This equation is for a two sided confidence interval.<img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fksla74foumq7mf%2Fe6a6a07a16c47336f367c18a961886fa89185d7ab1c0ad8a406e9bda081b1bd1%2Fconfidence_int.png' width='700' height='353' alt='' /></p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'hwk 5 questions 3 part 1', 'timestamp': '2023-02-19T23:08:29Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 106}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>For some reason, my import numpy and import scipy.stats says that they could not be resolved. Getting an error not sure why.</p> Answer: <p>If you are using VSCode make sure you select the right version and interpreter of python. If you recently upgraded your python version there is a chance your libraries stayed with the older version.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Hw 05 Problem 3', 'timestamp': '2023-02-19T22:30:11Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 111}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>What (if anything) can we conclude about the hypothesis at the confidence level of 0.05?</p><p></p><p>The question says that the <strong><em>confidence</em></strong> level is 0.05. Is it supposed to be asking about the <strong><em>significance </em></strong>level? Since usually alpha is the one that is less than 0.1 and c is the one that is above 0.9</p> Answer: You can treat this question as asking about the significance level, yes. <div><br /></div><div>Confidence intervals usually are higher, like .9 or .95, for example, and question 2 does not ask for a confidence interval.</div>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW5 wording clarification', 'timestamp': '2023-02-19T22:08:55Z', 'user': 'jzhn3s65vjd4by', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 104}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Are the rules for late submission of the coding homework applicable to the gradescope writeup submission, referring to HW5 only?</p> Answer: <p>The homework late submission rules are applicable to all homework assignments. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Are the late submission rules for HW5 writeup the same as the coding part of hw5?', 'timestamp': '2023-02-19T21:22:55Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 121}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I calculated the z score to be 2, but how to calculate the p value based on this information? My guess is that since 95% of the values fall within the rage of 2 * sigma, so the p value is 1 - 0.95 = 0.05. But I don&#39;t understand how 2 sigma can be related to a z score of 2. </p> Answer: <p>The z-score represents how many standard deviations away from the mean.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Sp22 Exam 1 6b', 'timestamp': '2023-02-19T20:59:10Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 132}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Can someone explain how to get p(x)? How are the .2 and .4 derived?</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb533c31sbi%2F66ff2fffebd76674f3d10a0f7ba8c122472d1d76ed3a9e17530115aac9861b6c%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <p>p(x) is the PMF in the previous question. Since it&#39;s asking the sum of x &lt; 0, which only contains 2 numbers: x = -2 and x = -1. The corresponding values for them are 0.2 and 0.4. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Sp22 Exam 1 3d', 'timestamp': '2023-02-19T20:47:32Z', 'user': 'ktnb533c31sbi', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 114}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>When doing parts 1 and 2 of problem 3, I was using stats.norm.ppf(1-(1-c)/2) to calculate the t_score. Then I read about using stats.t.ppf(1 - (1 - c)/2), using .9 and .95 for,  and the two functions didn&#39;t output the same value so I did not know which one I should be using. </p><p></p><p>Also, when I do stats.t.ppf my value for the t score is the same which I don&#39;t think is correct.</p><p></p><p>I also want to clarify that it will also be the value that we put in our write up for the t score or z score value for parts 1 and 2. </p> Answer: If you need to calculate a t-score, use stats.t.ppf(q,df); it takes in 2 parameters, the second being df which is degrees of freedom. df=sample size - 1 always <div><br /></div><div>If you don’t specify the degrees of freedom for the t-score, your answer will be off. <br /><div><br /></div><div>If you need to calculate z-score, use stats.norm.ppf(q), which only takes 1 parameter and would be what you have above. </div></div>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW5 problems(parts 1 and 2)', 'timestamp': '2023-02-19T19:55:17Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 127}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>One of the instructors mentioned that there would be an error tolerance of 0.001 on HW 5. What about for the questions that require integer answers?</p><p></p><p>For Problem 2 question 3 I am getting 1228 as my corresponding minimum sample size. This is off by 1 sample from the expected value of 1229. Is my answer correct or did I do something wrong?</p> Answer: <p>1228 would be an incorrect value for the test case. The wording of the question is asking what would be the <em>minimum. </em>1228 would not cross the threshold of p = 0.05<br /><br />This is most likely <em>not</em> due to a rounding error. I think it would be good to look at when you are calculating the standard deviation in your code. You will get 1228 if you use</p><p></p><pre>np.std(data1, ddof = 0)</pre><p>or </p><pre>np.std(data1)</pre><p>The following is from the README:<br /><br /></p><p><em>To find the standard deviation, type</em></p><p><em>sd = np.std(data, ddof=x)</em></p><p><em>where x is the differential from the number of samples N to determine the degrees of freedom. When we are calculating the standard deviation of a sample, the denominator in equation N-1 so we would set ddof=1 . If we are calculating the standard deviation of the population (i.e. we know the population mean, the numerator in the standard deviation question would be just N, (in which case ddof=0).</em></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We do NOT know the population mean, as we only have survey data from a sample of the population. If you calculations use ddof = 0 (or unspecify it and it defaults to 0), you will get 1228 in the test case. If you use ddof =1, you will get 1229 in the test case. <br /><br /><br /></p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW5 Error Tolerance for Integer Answers', 'timestamp': '2023-02-19T18:59:50Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 119}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Hi,</p><p>I passed the testcase with my code but somehow get a negative largest standard error for the answer. Is that normal?</p> Answer: It shouldn’t be negative. You probably just have to multiply your z-score by -1. """, meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW5 2.3 largest standard error', 'timestamp': '2023-02-19T18:23:22Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 115}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>For the corresponding minimum sample size, I&#39;m getting a value of 1145.3825 but since sample size has to be whole number I&#39;m not sure whether to round this number up or down. Mathematically this number should be rounded down to 1145 but statistically speaking it should be rounded up to 1146. What should I do in this case?</p> Answer: <div>Round up to a whole number. </div><div><br /></div>You are looking for the minimum sample size for the test to be significant at a level of .05. <div><br /></div><div>You are correct that a sample size must be a whole number.</div>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Problem 2: Question 3 rounding off', 'timestamp': '2023-02-19T17:15:40Z', 'user': 'ktnb4gjv4bi54q', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 14}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>For problem 3 on HW 5, we have to compute the standard error for each part, however, would the standard error not be the same for each confidence interval? Or is there a different formula for each confidence interval? </p> Answer: <p>The standard error would remain the same as it is $$ \frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}$$ and neither standard deviation nor the number of samples change as you change the confidence level.</p><p><br /></p><p>However, it would change for the part where you know the population standard deviation. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW 5 Problem 3', 'timestamp': '2023-02-19T16:50:12Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 125}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>How do I calculate the minimum sample and standard error:</p><p></p><p>This is what I am doing now: </p><p></p><div><div>zscorecalc = stats.norm.ppf(.95)</div><div>secalc = (avg - 8) / zscorecalc # calculating largest stand err</div><div>sample = (sd/secalc) * (sd/secalc) # calculating sample size</div></div><div></div><div>However, I am getting the answers:</div><div>zscorecalc:  1.6448536269514722<br />secalc: -0.052014084508006944<br />sample:  865.2910372786222</div><div></div><div>I am using the first test case, but am not getting the right numbers and do not know what is wrong. All of my first average, standard error, and z-score numbers match though. </div><div><div></div></div> Answer: <div>Please make posts where you post code or exact solutions private to instructors only. </div><div><br /></div>The z-score calculation is slightly off. Remember that this is a two-tailed test, and that affects what the p-value is. """, meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW 5 problem 2 question 3', 'timestamp': '2023-02-19T05:52:20Z', 'user': 'ksla74foumq7mf', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 26}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Would exam 1 be covering regex?</p> Answer: <p>Regex is on exam 2. </p><p><br /></p><p>There will be about 6 questions, covering weeks 1-6 of the course. Some questions will be on Python coding (either writing code segments or interpreting output of code), and others will be on data science. You can expect questions covering the following topics:</p><p></p><ul><li>Python data structures (lists, tuples, sets, dictionaries)</li><li>Basic Python operations (e.g., loops, arithmetic, manipulating data structures)</li><li>Functions and higher order functions in Python</li><li>List comprehensions in Python</li><li>Histograms</li><li>Random variables and probability distributions</li><li>Sampling, the law of large numbers, and the central limit theorem</li><li>Hypothesis testing</li></ul>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Regex', 'timestamp': '2023-02-19T05:48:25Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 154}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>In Problem 2, part 3, I was testing my code against the test cases and my largest standard error is negative. I am not sure what the problem is.</p><div><div>mean_of_sampling_distribution_1 =  8</div><div><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb6igyqfbch%2F7e54327cb918d5ef8e01dfa06835e9a8611c59ac23f9ac0448a8f8b9f0f160a3%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></div></div> Answer: It’s because the z-score you calculated is negative. Just multiply the z-score by -1. """, meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Problem in HW5', 'timestamp': '2023-02-19T05:45:00Z', 'user': 'ktnb6igyqfbch', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 12}),
