	Document(content="""Question: <p>I plotted the PDF to do the first part of the problem but it doesn&#39;t look right at all. I made a python function representing the piecewise function and then used</p><pre>x = np.linspace(-1, 1, 100)y = [f(i) for i in x]</pre><p>then plt.plot(x,y) to plot the function.</p><p>Is the PDF plot supposed to be a downward-facing parabola with its vertex at (0,0)? I am assuming not. If it is, am I supposed to take the integral/area under the function to find the mean?</p><p></p><p>(or are we supposed to look at plt.hist(y) instead?)</p> Answer: Regarding the mean and plot, you are solving for the weighted center of a distribution if its pdf was 3x^2/2 from -1 to 1. <div><br /></div><div>Regarding the mentioned ValueError, this appears to suggest your x and y lists do not have exactly the same shape. </div>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW 5 Problem 1 Plot Shape', 'timestamp': '2023-02-19T03:24:36Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 150}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>What kind of conclusions are these questions looking for? <img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5gx345d2ba%2F0ebcf9c30e65c625dca579f1ba4d743d1b304c7d85596a13a4c37179ac522980%2FScreen_Shot_2023-02-18_at_7.45.59_PM.png' alt='Screen_Shot_2023-02-18_at_7.45.59_PM.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: If you can reject/fail to reject the null hypothesis and what this says about the true mean(s) of the population(s)""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'hw5 prob2', 'timestamp': '2023-02-19T00:47:12Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 129}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I&#39;m having trouble understanding this problem. This is my current code:</p><div><div>z_c = norm.ppf(0.05/2)</div><div>se_2 = (avg-mu) / z_c</div><div>minsamp= (np.std(data1, ddof=1)/se_2)** 2</div><div>print(&#34;Largest standard error: &#34;, se_2)</div><div>print(&#34;Minimum sample size: &#34;, minsamp)</div></div> Answer: What values are you getting?""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Not able to get the correct value for Problem 2, Question 3', 'timestamp': '2023-02-19T00:05:07Z', 'user': 'k0by7b3lf0a6s3', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 13}),
	Document(content="""Note: <p>Dear Students,</p><p></p><p>Homework 3 has been regraded. The reports have been posted and the scores updated on Brightspace. If you believe an error has been made in grading, please send a regrade request according to our normal procedure within one week from the day the new grades are posted. </p><p></p><p>Thanks!</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'Homework 3 Regraded', 'timestamp': '2023-02-18T22:03:25Z', 'user': 'l6mal8zg4z85dx', 'tags': ['hw3', 'instructor-note'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 131}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>When using .add or .update for sets, how does it decide where to put the value into the set. Is it just random as sets are unordered?</p> Answer: <p>Sets are unordered in python.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['other'], 'title': 'Set question', 'timestamp': '2023-02-18T20:10:23Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['other', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 100}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I dont understand how we can compute the z-score without a null hypothesis, should we make one ourselves?</p> Answer: <p>When creating confidence intervals, you use the confidence level in order to find the z-score or t-score. You would use the norm.ppf or t.ppf functions to find the z or t score. The following slide should help. The ppf function takes the area under a curve up to a certain point on the normal distribution and returns what the corresponding z-score or t-score is at that point on the normal distribution.</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fksla74foumq7mf%2Fe6a6a07a16c47336f367c18a961886fa89185d7ab1c0ad8a406e9bda081b1bd1%2Fconfidence_int.png' width='700' height='353' alt='' /></p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Problem 3 Q3', 'timestamp': '2023-02-18T20:07:41Z', 'user': 'l6mapnjrz9s7m1', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 138}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I tried every possible combination yet still not getting a proper number for minimum sample size. Would appreciate any help!</p><p></p><p>#################################</p><p>For Homework 5 Q2 Problem 2 I get</p><p></p><p>Problem 2 Answers:<br /><kbd>sample size = 990</kbd><br /><kbd>sample mean = 7.9144</kbd><br /><kbd>standard deviation = 1.530037452188851</kbd><br /><kbd>standard error = 0.0486</kbd><br /><kbd>z-score = -1.7594</kbd><br /><kbd>p-value = 0.0785</kbd></p><blockquote><p>which are all correct according to the provided writeup answer key.</p></blockquote><p>and for problem 3 I get</p><p></p><p>Problem 3 Answers:<br /><kbd>largest standard error = 0.04359817489632101</kbd><br /><kbd>minimum sample size = 1231.593830472441</kbd></p><p></p><pre>######## code for question 2 ###########print(&#39;&#39;)#new lineprint(&#39;Problem 2 Answers:&#39;)# code below this line#sample sizen = len(data1)print(&#39;sample size =&#39;, n)#sample meanmean = sum(data1) / nprint(&#39;sample mean =&#39;, round(mean, 4))#standard errorstd = np.std(data1, ddof=1) #standard deviationstd_error = std / m.sqrt(n)#print(&#39;standard deviation =&#39;, std) #debug lineprint(&#39;standard error =&#39;, round(std_error, 4))#z scorez_score = (mean - 8) / std_error #z = (x - mu) / SEprint(&#39;z-score =&#39;, round(z_score, 4))#p-valuep = 2 * stats.norm.cdf(-abs(z_score))print(&#39;p-value =&#39;, round(p, 4))######## code for question 3 ###########print(&#39;&#39;)#new lineprint(&#39;Problem 3 Answers:&#39;)# code below this line#new z scoreznew = stats.t.ppf((1-0.95)/2,n-1)#largest standard errorlse = (mean-8) / znewprint(&#39;largest standard error =&#39;, round(lse,4))#corresponding minimum sample sizemss = (std/lse)**2print(&#39;minimum sample size =&#39;, round(mss,4))</pre> Answer: <p>To find the z-score (znew), you should be using stats.norm.ppf, not stats.t.ppf.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW5.3.2 - Code', 'timestamp': '2023-02-18T19:45:09Z', 'user': 'k80ltc9fklk327', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 14}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Hi,</p><p>I&#39;m not sure if the grades of the homework are released. I checked on brightspace and there&#39;s not grades at all for any of my homework. Though I&#39;m pretty sure I uploaded all my work to github and matches the test cases too. Or I might check it at the wrong place?</p> Answer: <p>Try submitting a regrade request. Your github username may not have been properly linked to your brightspace username on our end.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['other'], 'title': 'HW grades', 'timestamp': '2023-02-18T19:28:43Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['other', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 14}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>In the Spring 2022 Exam 1, what would happen if we used L instead of mL for the calculation of the z-score? Would that answer still be technically correct?</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fksi8k0dd7bh6fe%2F3aedb43302f8138b7e07e2ab5988a65a1f4d170abd8e3ed347dbceb3a614f574%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' width='532' height='437' /></p> Answer: <p>Z-scores are unitless, so I think the standard deviation&#39;s units  and means&#39; units would also have to change. And the z-score would remain the same.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'units in z-score calculation', 'timestamp': '2023-02-18T19:18:55Z', 'user': 'ksi8k0dd7bh6fe', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 119}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb4gjv4bi54q%2F6deedcd4ada03f0f4dae316fac4318cdb50bb829341c3d63f6ba9cca2db98ede%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p><p>For this question here, I am not sure if I&#39;m overthinking it or not but for the part where it asks about how we know the shape, is it just as simple as stating that we plotted it hence by visual insepction we know the shape?</p> Answer: <p>Yes, they are asking for you to comment on the shape (hence the distribution) and mean (how you got that mean). Basically your thought process in answering the other questions.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Hw5 Problem 1', 'timestamp': '2023-02-18T18:38:45Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 161}),
	Document(content="""Question: Instead of 990, I am getting 1024 for the sample size of the first question problem 2. I think this is resulting is small differences for all the following answers. Can I get some idea on why this might be? Answer: The writeup_for_testcases pdf that got released has the answers for the datasets titled vehicle_survey_1_tescase, vehicle_survey_2_testcase, and vehicle_survey_3_testcase -which are completely different datasets from vehicle_survey_1, 2 &amp; 3. <div><br /></div><div>We didn’t release the writeup answers for the actual data that you’re supposed to use for your writeup that you’re turning in. </div>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Getting different sample size for problem 2', 'timestamp': '2023-02-18T07:19:17Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 147}),
	Document(content="""Question: <md>I am a bit confused as to what is being graded in hw5. Is it just the writeup? Or does the code have to follow a specific format as well?</md> Answer: <p>We will be grading both the write up and code. Make sure to write clear and legible code in order to produce the results you include in your writeup. The code just needs to backup your conclusions in the write up,</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Hw5 Grading', 'timestamp': '2023-02-18T04:21:55Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 161}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>For Homework 5 Q2 Problem 2 I get</p><p></p><p>Problem 2 Answers:<br /><kbd>sample size = 990</kbd><br /><kbd>sample mean = 7.9144</kbd><br /><kbd>standard deviation = 1.530037452188851</kbd><br /><kbd>standard error = 0.0486</kbd><br /><kbd>z-score = -1.7594</kbd><br /><kbd>p-value = 0.0785</kbd></p><blockquote><p>which are all correct according to the provided writeup answer key.</p></blockquote><p></p><p>and for problem 3 I get</p><p></p><p>Problem 3 Answers:<br /><kbd>largest standard error = 0.04359817489632101</kbd><br /><kbd>minimum sample size = 1231.593830472441</kbd></p><p></p><p>the largest standard error is correct yet my minimum sample size is a bit off.</p><p>Is this a mistake I am making or is it a tolerable error?</p> Answer: A sample size must be a whole number —you cannot have a fraction of a sample. <div><br /></div><div>To ensure you receive full credit, it’d be best to ensure your code matches the testcase outputs exactly, or at least are within .0001 for answers rounded to 4 decimal places.</div><div><br /></div><div>It may help to review the use of functions as described in the readme. Should this not help, you could try and make a private post only viewable by instructors with your code for problem 3.</div>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW5.2.3', 'timestamp': '2023-02-18T02:26:00Z', 'user': 'k80ltc9fklk327', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 154}),
	Document(content="""Question: Parts 4 and 5 of problem 2 contradict each other in regards to the oil changing sample and the not oil changing sample. Which sample is which? Or does it not really matter? Answer: The labels for the 4th part are the correct ones, but it also shouldn’t matter. """, meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW 5 Problem 2.4-5', 'timestamp': '2023-02-17T23:23:18Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 140}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Coulf I get some help understanding where I am going wrong when trying to calculate largest std error and sample size?<img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5gx345d2ba%2Fc98b9a04d08227bc2acfcfb7c1cfa85b421dc3dc40049ccd57c9cd49d1bff10a%2FScreen_Shot_2023-02-17_at_6.12.02_PM.png' alt='Screen_Shot_2023-02-17_at_6.12.02_PM.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <p>The largest error should be calculated by using values of the sample size which will change in the direction that makes the p value significant. Once you get a value that is just before it is significant, you have found the sample size and can find the error from it.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'hw5 prob2 part 3', 'timestamp': '2023-02-17T23:13:21Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 13}),
	Document(content="""Question: For largest standard error, is the value 0.0436? I have 0.04365, which rounds to 0.0437. Answer: <p>It is 0.04365159575910931, which rounds to 0.0437 with 4 decimal places.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW5 Test Cases Problem 2.3', 'timestamp': '2023-02-17T22:34:48Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 151}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Hello,</p><p>I was checking the output grading and saw these decimal errors. I was wondering if this was similar enough to the output that some credit could be given back, as the rounding error is only for those two output values, and all other values work. </p><p></p><p>Please let me know if there is anything I can do about that!</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb65z8f7y683%2F24b4e4e03cbcaffcfa7407892de76e5e537eae23669a50b710a0cc4b79a7bde1%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: I would file a regrade request""", meta={'folders': ['hw4'], 'title': 'Rounding Error Grading', 'timestamp': '2023-02-17T21:57:09Z', 'user': 'ktnb65z8f7y683', 'tags': ['hw4', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 15}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>They give you the standard deviation which makes me think that you should calculate a z score instead of a t score but they do not give you the population mean? so how do you calculate it?</p> Answer: Just like in parts 1 and 2, you are calculating a confidence interval, which does not involve hypotheses. The only difference between the 2nd and 3rd parts for problem 3 is the provided population standard deviation.<div><br /></div><div>When calculating confidence intervals, you use the confidence level to find the corresponding z or t score using norm.ppf or t.ppf. </div><div><br /></div><div>Use a z-score if the sample size is 30 or greater or you know the population standard deviation. Otherwise, use a t-score. </div>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Q3 part 3', 'timestamp': '2023-02-17T19:39:51Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 140}),
	Document(content="""Note: <p>Hi all, </p><p></p><p>Homework 4 grades have been released for all sections now. All students, can view their grading feedback in their Homework 4 repository on GitHub. To view your feedback, go to your Homework 4 repository on GitHub, click the drop down menu under &#39;main&#39; --&gt; click &#39;Tags&#39; --&gt; click &#39;graded-update.&#39; There will be a file called grading_output.txt in your repository with the output of the grading script specifying which test cases you passed and the number of points they were worth. See attached picture for reference. </p><p></p><p>Note that homeworks are generally graded using test cases. We run your code on a number of test cases (these test cases are visible to you in the grading_output.txt file) and assign points based on the test cases your code passes. Each test case is worth a different number of points depending on its difficulty. </p><p></p><p>If you believe an error has been made in grading, please send a regrade request to</p><p><a href='mailto:ece20875.purdue.university@gmail.com' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>ece20875.purdue.university@gmail.com</a>.<strong> You have one week from the day grades are posted to Brightspace to request a regrade.</strong> Remember to include the following information in your email:</p><ol><li>Relevant identifying information. For homeworks, a link to your GitHub repository is needed.</li><li>Section Number</li><li>Grading item (e.g., homework 4)</li><li>Purdue email (if not sent from a Purdue email)</li><li>Your reasoning or explanation for a regrade, with specific details and justification pointing to the README.</li></ol><p>When submitting an email for a regrade request please do the following:<br /><br />1. Have a <strong>separate email</strong> for each HW<br />2. Have the subject line be the following: <strong>HW# regrade request</strong></p><p></p><p>(it makes it a lot easier for us to filter the inbox and find your email). </p><p></p><p>As usual, feel free to post on Piazza with any additional questions :-)</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkskmxecspaq4i1%2F29ecacea51a4a28c76fdccf9e92b3d0f2742cc5124680fd7775cdcfef35c6f4b%2FHowToSeeFeedback.jpg' alt='How to see feedback on github' /></p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw4'], 'title': 'HW4 Grades Released', 'timestamp': '2023-02-17T18:21:48Z', 'user': 'kya7649uhal80', 'tags': ['hw4', 'instructor-note'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 124}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Could you please clarify the error tolerance for hw5?</p><p>Is our answers supposed to be the exact same to the last decimal point or some error is acceptable.</p><p></p><p>For example: (test cases)</p><p><kbd>If the answer key says:</kbd></p><pre>sample size = 990sample mean = 7.9144standard error = 0.0486z-score = -1.7593p-value = 0.0785</pre><p><kbd>but if i get</kbd></p><pre>z-score = -1.7594</pre><blockquote><p>is this acceptable?</p></blockquote> Answer: <p>Yes. We will allow an error tolerance of .0001<br /><br />However, in your case, there was no error. I had rounded incorrectly. The z-score should be -1.7594. Thank you for bringing this up.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Error Tolerance for HW5', 'timestamp': '2023-02-17T17:55:38Z', 'user': 'k80ltc9fklk327', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 168}),
	Document(content="""Note: <p>Hi Class,</p><p></p><p>I apologize, Problem 2 Question 5 Standard Score answer was missing a negative sign. The answer for the test case should be -1.4113 instead of 1.4113. I have uploaded the corrected document to the previous piazza post and Brightspace, but wanted to make sure the word got out so I am creating this new post.  <br /><br />also attached here is the fixed solution that has the negative sign:<br /><br /><a href='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkskmxecspaq4i1%2F5bac61a7c9da3c0f03d052a01fa8336c46bf20c3ebc1139124574861eb9434e1%2FWriteup_for_testcases_fixed.pdf' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>Writeup_for_testcases_fixed.pdf</a><br /><br />Best of luck on the assignment<br /><br />Jason Toberman GTA</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW5 Test Case Solution Fix (missing negative sign)', 'timestamp': '2023-02-17T16:04:59Z', 'user': 'kskmxecspaq4i1', 'tags': ['hw5', 'instructor-note'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 189}),
	Document(content="""Note: <p>Hi Class,</p><p></p><p>I have created test case data so that you can verify your code for HW5 for problems 2 and 3. <br /><br />For problem 2, attached are .txt files that you can put in the same directory (folder) for HW5. They are:</p><p></p><p><a href='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkskmxecspaq4i1%2F121e1196b3dea2cdbe8bf3b82fdcf530f85d3913733a44927f85236c36d996e1%2Fvehicle_survey_1_testcase.txt' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>vehicle_survey_1_testcase.txt</a></p><p><a href='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkskmxecspaq4i1%2F71b9d96295b2e4bf4689bbb705f6a9a8c865821465c0c2c5e62641c176c61b4e%2Fvehicle_survey_2_testcase.txt' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>vehicle_survey_2_testcase.txt</a></p><p><a href='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkskmxecspaq4i1%2F024364ffc688eab54afbe7fcedf228a7f06fe32d1098a2bb0f79856d61bf0303%2Fvehicle_survey_3_testcase.txt' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>vehicle_survey_3_testcase.txt</a></p><p></p><p>(To easily download the files from piazza, right-click on the file and then select (&#34;save link as&#34;)). </p><p>To run the test case you will need to change the line of code that selects what file you are opening. For example: <br /><br /></p><pre>myFile = open(&#39;vehicle_survey_1.txt&#39;)</pre><p>will need to be changed to </p><p></p><pre>myFile = open(&#39;vehicle_survey_1_testcase.txt&#39;)</pre><p>to run the test case for Parts 1-3 for problem 2. Be sure to change it back to the original when generating your homework answers!</p><p></p><p>For Problem 3, use the following line of code to input the testcase data:<br /><br /></p><pre>data = np.array([199.7, 202.2,201.1,201.7,200.3,203.7,203.9,202.0,202.9,201.2,201.8,203.6,200.9])</pre><p><br />Use this instead of the given line of code (I would recommend commenting it out and then uncommenting it when you are ready to find your answers to the HW</p><p></p><p>I also have attached a .pdf that contains the answers to the testcase:<br /><br /><a href='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkskmxecspaq4i1%2F5bac61a7c9da3c0f03d052a01fa8336c46bf20c3ebc1139124574861eb9434e1%2FWriteup_for_testcases_fixed.pdf' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>Writeup_for_testcases_fixed.pdf</a><br /><br /><strong>To be clear this is not answers to the HW</strong>, this is that answers with the testcase data. <em>The HW you will turn in requires you to use the data that was given to you from the github assignment. </em><br /><br /></p><p>If you have already completed the assignment, I applaud you! Way to go! If you want to have more confidence in your existing submission, you can run the test case with your existing code. If you get the answers in the test case document, you are good to go. If not, you can make changes to your code, push your new solution to github and enter a new submission of your corrected Writeup.pdf to Gradescope. <br /><br /><br />If you have any questions, please ask over piazza. Best of luck to all of you on this assignment. I hope this helps!<br /><br />Jason Toberman GTA</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW5 Test Cases', 'timestamp': '2023-02-17T13:51:59Z', 'user': 'kskmxecspaq4i1', 'tags': ['hw5', 'instructor-note'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 203}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Is there any way to find the largest standard error in which the test will be significant at a level of 0.05 without using brute force?</p> Answer: <p>You know what the p-value is for this based on the alpha level and can then find the correct z-score and then the correct standard error from the z-score.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Problem 2 Question3', 'timestamp': '2023-02-17T02:44:57Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 150}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I was just wondering if we could have some virtual office hours over the weekend for Homework 5. It would be very helpful, but I understand if it isn&#39;t possible.</p> Answer: There will not be any weekend office hours, so I encourage you to visit office hours tomorrow if you need assistance.<div><br /></div><div>Should you need help over the weekend, you can still make a Piazza post and ask for help here.</div>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Weekend Office Hours', 'timestamp': '2023-02-17T02:16:20Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 129}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>To calculate standard error, when should we use $$\frac{\sigma^{2}}{n}$$ and when should we use $$\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}$$?</p> Answer: SE = σ/√n by definition. So you should use that.""", meta={'folders': ['other'], 'title': 'standard error', 'timestamp': '2023-02-17T01:45:34Z', 'user': 'ksi8k0dd7bh6fe', 'tags': ['other', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 114}),
