	Document(content="""Question: <p>Is there a reason why we still have a 0 for hw3?</p> Answer: <p>Details in Note @194 - sorry for the confusion!</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'Homework Grading', 'timestamp': '2023-02-16T17:11:38Z', 'user': 'ktnb4qz9lfe6ks', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 6, 'views': 133}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb6r8fak81te%2F5be1cf4cc201452ef6c481048a90231a6b5da97a856d023596e1e133107e41a1%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p> Answer: You need to calculate t or z using norm.ppf or t.ppf when you’re finding confidence intervals. """, meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW 5 Q3 How do we know what mu is?', 'timestamp': '2023-02-16T17:04:38Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 167}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I have two questions:</p><p></p><p>For problem 3 Question 1, is the t_c = stats.t.ppf(1 - (1-c)/2, df) function used to find the confidence interval? Is the number supposed to be between 0 and 100? Does this mean a percentage value is output?</p><p></p><p>How do you find the t-score? I saw this equation from the powerpoint, but it has a population mean which we were not given. How should I approach this problem? </p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fl6maptmggzy7op%2F845ebc8907ad557d24401f4a043f483ebf4ed4fd5ad7cf75525c8476acc3a1f1%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' width='228' height='56' /></p><p></p><p>Thank you</p> Answer: <p>For this question, you use should the equation t_c = stats.t.ppf(1-(1-c)/2, df) to find the t-score to use for the confidence interval. c = confidence level given, and you divide by two in the equation for t_c since you are finding a two-sided confidence interval. df = degrees of freedom = sample size - 1.</p><p></p><p>The confidence interval equation is (x - t_c*SE, x &#43; t_c *SE) where x=sample mean, SE=standard error, and t_c is found in the earlier equation.</p><p></p><p>t_c can have any value from -infinity to &#43;infinity because it represented the standardized number of standard deviations that the sample is from the population mean.</p><p></p><p>The confidence level c is what should have a value from 0-100% in percentile form and 0-1 in decimal form. For that formula, we are working with probabilities, and hence, should use the decimal form of c.</p><p></p><p>The confidence interval that is returned should be a range with a lower and upper bound.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Problem 3 Question 1', 'timestamp': '2023-02-15T23:11:10Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 164}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>When finding t using stats.t.ppf, should the second argument be size - 1 as the degrees of freedom or 1?</p> Answer: <p>If I understand your question correctly, the second parameter in stats.t.ppf should be the degrees of freedom, which for a t-test is always n - 1, where n = the sample size.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW 5 Prob 3 Steps 1 &amp; 2', 'timestamp': '2023-02-15T21:03:06Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 159}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>When it asks for the standard error, z score, and p score, how do we compute those with two data sets to get one answer?</p> Answer: The picture shows the equation for the z-score for a two-sample z-test. This should also be in the slide set for hypothesis testing. The denominator is the standard error.<img src='https://piazza.com/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fksla74foumq7mf%2F15d8cba1c078f81e267d37c8b9c31f83dc57edaba1ab1e611ca05f334ed06812%2Ftwo_samp_z_test.png' /><p></p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW 5 #2 pt 3', 'timestamp': '2023-02-15T20:47:25Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 162}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>When calculating the standard score in problem 3 for the confidence interval, what are we supposed to use in our calculation for mu since there is no given population mean? Is this something we don&#39;t account for when calculating confidence intervals? </p><p></p><p>Thank you.</p> Answer: You find the z-score or t-score for a confidence interval from the confidence level you are given. The equation shown in the slide below for z_c is for two sided confidence intervals <img src='https://piazza.com/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=attach%2Flcj9rez4czg6zj%2Fksla74foumq7mf%2Fqswyodwgekqi%2Fpublic_2023_02_15.jpeg' /><p></p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Problem 3 - confidence interval', 'timestamp': '2023-02-15T19:58:00Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 155}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I am getting a really low minimum sample size of 1.17.... is that reasonable?</p><p>Code is below </p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb6r8fak81te%2F5e0e4b2183311765d0fffb6ea579150845cf6afcb55572ccb2d80494b2c87b89%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <p>The calculation of z_c is slightly off. Think again about what the p-value should be exactly if the alpha value is 0.05 and you are conducting a two-sided z-test.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW 5 #2 pt 2', 'timestamp': '2023-02-15T19:11:01Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 12}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>How are we supposed to plot the PDF of the function? Right now I basically create 2000 values from x = [-1,1] and create a histogram with these values, using a large number of bins, which yields an unusual looking curve.</p><p></p><p>Is this the right approach?</p> Answer: <p>You can do this for x in range of -1,1 for the given function</p><p></p><p>this is as standard as it gets when plotting;</p><p></p><pre>x = np.linspace(-1, 1, 100)y = [f(i) for i in x]</pre><p></p><p>edit: make sure you are considering both conditions</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW 5 Prob 1', 'timestamp': '2023-02-15T18:58:51Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 177}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I couldn&#39;t find any documentation on scipy website on conducting a two sample z test. Would the following approach be correct?</p><pre>#standard errorse = np.sqrt((std1**2 / len(data1)) &#43; (std2**2 / len(data2))) #z-scorez_score = (mean1 - mean2) / se #p-valuep_value = 2 * stats.norm.sf(abs(z_score))</pre><p></p> Answer: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fksla74foumq7mf%2F15d8cba1c078f81e267d37c8b9c31f83dc57edaba1ab1e611ca05f334ed06812%2Ftwo_samp_z_test.png' width='718' height='296' alt='' /></p><p>@189 also asked about this. The above equation is for the z-score when conducting a two-sample z-test. This should also be in the hypothesis testing slide set.</p><p></p><p>Your approach works as long as your variables std1 and std2 are just the standard deviations of the datasets and not the standard errors. Also, make sure to use the cdf and ppf functions in the readme, not stats.norm.sf.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'two-sample z-test', 'timestamp': '2023-02-15T18:45:53Z', 'user': 'k80ltc9fklk327', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 10}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>When computing z score is it</p><p>1)</p><div><pre># compute z = (x - mu) / SEz_score = (8 - mean) / std_error</pre></div><p>or</p><p>2)</p><pre># compute z = (mu - x) / SEz_score = (mean - 8) / std_error</pre><p>Slides say 1 but then the z score ends up being negative.</p> Answer: <p>x (or x bar) should be the mean of the sample you are given, and mu should be the population mean. So, here mu should be 8, not x.</p><p></p><p>The first equation is the equation for z-score shown in the slides. </p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fksla74foumq7mf%2Fdca351dac0b6f27c6ab739d4de124c124f485179a49dc951a6e5f92ae3dabe43%2Fzscore_calc.png' width='920' height='837' alt='' /></p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'z-score', 'timestamp': '2023-02-15T17:11:20Z', 'user': 'k80ltc9fklk327', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 162}),
