	Document(content="""Note: <p>Hi Class!<br />We have decided to extend the due date for Homework 5 to February 19th (Sunday) at 11:59pm. Please take advantage of this extra time to ensure that you submit high-quality work.<br /><br style='font-style:normal;font-weight:400' />As a reminder, this assignment requires part of your submission to be submitted on <b style='font-style:normal'>Gradescope</b>. Please ensure that you have have access to <b style='font-style:normal'>Gradescope</b>. If you have any issues, please feel free to contact the lead GTAs.<br /><br style='font-style:normal;font-weight:400' />As usual, for those who need additional help, virtual lab hours are hosted on Discord from Tuesday to Friday between 9-11am ET, 1-2pm ET, and 5-8pm ET.  Additionally, in-person lab hours are hosted on Tuesday to Friday from 5-8pm ET in BHEE 206 (primary) and 207 (overflow), with a maximum of 10 people per half hour slot.<br /><br style='font-style:normal;font-weight:400' />Please do not hesitate to contact us if you have any questions or concerns. Good luck with the assignment.<br /><br />Homework 5 Link:<br style='font-style:normal;font-weight:400' /><a target='_blank' href='https://classroom.github.com/a/isS6ulqu' style='text-decoration:none;font-style:normal;font-weight:400' rel='noopener noreferrer'>https://classroom.github.com/a/isS6ulqu</a></p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW5 Due Date Extension', 'timestamp': '2023-02-15T15:44:02Z', 'user': 'kskmx82xa2s4ad', 'tags': ['hw5', 'instructor-note'], 'likes': 5, 'views': 184}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>My HW3 grade was released as 0/100 but I&#39;m fairly certain that my code passes the test cases provided. Are the grades final, or is it released as 0 because it is ungraded?</p> Answer: Please, kindly request a regrade, then I&#39;ll look into it. Thanks!<div>Sorry about that. </div>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'HW3 grading', 'timestamp': '2023-02-15T14:11:16Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 8, 'views': 172}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>For the standard error when comparing two samples, do I simply input the difference between the standard errors for the two populations?</p> Answer: <p>You&#39;re not using the difference of the standard errors of the two samples. The standard error for two samples is the denominator in the instructor&#39;s answer in @177_f1. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW5 Prob 2 Part 5', 'timestamp': '2023-02-15T02:15:19Z', 'user': 'ktnb73hor9a3y6', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 155}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>In part 3 of Problem 2, how do I find the corresponding minimum sample size for which there is largest standard error?</p> Answer: <p>First find out the z score using the significance level, then use the formula that relates z score to SE to find out the value for SE. The last step is to use the formula for SE to calculate the corresponding sample size. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Hw 5 Problem 2', 'timestamp': '2023-02-15T01:24:25Z', 'user': 'ktnb6igyqfbch', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 156}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I am coding in VScode. I am currently using matplotlib.pyplot&#39;s functions plt.plot() and plt.show() in order to show the function given in part 1 ( I have correctly input the right X and Y values). However, upon running my code, nothing happens. After troubleshooting for an hour, it appears that this is because I was forced to use the matplotlib.use(&#39;agg&#39;) workaround for importing matplotlib. I have literally no idea how to force this plot to show, as I am unable to make any proper package installations because I am unable to upgrade the pip version on the scholar node I&#39;m working from. I have tried installing jupyter to run the code as a block in an interactive window, and I cannot install jupyter due to how old the pip version is. I am wondering how I could workaround this and display plots from code that is running in the scholar node.</p><p></p><p>Edit:</p><p>I created a test python file on my desktop and it showed the plot properly first try.</p><p>However, I am stilled worried that a future homework will expect a plot to be displayed, and I will simply be unable to do it on the remote server I have been given to write the homework programs on.</p> Answer: <p>A workaround could be to use</p><pre>plt.savefig(&#39;image.png&#39;) </pre><p>instead of</p><pre>plt.show()</pre><p>This saves the plot in your current directory which you can then view.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW5 Problem 1 Cannot Plot', 'timestamp': '2023-02-14T21:20:12Z', 'user': 'ktnb4n74agk61e', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 174}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I&#39;m a little confused about when you&#39;re supposed to use t-score or z-score. Online, I&#39;ve found several sources that say to use z-score either when you know the standard deviation or when you have a large sample size of over 30 points of data. However, I have also found a source that states that there is a historical misconception about t-score v. z-score, and that you should always use t-score whenever you don&#39;t know the standard deviation.</p><p></p><p>I&#39;ve checked the slides and everything, but can&#39;t find a definitive answer.</p><p></p><p>I am also a little confused on what to do for question 2 part 5 - I have found sample size, standard error, z-score, deviation, etc for both sets of data, but I&#39;m not sure how (or if I am supposed to at all) to compile it into one set of data to find the sample error, standard score, and p-score).</p> Answer: <p>You should use z test if the population&#39;s standard deviation is known or the number of samples is greater than 30. Use t test otherwise. </p><p></p><p>For your second question, you can use the z test for 2 samples. You can find the equation to calculate the values inside the slides. (Slide 15 &#34;Comparing two means&#34;) </p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW 5 T-Score versus Z-Score', 'timestamp': '2023-02-14T18:00:21Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 180}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I can&#39;t seem to find this pdf in brightspace or in the github assignment. Not sure where to find it.</p> Answer: <p>The Writeup.pdf would be in the GitHub repository once you have accepted the assignment<img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fke80y12ngei1tx%2F9135a1ef6fa23b5ee08de618d0d66d30b47d265532230fc65d221b181b17073c%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Writeup.pdf', 'timestamp': '2023-02-14T14:32:22Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 166}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>When finding the largest error, do we just use the equation for z score and just solve for SE, in this case do we use the same sample mean and null hypothesis of 8 as the population mean to find the largest SE? and for the corresponding min n, do we use the same standard deviation from before?</p> Answer: <p>You can find the largest z-score needed to be relevant in a confidence level of 0.05 online, then plug that value into the equation </p><p></p><p>z-score = (xbar - mu) / SE --&gt; SE = (xbar - mu) / z-score</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Finding largest Standard Error for problem 2', 'timestamp': '2023-02-14T10:33:05Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 156}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>When asking for the sample size, do we assume vehicle survey 1 is already the sample itself, or do we have to randomly sample from it?</p> Answer: <p>I think the survey is the sample itself. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'hw5 problem 2, sampling', 'timestamp': '2023-02-14T07:21:42Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 153}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>From the Jupyter notebook for hypothesis-testing-and-confidence-interval-demo in Week 5, to calculate the standard deviation of the sampling distribution (highlighted below), why do we need to set ddof (delta degrees of freedom) to 1? It is 0 by default.</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fksi8k0dd7bh6fe%2F1f4d3ca69a72df9518e645c821504598cfadb0819cf31904dd896790e95e976f%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' width='696' height='174' /></p> Answer: <p>ddof=1 provides an unbiased estimator of the variance of the infinite population. <br /><br />ddof=0 provides a maximum likelihood estimate of the variance for normally distributed variables</p>""", meta={'folders': ['other'], 'title': 'ddof for numpy.std', 'timestamp': '2023-02-13T15:59:17Z', 'user': 'ksi8k0dd7bh6fe', 'tags': ['other', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 119}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>For Problem 2, Question 5, are we supposed to compute the standard error, standard mean, and p_value for each the vehicle_survey_2 and vehicle_survey_3? And if so, how should we enter them into the pdf chart?</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fksi8ka1ba1t6tv%2F341f0477a8e0fd48df2de8773c12176695c2719ee1388c64201b663c4e62db1c%2FScreen_Shot_2023-02-12_at_5.29.42_PM.png' alt='Screen_Shot_2023-02-12_at_5.29.42_PM.pngNaN' /><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fksi8ka1ba1t6tv%2F34c03563fbad12ff5e3512920bed622e5cae0ca939941f69eedbc14a69feda47%2FScreen_Shot_2023-02-12_at_5.26.47_PM.png' alt='Screen_Shot_2023-02-12_at_5.26.47_PM.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: You will be calculating one standard error, standard score, and p-value here. Think about what test you are performing. """, meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW 5 Problem 2 Q5', 'timestamp': '2023-02-12T22:31:45Z', 'user': 'ksi8ka1ba1t6tv', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 13}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Is our code supposed to print out all of the values we calculate (sample size, mean, etc.)? If so, do we have to round the printed results to 4 decimal values as well?</p> Answer: <p>I don’t think they will be grading the code, it is just there to verify you actually did the work and not copy it off from someone.<br /><br />You can round it all yourself but its easier to make printed values rounded imo.</p><p></p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW5 Q2 printing/rounding results', 'timestamp': '2023-02-12T22:00:13Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 159}),
	Document(content="""Question: To calculate standard error, we need the population standard deviation. In this case, are we allowed to use the sample standard deviation to estimate it? Answer: <p>I would recommend taking a look at slide 8 in hypothesis.pdf it goes over when you don&#39;t know the population standard deviation. <br /><br />in regards to the previous student answer, you do not determine which test to use based on the standard deviation. Instead you should be looking at the size of the sample to make that determination. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW5 Q2', 'timestamp': '2023-02-12T02:32:29Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 167}),
	Document(content="""Question: What exactly does Y = -X mean? Is it just X but flipped over the x axis? Answer: <p>We are defining a new random variable Y from the random variable X such that whenever X takes the realization t, Y takes the realization -t. We write this as Y = -X. The given random variables have no notion of &#34;axes&#34; since we have not specified sample spaces. The graphs of the PDFs or CDFs of these random variables of course do have axes.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW5 Q1B', 'timestamp': '2023-02-12T02:13:05Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 176}),
