	Document(content="""Question: <p>Can I have some help on how to complete this part of problem 1. I am confused on how I should grab these samples, how to get the sample mean random variable, and how to plot it to get the shape.</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb7hcvqm46hd%2Fb6aa83a16c5f1d7ce5c99fc7ec8165505f7fffaebfa710ed16560e48e69a6459%2FScreen_Shot_2023-02-11_at_7.18.05_PM.png' alt='' /></p> Answer: <p>It is asking you to plot the probability density function that was given. When you see the plot of it, you should be able to recognize where the mean would lie<br /><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkskmxecspaq4i1%2F72bfea3cb6a1f201f939f8f922b928521605688a7cd33c5bf96f2ebe4630aca3%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Problem 1', 'timestamp': '2023-02-12T00:32:38Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 190}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I can&#39;t find where the population mean is for this question. Is it given? </p> Answer: <p>Good question, you are working with a sample. On the ReadMe given Writeup.pdf it states it is a sample, and that you are trying to find the sample mean. So you do not know the population of all your prototype robots. You do not know the population mean or population standard deviation<br /><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkskmxecspaq4i1%2F62f56f63226bfb9619ad0d1577567d7929adcf80a13abab488b9f43f1d19a013%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /><br /><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkskmxecspaq4i1%2F176e8c591c4c5497da3f0d7da57ef8ebef9a941ea860bf453bf448cdb2c6813c%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Problem 3 Q1 is population mean given?', 'timestamp': '2023-02-11T03:54:34Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 169}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>After finding the values for problem 2 question 2, it asks if the data is &#34;statistically significant&#34;. What does this mean? </p> Answer: <p>I would recommend reading slides 9 -&gt; 15 (Be better to go through all the slides) of the hypothesis.pdf</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Problem 2 how is &#34;statistically significant&#34;', 'timestamp': '2023-02-11T02:58:01Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 154}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>When I run a standard score analysis for both t and z test i get the same results. Does that mean either or can be used or am i making a mistake somewhere?</p><pre>#z-scorez_score = (mean - 8) / (std / m.sqrt(n))print(&#39;z-score =&#39;, z_score)#t scoret_score, p_value = stats.ttest_1samp(data1, 8)print(&#39;t-score =&#39;, t_score)</pre><p><kbd>z-score = 1.8541077276954554</kbd><br /><kbd>t-score = 1.8532021805216874</kbd></p> Answer: <p>Your updated number are correct. </p><p></p><p>As the degrees of freedom increase, Student’s t distribution becomes less leptokurtic, meaning that the probability of extreme values decreases. The distribution becomes more and more similar to a standard normal distribution. With such a large dataset, the distribution becomes very similar to the standard normal distribution (which is where the z score comes from). You can see that there is a very small difference between your two numbers. You however will need to decide which is the correct one and supply that reasoning. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW 5, Problem 2', 'timestamp': '2023-02-10T23:10:20Z', 'user': 'k80ltc9fklk327', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 12}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Are we allowed to use matplotlib in hw2 or we must stick to numpy and scipy?</p> Answer: <p>For problem 1, you can use matplotlib (your code for problem 1 is not graded, just your answers in Writeup.pdf)<br /><br />For problems 2 and 3, you will just need the libraries that are provided. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW5 Matplotlib', 'timestamp': '2023-02-10T21:41:19Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 4, 'views': 183}),
