	Document(content="""Note: <p>This note contains useful information on Exam 1, in the form of FAQ. Check here periodically for updates.<br /><br /><strong>When/where is the exam?</strong><br />Wednesday, February 22, 6:30-7:35 PM in <strong>two different rooms</strong>, as explained below: </p><ul><li>WTHR 200 --- Section 1 (Instructor: Mahsa Ghasemi) and Section 2 (Instructor: Qiang Qiu) </li><li>BHEE 129 --- Section 3 (Instructor: Murat Kocaoglu) and Section 4 (Instructor: Anuran Makur)</li></ul><p>We will check the collected exams to make sure you were in the correct room.</p><p><strong><br />Is the exam coordinated for all four sections?</strong><br />Yes.</p><p><strong><br />What will be on the exam?</strong><br />There will be about 6 questions, covering weeks 1-6 of the course. Some questions will be on Python coding (either writing code segments or interpreting output of code), and others will be on data science. You can expect questions covering the following topics:</p><p></p><ul><li>Python data structures (lists, tuples, sets, dictionaries)</li><li>Basic Python operations (e.g., loops, arithmetic, manipulating data structures)</li><li>Functions and higher order functions in Python</li><li>List comprehensions in Python</li><li>Histograms</li><li>Random variables and probability distributions</li><li>Sampling, the law of large numbers, and the central limit theorem</li><li>Hypothesis testing</li></ul><p><strong><br />What is the format/procedure of the exam?</strong></p><p>You will take this exam on printed paper with a pen/pencil, on an exam packet that we will provide to you. Your completed exam will be scanned and uploaded to Gradescope, which we will use for grading and returning the exams to you. We will be leveraging Purdue’s Instructional Data Processing to have your exams uploaded. As a result, <strong>it is critical that you follow the exact template we have provided in the exam packet</strong>. This includes (1) writing all of your work on the exact sheet of paper provided for each question, and (2) writing your name and PUID at the top of every question. To facilitate this, the first 5 minutes of the exam will be used solely to fill out your name/ID on each page.</p><p><strong><br />What materials am I allowed to bring?</strong><br />Computers/tablets/calculators/electronic devices are not allowed, but other than that, the exam is open notes. You may bring hard copies of anything on Brightspace and may bring handwritten notes. You can also bring printed notes, e.g., a printed copy of a notebook you created or a PDF of notes you created. You are also allowed to bring a reference book (such as a Python reference book); however, we discourage this because we expect that looking anything up in a book might waste a lot of your time and negatively affect your overall performance.</p><p><strong><br />What is the best way to study for the exam?</strong><br />Go through all the lecture notes thoroughly. Then make sure you are comfortable with how to do the homeworks that have been assigned so far. Finally, take the practice exams posted on Brightspace.</p><p><br />One suggestion is to create your own summary sheet / crib sheet that summarizes and synthesizes the lecture notes and/or homeworks. Often by creating something rather than merely looking at the notes, you will gain a deeper understanding of the material.</p><p><strong><br />Will you take off points for syntax errors?</strong><br />If the syntax error is trivial (e.g. missing a colon at the end of an if statement), we will only assess a minor penalty. If the syntax error is significant (e.g., you write a for loop without the “in” keyword or write a C-based for loop instead of Python for loop), we may assess more penalty because this may show a fundamental lack of understanding of the syntax.</p><p><strong><br />What if I have a DRC accommodation?</strong><br />Please schedule an exam with the DRC Testing Center, and email the instructor for your section if you have any questions. All other details will remain the same.</p><p></p><p><strong>Note: </strong>Students have until <strong>11:55 PM seven days before an exam</strong> to submit a request to the DRC Testing Center.</p><p><strong><br />Any other logistics to be aware of?</strong><br />There are not assigned seats during the exam, but you should leave one seat between you and the people on either side of you. <strong>Please try to arrive 10-15 min early</strong> to have enough time to find an appropriate seat. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Exam 1: FAQ', 'timestamp': '2023-02-07T20:31:41Z', 'user': 'ks3l0aykohs3yd', 'tags': ['exam', 'instructor-note', 'pin'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 392}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I understand a stencil function slides across a list, and whatever the result of the function is will get placed into a new list.</p><p></p><p>But for this function in Problem 2, it is taking the sum of all the data in the list and dividing it by 3. So where does the sliding/window of operation occurs? Wouldn&#39;t it produce the same number no matter how it is slid?</p><div><div><pre>def mov_avg(L):	return float(sum(L)) / 3</pre></div></div><p></p> Answer: <p>You are right about the fact that the function itself produces the same result given that the input remains the same. However, the way you utilize mov_avg to do a sliding window operation is that you change the input parameter (the list L). <br />Consider the snippet of code in Problem2.py from your homework file (lines 37 to 57). <br />If you look at lines 49 and 50, you see that the functions are passed in as the arguments for the stencil function. The sliding window operation will essentially be done in the stencil function. <br /><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fke80y12ngei1tx%2F5fd6c8b923d8fe3c78aeced572d77bb587aa68deb1d1e80f867f84410105988e%2Fimage.png' alt='Image snippet of code from Problem 2' width='644' height='542' /><br />What you want to do in the stencil function (as a reminder, the stencil function has the following parameters - data (the list under consideration), f (the filter function) and width (which is the width of the list that f will take in as its parameter)) is you take &#34;width&#34; number of elements at a time of a list and call the function on that snippet of the list and append that to the output of your stencil function. You keep going till you run out of elements.</p><p></p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw4'], 'title': 'HW4 Problem 2', 'timestamp': '2023-02-06T20:15:25Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw4', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 167}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I am working on problem 2 of homework 4, and am getting this error. Does anyone know what could be causing this? Thank you!</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fl6maptmggzy7op%2F65aaee447110d17b41cbab4f0fa10549624cf703b4e7f023aae4d76be01c2b76%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p><p></p><p>This is my code so far.</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fl6maptmggzy7op%2F29d6348a78603578847d7a426f85ce5e2423352e7ac2e140148bc02c785f1c41%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p> Answer: You&#39;re indexing f in the wrong way. It&#39;s supposed to be f[i] not f(i)""", meta={'folders': ['hw4'], 'title': 'Error in mov_avg function', 'timestamp': '2023-02-04T19:56:32Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw4', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 19}),
	Document(content="""Question: Its been a few weeks since HW1 was returned, and that is still a zero for me, and now HW2 is a zero. I got &gt;0 on github, so I don&#39;t know what the problem is. I filled out the form before the first day of class. Answer: Fill out a regrade request""", meta={'folders': ['hw1', 'hw2'], 'title': 'HW 1, 2 grades still zero', 'timestamp': '2023-02-04T18:21:09Z', 'user': 'klh98pfz6y127s', 'tags': ['hw1', 'hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 168}),
	Document(content="""Note: <p>Hi all, </p><p></p><p>Homework 2 grades have been released for all sections now. All students, can view their grading feedback in their Homework 2 repository on GitHub. To view your feedback, go to your Homework 2 repository on GitHub, click the drop down menu under &#39;main&#39; --&gt; click &#39;Tags&#39; --&gt; click &#39;graded-update.&#39; There will be a file called grading_output.txt in your repository with the output of the grading script specifying which test cases you passed and the number of points they were worth. See attached picture for reference. </p><p></p><p>Note that homeworks are generally graded using test cases. We run your code on a number of test cases (these test cases are visible to you in the grading_output.txt file) and assign points based on the test cases your code passes. Each test case is worth a different number of points depending on its difficulty. </p><p></p><p>If you believe an error has been made in grading, please send a regrade request to</p><p><a href='mailto:ece20875.purdue.university@gmail.com' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>ece20875.purdue.university@gmail.com</a>.<strong> You have one week from the day grades are posted to Brightspace to request a regrade.</strong> Remember to include the following information in your email:</p><ol><li>Relevant identifying information. For homeworks, a link to your GitHub repository is needed.</li><li>Section Number</li><li>Grading item (e.g., homework 2)</li><li>Purdue email (if not sent from a Purdue email)</li><li>Your reasoning or explanation for a regrade, with specific details and justification pointing to the README.</li></ol><p>When submitting an email for a regrade request please do the following:<br /><br />1. Have a <strong>separate email</strong> for each HW<br />2. Have the subject line be the following: <strong>HW# regrade request</strong></p><p></p><p>(it makes it a lot easier for us to filter the inbox and find your email). </p><p></p><p>As usual, feel free to post on Piazza with any additional questions :-)<br /><br /><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkskmxecspaq4i1%2F29ecacea51a4a28c76fdccf9e92b3d0f2742cc5124680fd7775cdcfef35c6f4b%2FHowToSeeFeedback.jpg' alt='How to see feedback on github' /></p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'HW2 Grades Released', 'timestamp': '2023-02-04T16:58:54Z', 'user': 'kya7649uhal80', 'tags': ['hw2', 'instructor-note'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 141}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>It says compute_j needs to output the list of probabilities and the number of samples. Are these quantities supposed to be printed to the screen? </p> Answer: A list of probabilities and the number of samples can be calculated in norm_hist for use in compute_j. No printing is necessary — compute j’s only output should be its return of the j value.""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'Question About compute_j', 'timestamp': '2023-02-04T03:18:04Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 118}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>My compute_j function is outputting for the test case:</p><p>-0.024869412406267666</p><p></p><p>I wrote this code as many different ways I could think and am very unsure where I am going wrong. My code for compute_j is:</p><p></p><p> # generating list of probabilities and total count (m)<br />    probs, m = norm_histogram(histo)</p><p> sum_s = 0</p><p>    for x in probs:<br />        j &#43;= 2/(width*(m-1))-((x**2)*(m&#43;1)/(width*(m-1)))</p><p></p><p>and im calling it in my sweep_n function as:</p><p> hist_list = np.histogram(data)<br />    #print(hist_list)</p><p>    # tuple unpacking<br />    hist, bins = hist_list</p><p>    print(hist)</p><p>    # computing error<br />    compute_j(hist, ((maximum - minimum) / len(hist)))</p><p></p><p>Thank you</p> Answer: As of right now, I believe you are adding the first term (2/((m-1)w)) to your j result each time through the for loop—in effect multiplying it by the number of bins.<div><br /></div><div>As seen in the formula, this term should only contribute to your j value once.</div>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'compute_j function outputting close but wrong result', 'timestamp': '2023-02-04T03:08:45Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 17}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Compute_j function is outputting -0.024869412406267666 for the test case. I retyped this and tried everything for hours and it is the only part of my code that does not work. Any suggestions on what to try? I tried everything I have seen on piazza so far. My parameters seem right, please help. </p> Answer: If you haven’t already, look at @139. If this does not help, you can try making a private post only visible to instructors with your compute_j function.""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'compute_j function not working', 'timestamp': '2023-02-04T03:02:14Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 106}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I am getting about -0.02592834145089025 and the README says it should be -0.025857288773526013. Is this close enough?</p> Answer: I would recommend comparing your formula to the one in the slides. Two common issues I have noticed were  multiplying both terms by the sum of squared probabilities, and not using enough parentheses to ensure  width is also present in your denominators.""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'Do the numbers for testbin.py need to be exactly the same?', 'timestamp': '2023-02-04T02:49:02Z', 'user': 'ktnb66os5wv6bv', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 98}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fke7n72og51t1mt%2F0461f82aabb1adcb82c509cfa8ace7f5caa9bf251f58ea19a1fd327c096f662d%2FScreenshot_2023-02-03_214013.png' width='567' height='172' alt='' /></p><p>For some reason my output doesn&#39;t include &#39;norm&#39;, does anybody know why this might be?</p> Answer: I would recommend tracing the string “norm” throughout the program — it should be with the other distribution types. If this does not work, consider posting your problem 2 file in a private post that only instructors can see.<div><br /></div><div>Edit: glad to see it worked out</div>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'Not getting &#34;norm&#34; in p2 output', 'timestamp': '2023-02-04T02:40:58Z', 'user': 'ke7n72og51t1mt', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 87}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I&#39;m stuck on find_dist function.</p><p>From README, I thought sum_err is list with sum of squared distances.</p><p>But I see list inside the list.</p><p>Do I have to sum up the items in the list?<img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fk81v37lankw24g%2Fe0e2e9ae880c1acf82ac4f9fb7025bf094400702c425e4c712e50bf52c4d96f4%2FScreenshot_2023-02-03_at_21.08.43.png' width='836' height='90' alt='' /></p> Answer: I believe sum_err should simply be a list of floats. If it is not in your code, consider checking over your get coordinates and calculate distance functions.""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'sum_err list of lists', 'timestamp': '2023-02-04T02:11:55Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 81}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I am getting an error that says what I pass into dists.index() must be a tuple but the documentation says it can be any element. Any idea what&#39;s wrong?</p> Answer: The .index function returns the index of the parameter passed to .index within a list.<div><br /></div><div>For example:</div><div><br /></div><div>If nums = [1, 3, 4, 8, 12]</div><div>nums.index(4) = 2</div><div><br /></div><div>I’m not sure exactly what your issue is without looking at it, but hopefully this helps you troubleshoot.</div>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'dists.index error', 'timestamp': '2023-02-03T22:20:00Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 88}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I get this using probplot numpy.core._exceptions._UFuncNoLoopError: ufunc &#39;add&#39; did not contain a loop with signature matching types (dtype(&#39;float64&#39;), dtype(&#39;&lt;U4&#39;)) -&gt; None</p> Answer: <p>I had this issue as well. I would check out @120. I believe the problem is with your second parameter for stats.probplot. You should be passing &#34;dist = each_dist&#34; for the second parameter</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'H3 Problem 2 probplot', 'timestamp': '2023-02-03T21:39:12Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 3, 'views': 99}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>We are asked to put an error message &#34;Calling box filter with the wrong length list. Expected length of list should be n.&#34; when the list length is not the same. Should we put the message inside of the box_filter function definition? But in this case wouldn&#39;t the error message be displayed multiple times in the stencil function? </p> Answer: <p>The error message should be in the box_filter function definition.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw4'], 'title': 'Where should the error message be placed in HW4 Q2', 'timestamp': '2023-02-03T19:55:10Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw4', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 128}),
	Document(content="""Note: <p>Hi Class!<br />Homework 4 has been released on GitHub classroom. Please use the link in the post to accept the assignment and get started with the homework for the course. Note that Homework 4 is due on the 10th of February at 11:59pm. Moreover, you can also take benefit of the TA lab hours (in-person and virtual) to get help for the current and all future homeworks.<br /><br />Homework 4: https://classroom.github.com/a/nhfDoEd4<br /><br />*Follow the link, you will get access to the homework. The homework will provide instructions on how to submit the homework. This class does not have the students added the github classroom. <b>Use the same github account that you documented in the git hub user google form survey!</b><br />TA Lab Hours Info:<br />Virtual lab hours (Discord): T-F 9-11 am ET, 1-2 pm ET, and 5-8 pm ET. Discord link: <b><a target='_blank' href='https://discord.gg/vU94QaeacS' rel='noopener noreferrer'>https://discord.gg/vU94QaeacS</a></b><br />Limited in-person lab hours (maximum of 10 people per half hour slot) :<br />BHEE 206 (primary - go here first) &amp; 207 (overflow) T-F 5pm-8pm ET<br /><br /></p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw4'], 'title': 'H4 Released', 'timestamp': '2023-02-03T18:15:27Z', 'user': 'ksla74foumq7mf', 'tags': ['hw4', 'instructor-note'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 278}),
