	Document(content="""Question: <p>For some reason I can&#39;t import numpy even though when I used the install command again it says that the requirement is already satisfied and that I have it downloaded. </p> Answer: <p>This could happen for a number of reasons, some might be that you have multiple versions of Python on your personal computer/PATH issues.</p><p></p><p>You could try </p><pre>python3 -mpip install numpy </pre><p>as the first step.<br />On another note, you can work on the homework on eceprog instead of on your personal computer</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'No module named &#39;numpy&#39;', 'timestamp': '2023-02-03T04:09:39Z', 'user': 'jzhn3s65vjd4by', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 127}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>For some reason I suddenly couldn&#39;t log into my remote ssh. It keeps telling me to retype my password. Everything was working alright until I tried to log in today. Does anyone have any idea how to fix this?</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5b8oexj1jg%2Fee9dd8474518e597bdced3ce4fb829d60493f7f91cc90240b298b785be65fa2c%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p><p></p><p>When I try to reestablish the server connection, I got into this error</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5b8oexj1jg%2F583eb01333d55aeabc906cbce7766860d78504f2006d1a10fb4988dce43d6a79%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <p>If you press Ctrl &#43; Shift &#43; P and search for Remote-SSH: Settings, there is a connection timeout setting. If you extend that time, it may fix the issue because this setting times you out if it can&#39;t connect you with the computer in 15 seconds (default). This may fix your issue but if it doesn&#39;t, you can try connecting to a different ECN computer.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['logistics'], 'title': 'Cannot log into my ssh', 'timestamp': '2023-02-03T03:57:22Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['logistics', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 90}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb4k37vlk5k5%2F57d0f1f73be212100c3f7ba844cade3ca59f5433a10023b00d922a89eb91729a%2FScreen_Shot_2023-02-02_at_10.39.19_PM.png' width='461' height='382' alt='' /></p><p></p><p>I tried installing sciPy but none of the troubleshooting tips seem to help. Can you please advise? </p> Answer: <p>One solution would be to SSH into one of the ECN computers (such as eceprog.ecn.purdue.edu) to work on the code. If you are using VSCode, there is an SSH extension so that you can use VSCode to access all files and work on your code.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'unable to install scipy on mac', 'timestamp': '2023-02-03T03:42:44Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 91}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I&#39;m confused on what this question is asking for. What is the error that we are supposed to return?</p> Answer: <p>What Q2 is trying to do is get datapoints from each file and see how closely they fit to different distributions. Since no real dataset fits perfectly to a distribution, there will be a difference (distance) in the actual datapoint and the respective point in the distribution,. The error that is being referred to is the sum of squares of the differences of each datapoint. After getting the error for each distribution, the distribution with the minimum error is selected as closest fit distribution and returned</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'HW3 Q2 find_dist', 'timestamp': '2023-02-02T23:02:42Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 104}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>In the sweep_n function how do we determine the width and what parameters should we create the histogram with?</p> Answer: <p>The purpose of sweep_n is to test all potential widths in the range min_bins to max_bins. These values, along with the other necessary variables to make a histogram, are given to you as input parameters for sweep_n.</p><p></p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'HW3 prob 1', 'timestamp': '2023-02-02T22:42:18Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 110}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>So I&#39;m trying to return the array from the sweep_n function, and no matter what I do, it keeps returning &#34;none&#34;. What can I do to fix it?</p> Answer: My initial guess is that you initialize something to be empty, so then you don’t actually properly fill up the list/tuple/wtv. Either initialize as 0 or use the .append() function to fill in the values""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'HW3', 'timestamp': '2023-02-02T22:24:01Z', 'user': 'l8au993a2bs71z', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 110}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Can we assume that all the values given in the test cases are valid? Or would we have to check if for example the bin number was negative? </p> Answer: <p>I&#39;m pretty sure all test cases they give us would be valid. If they wanted us to check for possible invalids they would tell us like with homework 2 when we had to swap min and max vals if min was larger.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'Hw 3, valid inputs', 'timestamp': '2023-02-02T22:04:17Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 97}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I&#39;m unsure what the get coordinates function is supposed to return for us. All my attempts at making mine have resulting in my (x, y) tuple having x and y be long lists of floats. Do we need to add/average them in some way to make it usable in other functions like calculate_distance()?</p> Answer: <p>I figured it out. In case anyone else was wondering, yes the xy tuple is supposed to be a list, I was simply indexing improperly which made the IDE consider it non-iterable</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'HW3 Problem 2 - get_coordinates() question', 'timestamp': '2023-02-02T21:37:30Z', 'user': 'k83r1y8tdcp38c', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 100}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Can someone clarify what we are supposed to do with matplotlip.pyplot.hist in sweep_n? I&#39;m not sure why this is needed or what the output should look like</p> Answer: <p>So, n refers to the number of bins. In sweep_n, you will sweep the number of bins from the min_bins to max_bins and calculate j values. Then, return a list of j values. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'sweep_n plot', 'timestamp': '2023-02-02T21:01:51Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 103}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb6r8fak81te%2F15abae6ae0a5d0fd3667eebce595a13691c2c7628d51f6af60b6a93b326765b3%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p><p></p><p>I have this error. I think it is an issue with my parameters for the stats.probplot function, but do not know what...</p> Answer: <p>If you look at the documentation for stats.probplot, this is the definition of the function: </p><p></p><pre>scipy.stats.probplot(x, sparams=(), dist=&#39;norm&#39;, fit=True, plot=None, rvalue=False)</pre><p>When you call the function in the way you do with stats.probplot(data, each_dist), Python assumes that each_dist corresponds to the parameter s_params() (which is a tuple of parameters that are specific to shape of a distribution). In this function, you do not know those parameters, but you know the name of the distribution (which is what each_dist is). Therefore, the correct function call to stats.probplot will be: </p><pre>stats.probplot(data, dist = each_dist)</pre>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'error on #2 hw 3', 'timestamp': '2023-02-02T20:55:35Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 111}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Can you use import math for the sqrt function for problem 2 for HW 3?</p> Answer: <p>Yes!</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'Import Math', 'timestamp': '2023-02-02T20:49:18Z', 'user': 'ksi8k4cpa9y6m5', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 100}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>As data is not processed in function sweep_n should we compute the count list of this data?</p> Answer: Yes. sweep n will call compute j, and as such it must have a list of counts and width to pass as parameters.""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'Hmw 3 ex1.3', 'timestamp': '2023-02-02T18:11:32Z', 'user': 'lcrzmj6nzh1w6', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 98}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I am confused when sweep_j mentions a min_bin and max_bin variable.... how do we find those values and how do we determine the range we perform sweep_j for? </p> Answer:  Min and max bins are two of the parameters of your function. <div>Your range would be from min to max, but you also need to add one (because for example, 0 -&gt; 4 is 5 numbers, but 4-0=4)</div>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'finding max', 'timestamp': '2023-02-02T02:43:29Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 101}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Should we assigned a specific name to the tuple returned on the first function?</p><p>On the second function what is parameter histo, the count list, the tuple of function one or other input?</p> Answer: norm_histogram merely has to return a tuple as specified in the readme — any variable name you assign to this tuple should not impact the result; as long as the tuple contains the proper contents, your function will work.<div><br /></div><div>The histo passed to compute j is a list of counts — you will need to use norm_histogram inside it to obtain a list of probabilities in order to calculate the j value.<br /><div><br /></div><div><br /></div></div>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'Name of the variables Exercise 1', 'timestamp': '2023-02-02T00:47:10Z', 'user': 'lcrzmj6nzh1w6', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 105}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fjzhn3s65vjd4by%2F4c880a9efd60ba5d9edb2c42c59676d26c8e80fecfd64b6be2030b96929ccd45%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p><p>What should I do?</p> Answer: <p>I got an error when trying to install it too and what worked for me was removing the &#39;==2.1.2&#39;</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'Unable to download matplotlib', 'timestamp': '2023-02-01T22:46:24Z', 'user': 'jzhn3s65vjd4by', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 108}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5gx345d2ba%2F8cfac9c935b06b5309056d0404215e48102893f0b70450943cccb3cb72b47227%2FScreen_Shot_2023-02-01_at_4.35.45_PM.png' alt='Screen_Shot_2023-02-01_at_4.35.45_PM.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: My best guess is that your get coordinates function is returning a tuple instead of an individual function for either x or y (or both). I would try printing the output of get coordinates.""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'how to solve this error', 'timestamp': '2023-02-01T21:36:52Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 109}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I keep getting this error when trying to test my code. How do I fix this?</p> Answer: If the student response does not resolve your issue, I would recommend trying to switch to absolute pathing for input.txt (you should be able to copy the absolute path by right clicking in the list of files in most IDEs).""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'FileNotFoundError: input.txt not found.', 'timestamp': '2023-02-01T16:55:44Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 116}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I still need help figuring this issue out @105 . I have been trying to troubleshoot for days. I am using a mac.</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb60yugxr5ja%2F0660e12b9b9f3e05b40f70538266372e62c2444c950ead29289118e18e166348%2FScreen_Shot_2023-02-01_at_9.50.04_AM.png' alt='Screen_Shot_2023-02-01_at_9.50.04_AM.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <p>Are you installing scipy? Following <a href='https://stackoverflow.com/questions/70916814/error-metadata-generation-failed-cant-install-artic-module' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>https://stackoverflow.com/questions/70916814/error-metadata-generation-failed-cant-install-artic-module</a> - maybe try to do this while installing packages - </p><pre><code>pip install &lt;package-name&gt; --use-deprecated=backtrack-on-build-failures</code></pre>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'Installing Help', 'timestamp': '2023-02-01T14:51:24Z', 'user': 'ktnb60yugxr5ja', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 122}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>My code works and passes all test on my local machine but when I try running it on ececomp, to check if it will also work properly when being graded in that environment, it says matplotlib module not found. When I try installing or upgrading it, it says module already up to date. Is there a specific way im supposed to run it for it to work?</p><p></p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkz5ooutiquc22c%2F7859f6f57118df3280aab77961a951aa196aebffdd25fa8ccf23a63f5619e50e%2FScreenshot_2023-01-31_at_11.20.07_PM.png' width='786' height='400' alt='' /></p> Answer: <p>Have you tried -</p><p></p><pre>python3 -mpip install --user --upgrade matplotlib</pre><p></p><p>Addition: you may also use  pip list to list all modules installed. Make sure you do not put any python PATH in ~./bashrc nor ~/.bash_profile (It makes your machine cannot find the modules). <strong>Besides, just switch to eceprog may solve it automatically. </strong></p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'ececomp Doesn&#39;t properly run code', 'timestamp': '2023-02-01T04:20:46Z', 'user': 'kz5ooutiquc22c', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 124}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>When I run my code, it shows me this. Can anyone tell me how to fix this.</p><p>Thanks</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb6igyqfbch%2Fdcde6bb101c73af35667b763075203f89fdf2d10e279c736ece00b9c5c349081%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p> Answer: <p>You seem to have posted a part of the error message - could you post a screenshot of the full error?</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'Error in running the code', 'timestamp': '2023-02-01T01:28:42Z', 'user': 'ktnb6igyqfbch', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 115}),
