	Document(content="""Question: Im using Vscode and trying to install the modules, and it keeps saying that I have pip version 8.1.2 which is way too old, I tried running the upgrade command and it says there’s some kind of syntax issue, I found that in my linux folder there is both python 2.7 and the new one, and for some reason it’s taking the pip version from the 2.7, I have tried deleting it but it says that the system cannot find the path specified and I don’t know what else to do , since I can’t use the modules with a pip that old Answer: <p>If you are on scholar, try switching to eceprog.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'Pip upgrade issues', 'timestamp': '2023-01-31T17:50:37Z', 'user': 'ktnb3wm15ca2pa', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 125}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Without any additional code to the homework, when I try to initially run my testbin.py I get the following error:<br /><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb4luwdlo5sa%2F741e61d7dd4b95c560935f8b51a5a61f4915041a02adce888edd9c92ae2601e9%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p><p>I have tried removing all of the modules and re-downloading them, I have tried updating all modules, and I have tried importing the </p><pre><code>from collections.abc import MutableMapping</code></pre><p>as suggested online. I am operating in my W:\ drive which is connected to eceprog through an SSH. I figured that my issue may be the path between my modules and my cloned files, but I have also tried to clone my files into my local C:\ drive and run &#34;testbin.py&#34; not on eceprog but I had no success.</p><p></p><p>I have also tried all of the troubleshooting tips laid out in the README file for homework 3.</p><p></p><p>I have discussed my issue with a TA and have attempted to troubleshoot this for hours and haven&#39;t gotten anywhere.</p><p></p><p>Any suggestions on how I can fix this issue would be much appreciated.</p> Answer: <p>First suggestion: check your python -version using python3 --version. By default, eceprog uses python 3.10.6, and matplotlib should be installed. Do not put any PATH setting in ~/.bashrc nor ~/.bash_profile.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'Matlibplot Path / MutableMapping', 'timestamp': '2023-01-31T17:29:54Z', 'user': 'ktnb4luwdlo5sa', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 134}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>When I run the first command given in the Readme, I get this error: </p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb60yugxr5ja%2F453e7fbb320cdf3d76b659c0f31e4ee6ca20646b7f879135ec58789e93a50cbf%2FScreen_Shot_2023-01-31_at_10.18.10_AM.png' alt='Screen_Shot_2023-01-31_at_10.18.10_AM.pngNaN' /></p><p>What does this mean?</p> Answer: If pip doesn&#39;t work, you may try <div>python3 -mpip install &lt;package-name&gt;</div><div>if it&#39;s a windows computer </div><div><br /></div>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'Downloading Pip Error', 'timestamp': '2023-01-31T15:18:44Z', 'user': 'ktnb60yugxr5ja', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 133}),
