	Document(content="""Question: <p>For the output of Problem1.py and testbin.py, I have the correct output for the sweep_n, indices of the smallest values and the smallest values, but my mean is off by roughly 0.001.</p><p>The expected output is:</p><p>([20, 17], [-0.027433185012049905, -0.027377132527427107], -0.027405158769738508)</p><p>My output is:</p><p>([20, 17], [-0.0274331850120499, -0.02737713252742712], -0.026418985246613222)</p><p></p><p>While there are minor discrepancies past 15&#43; digits, these should not be large enough to sway the mean dramatically. Is anyone else having this problem?</p> Answer: Answers will only be checked to 4 decimal places""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'H3 Problem 1 Output', 'timestamp': '2023-01-28T17:38:00Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 168}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>My hw1 just got updated as a 0 on brightspace and it is not graded on GitHub. I submitted the google form. What should I do?</p> Answer: Mine is also like that. I think it&#39;s an error, they&#39;ll probably fix it.""", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'HW1 not graded', 'timestamp': '2023-01-28T15:51:59Z', 'user': 'ktnb839mwas1tt', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 118}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I have read the ReadMe a couple of times now but I am having a lot of trouble understanding the sweep_n function. How am I supposed to use the matplotlib.hist in this function? I understand at a high level that I am trying to calculate the j error for all the bins from min_bins to max_bins, but I do not understand what to do with the minimum or maximum input variables, or how matplotlib.hist relates to this function and where to use it.</p> Answer: The maximum and minimum input variables will be necessary for calculating the bin width at each step. As for using matplotlib, I have no idea. They don&#39;t say anything about actually producing a histogram in this function.Use the hist function to use data to generate the histogram using the three arguments. You have to use the example they put in the test python file. You’re going to have to make the histogram for every bin size and calculate the j value at the same time.""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'HW 3 Sweep Bins', 'timestamp': '2023-01-28T06:06:24Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 163}),
	Document(content="""Note: <p>Hi all, </p><p></p><p>Homework 1 grades have been released for all sections now. All students, can view their grading feedback in their Homework 1 repository on GitHub. To view your feedback, go to your Homework 1 repository on GitHub, click the drop down menu under &#39;main&#39; --&gt; click &#39;Tags&#39; --&gt; click &#39;graded-update.&#39; There will be a file called grading_output.txt in your repository with the output of the grading script specifying which test cases you passed and the number of points they were worth. See attached picture for reference. </p><p></p><p>Note that homeworks are generally graded using test cases. We run your code on a number of test cases (these test cases are visible to you in the grading_output.txt file) and assign points based on the test cases your code passes. Each test case is worth a different number of points depending on its difficulty. </p><p></p><p>If you believe an error has been made in grading, please send a regrade request to</p><p><a href='mailto:ece20875.purdue.university@gmail.com' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>ece20875.purdue.university@gmail.com</a>.<strong> You have one week from the day grades are posted to Brightspace to request a regrade.</strong> Remember to include the following information in your email:</p><ol><li>Relevant identifying information. For homeworks, a link to your GitHub repository is needed.</li><li>Section Number</li><li>Grading item (e.g., homework 1)</li><li>Purdue email (if not sent from a Purdue email)</li><li>Your reasoning or explanation for a regrade, with specific details and justification pointing to the README.</li></ol><p>When submitting an email for a regrade request please do the following:<br /><br />1. Have a <strong>separate email</strong> for each HW<br />2. Have the subject line be the following: <strong>HW# regrade request</strong></p><p></p><p>(it makes it a lot easier for us to filter the inbox and find your email). </p><p></p><p>As usual, feel free to post on Piazza with any additional questions :-)</p><p></p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkskmxecspaq4i1%2F29ecacea51a4a28c76fdccf9e92b3d0f2742cc5124680fd7775cdcfef35c6f4b%2FHowToSeeFeedback.jpg' width='708' height='2020' alt='How to see feedback on github' /></p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'HW1 Grades Released', 'timestamp': '2023-01-28T04:43:34Z', 'user': 'kskmxecspaq4i1', 'tags': ['hw1', 'instructor-note'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 251}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb5b8oexj1jg%2F15bf34f434521c78331a7da5d47465b6571d4a480123a2cdc3905a2e9ede0d5a%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p><p></p><p>When I try to unpack the return values from plt.hist, I run into the error <strong>&#34;TypeError: cannot unpack non-iterable numpy.float64 object&#34;</strong>. Does anyone seem to know what the problem is? Is my unpacking method wrong?</p> Answer: <p>Nevermind. This is resolved</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'HW3 unpacking hist()', 'timestamp': '2023-01-28T04:16:35Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 138}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>On Brightspace, it says I have a 0 for homework 1. However, I have submitted homework 1 and have passed all the test cases. Is this a bug?</p> Answer: <p>You got a 100, when I created the assignment and was uploading the grades, you may have looked on brightspace inbetween when I had created it, but had not uploaded the scores. Sorry for the scare. Congrats on your well done work!</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'HW1 Grade', 'timestamp': '2023-01-28T02:04:46Z', 'user': 'ktnb46l8gil3vd', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 18}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Where do we check to see that our submission has been pushed?</p> Answer: Github. Look for your commit msg""", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'Submission', 'timestamp': '2023-01-28T00:57:13Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 120}),
	Document(content="""Question: I have an if statement that is inside of a two while loops that states this &#34;if months[j] != months[l]:&#34; I keep getting an error that states &#34;list index is out of range&#34;. I don&#39;t know what this means. Answer: List index out of range means you’re trying to access an index that’s not in the list. For example, if the highest index in a list is 3 and you try to access an index of 4, you will get this error. This applies to anything that is iterable, such as dictionaries.""", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'HW Q2 Error', 'timestamp': '2023-01-28T00:12:24Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 101}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>In problem 2, we&#39;re supposed to keep only the older person if the months are the same. I haven&#39;t been able to figure out how to do this for some time. Can someone give me some tips or pointers? </p> Answer: We need to check who’s older. Is the year of the person you want to add smaller (older) than the existing one? If yes, replace; if no, move on to the next person""", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'HW2 how to keep only the older person', 'timestamp': '2023-01-27T20:41:15Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 120}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>When I try to run my code for hw3 problem 1, it shows an error related to importing matplotlib (shown below). Does anyone know how to solve it?</p><p></p><p>Traceback (most recent call last):</p><p>File &#34;/Users/Dropbox/Mac/Desktop/Python/homework-3/Problem1.py&#34;, line 2, in &lt;module&gt;<br />    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt<br />  File &#34;/Library/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/3.10/lib/python3.10/site-packages/matplotlib/__init__.py&#34;, line 113, in &lt;module&gt;<br />    from . import _api, _version, cbook, _docstring, rcsetup<br />  File &#34;/Library/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/3.10/lib/python3.10/site-packages/matplotlib/rcsetup.py&#34;, line 27, in &lt;module&gt;<br />    from matplotlib.colors import Colormap, is_color_like<br />  File &#34;/Library/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/3.10/lib/python3.10/site-packages/matplotlib/colors.py&#34;, line 51, in &lt;module&gt;<br />    from PIL import Image<br />  File &#34;/Library/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/3.10/lib/python3.10/site-packages/PIL/Image.py&#34;, line 114, in &lt;module&gt;<br />    from . import _imaging as core<br />ImportError: dlopen(/Library/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/3.10/lib/python3.10/site-packages/PIL/_imaging.cpython-310-darwin.so, 0x0002): tried: &#39;/Library/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/3.10/lib/python3.10/site-packages/PIL/_imaging.cpython-310-darwin.so&#39; (mach-o file, but is an incompatible architecture (have &#39;x86_64&#39;, need &#39;arm64&#39;)), &#39;/System/Volumes/Preboot/Cryptexes/OS/Library/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/3.10/lib/python3.10/site-packages/PIL/_imaging.cpython-310-darwin.so&#39; (no such file), &#39;/Library/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/3.10/lib/python3.10/site-packages/PIL/_imaging.cpython-310-darwin.so&#39; (mach-o file, but is an incompatible architecture (have &#39;x86_64&#39;, need &#39;arm64&#39;))</p> Answer: Do you have matplotlib already installed on your PC? If you have and are still getting the error, you may want to try out some comments on this page:<div><br /><div>https://stackoverflow.com/questions/66122146/pip-install-matplotlib-fails-on-m1-mac</div></div>""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'Unable to use matplotlib', 'timestamp': '2023-01-27T19:48:02Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 157}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>In homework 3, for problem 1 in the norm_histogram function how do we determine what number of bins to use? The example in the instructions uses 5 bins but as we are sweeping the number of bins how should be approach this?</p> Answer: You have not been asked to determine the number of bins. The hist parameter to the norm_histogram refers to the list of counts. So, you are to write this function so that it sums the entries in this list and returns a tuple that contains the list of probabilities (for each entry in the list) and the sum. The example with 5 bins was only an illustration. You should use the testbin.py file to test if your function was written correctly. Ensure that it matches what was given in the README file.""", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'HW3 Clarification', 'timestamp': '2023-01-27T18:46:35Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 167}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>My outputs for question 2 are as follows:</p><p></p><pre>{3: ((&#39;Alice&#39;, (2, 1980, 42)), (&#39;Charlie&#39;, (1, 1990, 32))), 4: (&#39;Bob&#39;, (3, 1970, 52))}{1: ((&#39;John&#39;, (15, 1985, 37)), (&#39;Bob&#39;, (5, 1995, 27))), 2: (&#39;Jane&#39;, (20, 1989, 33))}</pre><p></p><p>On the assignment is has the months and names in quotes such as:</p><p>{&#34;3&#34;: ((&#34;Alice&#34;, (2, 1980, 42)), (&#34;Charlie&#34;, (1, 1990, 32))), &#34;4&#34;: ((&#34;Bob&#34;, (3, 1970, 52))}</p><p>or</p><p>{1: ((&#34;John&#34;, (15, 1985, 37)), (&#34;Bob&#34;, (5, 1995, 27))), 2: ((&#34;Jane&#34;, (20, 1989, 33)))}</p><p></p><p>Does this matter if my answers are in single quotes, double quotes, or any quotes at all? If so I am not sure how to get that</p> Answer: <p>Your output is acceptable. Look at note @51 for more clarifications. </p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'HW2 Q2 Outputs', 'timestamp': '2023-01-27T18:26:38Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 120}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I worked in an online compiler, where all my code was working and outputting the correct values, but for som reason when I put it into the assignment and test with the output files the output is wrong. anyone have a similar issue?</p><p></p><p>when I run the debugged file the code outputs correctly, but not when I do it normally</p> Answer: <p>Make sure you are returning the right histogram list and not just printing it. What kind of an output are you getting when you run it with the test cases given to you? </p><p></p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'compiler to vscode issues', 'timestamp': '2023-01-27T17:20:40Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 101}),
