	Document(content="""Question: <p>Will other sections also be going virtual tomorrow? Dependent on snow it can make it very difficult to get here for off campus students. My section would be the 12:00 section in ME with Makur. I would not want to miss attendance points if I am unable to safely make it to campus. </p> Answer: <p>At the moment, we believe sections tomorrow will remain in-person, since weather forecasts suggest that the worst of the snow storm should end by today evening. However, we are constantly monitoring the weather advisory as well as Purdue guidelines, and we will make an announcement if things need to go virtual. In the absence of such an announcement, please assume usual operations.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['logistics'], 'title': 'Zoom lecture', 'timestamp': '2023-01-25T15:41:00Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['logistics', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 149}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I am trying to finish the second problem with the dictionary, and noticed that, if there are two identical keys, then only the most recent element of the dictionary with that key remains. How would I be able to make it so that the person with the greater age is returned? Thank you!</p> Answer: 1. Append the first person<div>2. Every time before you append, check if the month is already in the dataset </div><div>3. If it is, check which one is older </div><div>4. If new one is older, insert. Else, finish iteration </div>""", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'Problem 2 Homework 2', 'timestamp': '2023-01-25T03:39:06Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 156}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Is the bracket underlined red supposed to be &#39;(&#39; or &#39;[&#39;??? Does that mean I do not include the min_val?? Is the max val also inclusive? </p><p></p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb502f6237m0%2F1187c9ce5c00461aa883d796ba5815191dc1c67685176a508634490d9274d52a%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <p>The underlined bracket is supposed to be open &#39;(&#39;. This is taken care of in step 7 where you ignore any values in data that are less than or equal to the minimum value given as min_val.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'HW 2 histogram bounds', 'timestamp': '2023-01-25T02:58:16Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 141}),
	Document(content="""Note: For Sec. 002 (MWF, 9:30 am-10:20 am in ARMS 1010)We will have our lecture tomorrow in Zoom (Wed. 01/25), due to the expected winter storm. We will use my office hour zoom link:https://purdue-edu.zoom.us/j/96282185900?pwd=UDBFdWtBbWV6RFozcyt3d0lxWFV6UT09Qiang""", meta={'folders': ['logistics'], 'title': 'Sec. 002 Zoom lecture tomorrow (Wed. 01/25)', 'timestamp': '2023-01-24T18:39:42Z', 'user': 'kduwvc06f5a30c', 'tags': ['instructor-note', 'logistics'], 'likes': 4, 'views': 157}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I&#39;m in the 12:00 section in ME 1061 and sometimes it&#39;s difficult to hear the instructor, is there a possibility of him using a microphone in class soon?</p> Answer: <p>With regard to the lecture in ME 1061, the microphone unfortunately does not pick up my voice when I tried it in the first week. So, I had requested students several times in the first week to come up to the front of the class so they could hear me. There are usually plenty of empty seats in front. I encourage you to fill up those seats. I know some of the other instructors have also suffered from this mic issue, so it may be the same for ARMS.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['other'], 'title': 'Microphone for lecture?', 'timestamp': '2023-01-24T17:36:43Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['other', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 139}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>For homework 2 part 1, all of my test cases work but the fourth one. I think that this could have something to do with the bins including values on the bottom of the bin but not the top of the bin. Do you know what my problem could be? Test case 4 for me outputs [1, 0, 0, 0, 0] instead of [0,0,0,0,0]. I think I sent this only to instructors, so I can also show that part of my code if I am allowed to and if that woule help. Thank you!</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fl6maptmggzy7op%2F1d5cd6be8d6d9a0edab564d0ec31a17cc43105cbc82289c8326d4280f9a83e42%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p> Answer: <p>You are welcome to post your code as long as the post is set to private, for only instructors. I would imagine the issue has something to do with a your lower boundary on the first bin, but would have to see it to be sure.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'Homework 2 Question', 'timestamp': '2023-01-23T20:50:43Z', 'user': 'l6maptmggzy7op', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 20}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p dir='ltr'>Will we be tested on repeated names?</p><p dir='ltr'></p><p dir='ltr'>Take the following test inputs for example:</p><p dir='ltr'></p><p dir='ltr'>person_to_day = {&#39;Tom&#39;: 25, &#39;Jerry&#39;: 30, &#39;Chris&#39;: 6, &#39;Sam&#39;: 6, &#39;Carl&#39;: 31, &#39;Tom&#39;: 31}</p><p dir='ltr'></p><p dir='ltr'>person_to_month = {&#39;Tom&#39;: 9, &#39;Jerry&#39;: 8, &#39;Chris&#39;: 8, &#39;Sam&#39;: 4, &#39;Carl&#39;: 5, &#39;Tom&#39;: 6}</p><p dir='ltr'></p><p dir='ltr'>person_to_year = {&#39;Tom&#39;: 1975, &#39;Jerry&#39;: 1980, &#39;Chris&#39;: 1968, &#39;Sam&#39;: 2003, &#39;Carl&#39;: 1902, &#39;Tom&#39;: 2005}</p><p></p><p dir='ltr'>where the person, ‘Tom’,  occurs twice.</p> Answer: Because the input dictionaries use names as keys, it is not possible for the input dictionaries to have the same name listed with two different days, months, or years — each key corresponds to one item.<div><div><br /></div></div>""", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'HW 2 Problem 2 Question', 'timestamp': '2023-01-23T19:24:48Z', 'user': 'ksi8ka1ba1t6tv', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 164}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>In Problem 2 it was stated that the final result needed to be a dictionary of tuples, however, the expected output does not have a comma for a tuple with a single element even though all single-element tuples have a comma at the end. Is my answer acceptable or do we need to take out the comma?</p><p></p><p>Using Tuple {1: ((&#39;John&#39;, (15, 1985, 37)), (&#39;Bob&#39;, (5, 1995, 27))), 2: ((&#39;Jane&#39;, (20, 1989, 33)<strong>),)</strong>}</p><p></p><p>Expected Output: {1: ((&#34;John&#34;, (15, 1985, 37)), (&#34;Bob&#34;, (5, 1995, 27))), 2: ((&#34;Jane&#34;, (20, 1989, 33)<strong>))</strong>}</p> Answer: <p>nvm, didn&#39;t see clarifications </p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'Problem 2 clarification', 'timestamp': '2023-01-23T00:48:41Z', 'user': 'ksi8kdj5jo1700', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 183}),
