	Document(content="""Question: <p>Hi I get all my answers false, when they supppose to be correct </p><p></p><p></p><p>Problem 1:<br />Problem 1 answer correct? False     Student answer was: = odd<br />Problem 1 answer correct? False     Student answer was: = even<br />Problem 1 answer correct? False     Student answer was: = leap<br />Problem 1 answer correct? False     Student answer was: = leap<br />Problem 1 answer correct? False     Student answer was: = even (end of century but not divisible by 400)</p><p>Problem 2:<br />Problem 2 answer correct? False       Student answer was: [0.0, 1.0, 3.0, 6.0]<br />Problem 2 answer correct? False       Student answer was: [0.0, 1.0, 3.0, 6.0]<br />Problem 2 answer correct? False       Student answer was: [0.0, 1.0, 3.0, 6.0, 10.0, 15.0]<br />Problem 2 answer correct? False       Student answer was: [0.0, 1.0, 3.0, 6.0, 10.0, 15.0]</p> Answer: For problem 2 use the int type cast during ur calculations. """, meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Not well graded', 'timestamp': '2023-01-20T23:41:59Z', 'user': 'lcrzmj6nzh1w6', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 173}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>In the README for problem 2, the answers is formatted like so</p><pre><code>{3: (&#39;John&#39;, (5, 1990, 32)), 5: (&#39;Jane&#39;, (10, 1995, 27)), 7: (&#39;Mike&#39;, (20, 2000, 22))}</code></pre><p>However, in the testbirthday files, the expected output is formatted with an extra pair of parantheses around each value, implying that all values should be placed inside of a tuple regardless of whether or not there is more than one person with that birthmonth</p><p>(testbirthday1)</p><div><pre>#Expected Output: {1: ((&#34;John&#34;, (15, 1985, 37)), (&#34;Bob&#34;, (5, 1995, 27))), 2: ((&#34;Jane&#34;, (20, 1989, 33)))}</pre></div><p>(testbirthday2)</p><div><pre>#Expected Output: {&#34;3&#34;: ((&#34;Alice&#34;, (2, 1980, 42)), (&#34;Charlie&#34;, (1, 1990, 32))), &#34;4&#34;: ((&#34;Bob&#34;, (3, 1970, 52))}</pre><p>The second test file also has one less paranthesis at the end of the &#34;4&#34; value but im assuming thats just a typo</p></div><p></p><p>So which example should we go off of? Are we supposed to always include a &#34;wrapper&#34; tuple, or do we only do it for months with more than one person?</p> Answer: <p>Notice how Bob and John in <kbd>testbirthday1.py</kbd> have birthdays in the same month; as do Charlie and Alice in <kbd>testbirthday2.py</kbd>. This is because you&#39;re creating a dictionary for the months of the year, and a tuple including Bob and John fall under January; Alice and Charlie fall under a tuple in March.<br /><br />Annapoorna: These inconsistencies are addressed in note @51</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'Inconsistancies with birthday test cases', 'timestamp': '2023-01-20T22:56:26Z', 'user': 'ktnb3vlkh772ks', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 150}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>For HW2, the testbirthday files have a comment with the intended output while the testhisto files do not. Was this on purpose or is it a mistake?</p> Answer: <p>I would assume it was intentional. If you don&#39;t want to manually calculate and compare the answers you could just copy and paste the examples from the ReadMe and check them using those results.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'Was expected output intentionally omitted from the testhisto files?', 'timestamp': '2023-01-20T21:54:31Z', 'user': 'ktnb3vlkh772ks', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 145}),
