	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb4jghyzy5i0%2F6917ed9f4b48e8d53bb55f7165bc42162c2c79cb48ada2e0c50fbde3ec50e972%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p><p>I got this error and I tried to connect my personal and school email, but its not working. Idk how to solve this.</p> Answer: <p>Please refer to the error message shown on screen for the correct syntax. </p><div></div><div>Specifically, user.email and user.name should not be omitted as they specify which property you’re setting. Additionally, your email/name should be in quotes</div>""", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Invalid Key/Unknown Author Identity', 'timestamp': '2023-01-20T04:03:14Z', 'user': 'ktnb4jghyzy5i0', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 132}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I just want to confirm that as long as we get all test cases correct, we should get all points for the HW. Also Is it possible to get a &#34;pre-grade&#34; if there is an autograder?</p> Answer: <p>If your output matches the expected output then you are in a good place. Some homeworks require you use/not use certain packages, so make sure to follow those instructions as well. Unfortunately, no pre-grades.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'HW grade', 'timestamp': '2023-01-19T18:34:00Z', 'user': 'ke4p3ybt1f24t8', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 171}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I was working on the first home work and was looking at the note on submission in the syllabus about having to use scholar cluster and or ececomp. I am currently using my personal machine, a Macos system, to program and submit the homework. Will I have to setup up a remote SSH connection with ececomp to work on the homework  or can I continue to work from my personal machine. I read that the main concern is that the versions of python might not be the same and that can lead to differences in the compilation and success of the code. Can I avoid that problem if I simply know what version of python ececomp or scholar cluster uses and just use that same version on my laptop?</p><p></p><p>Also, I currently program using VS code. Would you recommend I continue with VS code or should I start using Jupyter lab on either the anaconda package or the scholar cluster since for data science its more efficient to use Jupyter Lab or notebook for data processing?</p> Answer: <p>Ok. Here is the ranking: scholar cluster &gt; eceprog &gt; Unix/Linux &gt; Mac &gt; Windows. However, I only worked on my Windows computer when I took this class. You probably will only see differences due to the version or machine in the last few assignments. </p><p></p><p>I will say VS code is even much better than Jupyter. (Jupyter has its own advantages.) And anaconda is something else, you can use anaconda and Jupyter notebook in VS code.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Elaboration on HW Submission', 'timestamp': '2023-01-19T17:36:50Z', 'user': 'kz5ooutiquc22c', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 17}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Hey so I was able to push and commit changes however I am trying to run the python code on vs code and it is asking for a python interpreter and so I am really confused on what versions of python I should be using for the interpreter as well as what version of the python extension I should be using in vs code</p> Answer: <p>Even if you have python installed on your computer, you still need vs code python extension. In general, the version of python does not matter. They should have the same result. If you do not feel safe, you can check your program on scholar cluster or eceprog machine with ssh. You can also check the python version used on these machines.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Homework 1', 'timestamp': '2023-01-19T17:17:21Z', 'user': 'ktnb5cdi52e1o5', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 165}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Hello there. I am using spyder editor for my python editor. How would I submit to GitHub using Spyder editor? I&#39;ve tried researching it but it has not worked so far. Thanks for your help.</p> Answer: <p>If you are working on your own computer, especially if it is Windows, make sure you install local Git for Windows, or you cannot use the git command line in the Shell.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Spyder', 'timestamp': '2023-01-19T15:54:40Z', 'user': 'l8au993a2bs71z', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 155}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>When I push my code, it shows this in my workflow runs and I have no idea how to fix it<br />Did I miss something in my code? <br />Or should I just ignore it?</p> Answer: <p>It may be not a Github failure, probably due to some extension like pyTest. If you could see your code and commit on Github Web, you are good. If not, come to our office hours.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Error: Process completed with exit code 5.', 'timestamp': '2023-01-19T01:31:37Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 131}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>After I finished my code, I just go to GitHub website and edit my code (<a href='https://github.com/ECEDataScience/homework-1-s23-c0y93/blob/main/problems.py'>problems.py</a>) there<br />Does that work? It sends an &#34;All jobs have failed&#34; email so it doesn&#39;t look like a good sign<br />Or do I really need to went through SSH something</p> Answer: There are different ways to go about doing so (and there are other posts here regarding this), but you should be cloning a repository, and pushing your code to GitHub.""", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'HW submission', 'timestamp': '2023-01-19T00:17:47Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 148}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I&#39;m not sure if this has been asked before, but do we have to use SSH and/or Scholar to submit assignments? I was able to clone, commit, and push the repo using Git version 2.39.0 and Python version 3.10.9. I&#39;d prefer to not use SSH/Scholar for simplicity, if possible.</p> Answer: SSH isn’t technically required but recommended. I believe assignments are graded on ECN servers so consistency is always nice but if you worked locally and your files work on ECN servers you’re good""", meta={'folders': ['logistics'], 'title': 'Is SSH required?', 'timestamp': '2023-01-18T21:05:51Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['logistics', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 161}),
	Document(content="""Note: <p>Note: you may also use eceprog instead of ececomp, I don&#39;t think ecegrid works with VS smoothly anymore. Essentially, in this post anywhere you see ecegrid, replace it with ececomp or eceprog. Just stay consistent.</p><p></p><p>Assignments are accepted through GitHub. If you are a Windows or Mac user, the following is a short tutorial on how to access the ECN servers work on your code, and submit via GitHub</p><p></p><p>Access the Extensions page on the left sidebar and search for the &#34;Remote - SSH&#34; extension. Go ahead and install that:</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkeuahk7t7pc1oq%2Fcdc7c32e586ef7d30a940d5f6af8e8f1f8bbe1d16e2cc138c69d48f275add0b9%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' width='734' height='342' /></p><p></p><p>While you&#39;re at it, install Python.</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkeuahk7t7pc1oq%2F17a2388778a79adfd492fc3c34cbed9e52a16cbcf172ddc1d3582b89b83a5117%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' width='523' height='104' /></p><p></p><p>Next, navigate on the left sidebar to your remote explorer.</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkeuahk7t7pc1oq%2F7d0fcb684a2bcbfc9a000321740901991698e3f32f35bca4867c5b18f0760073%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' width='135' height='179' /> </p><p>Click the plus button, and VS should prompt you with:</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkeuahk7t7pc1oq%2Ff465adc72c9c33e8c70cdfc83b03133a04ec0d8d8dabd67b936b31a6902d1904%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' width='497' height='85' /></p><p>Type in: ssh YOURPURDUEUSER@ecegrid.ecn.purdue.edu and click enter. <strong>(</strong><strong>UPDATE: USE eceprog or ececomp INSTEAD OF ecegrid: YOURPURDUEUSER@eceprog.ecn.purdue.edu)</strong></p><p></p><p>The following prompt might show up... just press enter at the step (if you set it up elsewhere, remember where you set up the config file.). Don&#39;t click anything else.</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkeuahk7t7pc1oq%2F5531dba3fc20298ed7062d64cb26165de312419a153e6add74a478493b7d1c33%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' width='478' height='121' /></p><p></p><p>Now back to this:</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkeuahk7t7pc1oq%2F7d0fcb684a2bcbfc9a000321740901991698e3f32f35bca4867c5b18f0760073%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' width='135' height='179' /></p><p>Click the settings button and press enter (you want to open the config file). A config file should pop up as follows:</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkeuahk7t7pc1oq%2F3554e0ed94527c34bd4a31e3b937efbfdda8f82e840df4a3f635a01297faab31%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' width='520' height='216' /></p><p></p><p>Add &#39;  PasswordAuthentication yes&#39; and save the file:</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkeuahk7t7pc1oq%2F49df29fdd113606464f8f33ee2ad70e354dabaea75378f2c8108646aef7974f2%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' width='533' height='263' /></p><p></p><p>Now going back to the remote explorer: click the open in new window button, the one in the bottom right of the photo below (if you don&#39;t see this, click the reload button to the right of the &#39;REMOTE&#39; and it should update):</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkeuahk7t7pc1oq%2F2bb013099d37547fd334a08060dd7ba332d916f4936a6246882c648005eaafe3%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' width='256' height='111' /></p><p></p><p>A prompt will pop up... Click Linux.</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkeuahk7t7pc1oq%2F32de1b4775e3ae957642ed659f03060a96ff2b498bb1027acadb62e66528d276%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' width='692' height='146' /></p><p>Yeah you want to continue.</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkeuahk7t7pc1oq%2F4080e7eb71a1527124a0a0f1272f3df9d6aee09812008062d6ffc576ca283bb3%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' width='691' height='120' /></p><p>Type in your password. Like you would for Microsoft Outlook, so not the xxxx,push password. I&#39;m using ececomp here. You may also use<strong> eceprog.</strong></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkeuahk7t7pc1oq%2Ffd4e337ea1ee58c78b19a605d8a83b6d2a6794c4b10a04ff02ae8b0b118ab343%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' width='691' height='85' /></p><p>At this point VS will take a second to connect to the Linux servers. After it&#39;s done loading, open up a new terminal. You&#39;ll be able to use all the fancy Linux commands, like ls, cd, etc. </p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkeuahk7t7pc1oq%2Ff8d009760a965b9d14ff5bf517c2d9292c31f83a0d4a622c71ea25389fb9e22c%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' width='664' height='193' /></p><p></p><p>At this point you can go ahead and clone your GitHub assignments straight onto the <strong>eceprog </strong>servers. Navigate to the following section:</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkeuahk7t7pc1oq%2F3ce27fd2885c5cb7635196aeb40891e9da601fbb5ef1b3619865a2ddfdfa5682%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' width='182' height='343' /></p><p></p><p>You could just clone the repository directly here by linking your GitHub and VSCode accounts. Follow the prompts, give VS/Github permission where they request it, etc. If you cloned already, then open the folder that you cloned by clicking &#34;open folder&#34; and just navigate to whatever it&#39;s called. It&#39;s possible you have to type in your password again. Just follow whatever the prompts ask you to do. You also might have to trust the authors of the file. Click yes in this case.</p><p></p><p>At this point my screen looks like this (you&#39;ll see different files. This repo is <strong>not</strong> a 20875 repo):</p><p></p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkeuahk7t7pc1oq%2F9d9bae4e599651b84dbf4a15e1c85507a331b7618ed8a23ed1470257e9125182%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' width='666' height='500' /></p><p></p><p>All of the files are now one click away and you can edit directly in VSCode. When you save, it automatically saves to the <strong>eceprog </strong>servers. Another tip - you know you&#39;re connected to the server because of the bottom left that says SSH: <strong>eceprog.ecn.purdue.edu</strong>. Remember that you still have to commit and push for GitHub to receive your changes. You&#39;re able to do all that in the VSCode terminal.</p><p></p><p>To run/test your files, there&#39;s a little play button to the top right of the window. Click this and it will run the python file that is currently open. </p><p></p><p>When you want to submit to Github:</p><p></p><pre>git add .git commit -m &#34;message&#34;git push</pre><p>GitHub should now be updated. </p><p></p><p>Feel free to open any followup discussions if these steps weren&#39;t clear or if you encounter an issue you can&#39;t solve. Hope this helps</p>""", meta={'folders': ['logistics'], 'title': 'GitHub with VSCode on ECN servers', 'timestamp': '2023-01-17T23:43:34Z', 'user': 'keuahk7t7pc1oq', 'tags': ['instructor-note', 'logistics'], 'likes': 8, 'views': 205}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Does anyone know what the process for honors contracting ECE 20875 is?</p> Answer: <p>Please email your professor, but last year the process was an addition to the final project.</p><p></p>""", meta={'folders': ['other'], 'title': 'Honors Contract', 'timestamp': '2023-01-17T18:33:44Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['other', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 162}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>After I finshed the assignment, I deleted the given comments (the problem parameters), before I read the part about how to submit in github. Where can I see the empty assignment files to paste the commentary into my code?</p> Answer: You can find the given comments either on GitHub if you have not pushed your code yet, or in the past versions of files on GitHub.""", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'deleted the given comments', 'timestamp': '2023-01-17T02:24:42Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 170}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I was trying to push my code onto github and I keep getting this. How could I fix this issue? <img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb44elial3m8%2F449924a19837e51cb057010595fdb7871b67b85a944f9fec8c911f0621f17840%2FScreen_Shot_2023-01-16_at_6.28.48_PM.png' alt='Screen_Shot_2023-01-16_at_6.28.48_PM.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <p>nevermind, i got it.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'GitHub Issues', 'timestamp': '2023-01-16T23:29:58Z', 'user': 'ktnb44elial3m8', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 25}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I am trying to access the scholar cluster remote desktop but I am stuck on this screen, no matter what I type when I press enter it just disconnects me.  <img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb4ckmtz14lb%2F77e698d5c7657bf9923d0d6228d9d7778cc99f546d88f69b5f9e3fce6b6c5e3c%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <p>Other solutions are: using eceprog, which is similar, or SSH terminal/workspace connection. Most homework can also be run on a windows machine with the same result.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Help with Scholar Cluster', 'timestamp': '2023-01-16T23:28:56Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 166}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I am trying to connect to SSH and this pops up - does anyone know what this means and how to solve it?</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb60yugxr5ja%2F962b24af35ed5040a9763555be58e563b8d7280c5166a32a8b62ae30c7fdbcd9%2FScreen_Shot_2023-01-16_at_4.37.02_PM.png' alt='Screen_Shot_2023-01-16_at_4.37.02_PM.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <p>Did you install the Remote SSH extension? If you did, try uninstalling and reinstalling it.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Missing API?', 'timestamp': '2023-01-16T21:37:21Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 170}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I&#39;m new to GitHub and I&#39;m trying to get started on the homework by following the video on Brightspace, but this message comes up when I try to clone the repository. Does anyone know what to do?</p><p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb4yplxsk7g3%2F17cf8caa12c6bc6b594653f9cce5ab75cd60da0eb1f500fdbdd5c8fd23487679%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' /></p> Answer: <p><a href='https://docs.github.com/en/authentication/connecting-to-github-with-ssh/adding-a-new-ssh-key-to-your-github-account' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>https://docs.github.com/en/authentication/connecting-to-github-with-ssh/adding-a-new-ssh-key-to-your-github-account</a></p><p></p><p>I believe you need to add a key now.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'How to get started on the homework?', 'timestamp': '2023-01-16T20:46:56Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 200}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fk89ehhhugeg7bx%2Fcb48b47f76716080205167e30c1fe5a8708833422d68442156654c1eff1cb191%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' /></p><p>After I get correct test result with &#34;python3 problems.py&#34;, I add,commit,push the code. Then I&#39;m done for hw1 correct?</p> Answer: After completing the homework and pushing it to the repository (you should be able to see it updated on GitHub), you are done, yes. As a note, not all grading test cases will always be tested for in the provided cases.""", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'To verify if I did everything correct', 'timestamp': '2023-01-16T13:57:51Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 200}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Is there any way for us to know if we have filled out our github info correctly on the google form? Or will we find out once the grade for hw1 comes out? </p> Answer: If you were able to use GitHub in the completion of the homework and receive the correct grade in Brightspace, you should be good. If your grade in Brightspace is incorrect, please file a regrade request.""", meta={'folders': ['logistics'], 'title': 'GitHub User Google Form', 'timestamp': '2023-01-15T23:25:45Z', 'user': 'ktnb47rugdl40e', 'tags': ['logistics', 'student'], 'likes': 6, 'views': 182}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Does anyone know what day usually our hw released so that we can work on it earlier compared to the first one. Is it right after the due date of previous hw?</p> Answer: Homework is usual released on or close to the Friday before it is due.<div><br /></div><div>See follow up below for more details. </div>""", meta={'folders': ['other'], 'title': 'Hw released date', 'timestamp': '2023-01-15T17:00:16Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['other', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 196}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Whenever I try using git push, it says it cannot find the remote repository. I already added the SSH key and checked the URL for my origin, it matches what it should be but when I run it there&#39;s an extra slash on the end of the URL. I&#39;m not sure if the slash is what&#39;s causing the issue, but I don&#39;t know how to get rid of it to test.</p><p></p> Answer: <p>resolved</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Unable to Push to Remote Repo', 'timestamp': '2023-01-14T23:24:24Z', 'user': 'ktnb3vlkh772ks', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 196}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Are we allowed to import the math library for HW1, and are there any other library restrictions?</p> Answer: <p>You can use *most* Python libraries as long as you have an understanding of <strong>how </strong>a particular function works.</p><p></p><p>Libraries like math and numpy are fine, and later in the class, you&#39;ll use sklearn and NTLK for some assignments, but you will know the theory before you actually use it.</p><p></p><p>You cannot use functions/libraries that you don&#39;t have an inherent understanding of.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'math library', 'timestamp': '2023-01-13T22:36:45Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 220}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Are we allowed to use continue and break statements for this class?</p><p></p> Answer: <p>I believe anything in the Python language is fair game</p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Continue and break statements', 'timestamp': '2023-01-13T22:09:16Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 193}),
	Document(content="""Note: <p>For those of you that took ECE264 last semester, this post may look familiar. I combined and edited two posts from the 264 piazza to make a more comprehensive guide. Feel free to leave a comment if you run into any errors.</p><p></p><p>Install Remote SSH Extension program to VSCode<br />       - <a href='https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=ms-vscode-remote.remote-ssh'>https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=ms-vscode-remote.remote-ssh</a></p><p></p><p>Open VS Code and click on Remote Explorer button on the left.<br /><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkz5opoahaka46s%2F473725285bc932e9cb8ffdd05c5f62801c9206cf8c5431aee4d60ae6ec04ecc9%2FScreen_Shot_2022-08-25_at_9.33.53_AM.png' alt='' width='513' height='311' /></p><p></p><p>Click &#43; on SSH Targets Tab and enter your own ssh command (ssh USERNAME@scholar.rcac.purdue.edu).<br /><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb6q0n1t11mg%2Fbadfc4dd5365b0bdfba846ad0bf1f89c0d1c9d3e3696d2085049030cbce5f5c1%2FScreenshot_2023-01-13_at_4.05.30_PM.png' alt='Screenshot_2023-01-13_at_4.05.30_PM.pngNaN' width='402' height='92' /><br />After Entering, click on /Users/LAPTOPNAME/.ssh/config<br /><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb6q0n1t11mg%2F9bc1e4c921aaca9e506a2fd7d6a3c9dfb44274707ad6d3d3ee21db80f8f052f8%2FScreenshot_2023-01-13_at_4.06.12_PM.png' alt='Screenshot_2023-01-13_at_4.06.12_PM.png' width='495' height='193' /><br />This will create/add SSH Connection configuration data to the path you have clicked as in the image above.</p><p></p><p>You now should edit the configuration that you have created by specifying your SSH requires a password.<br />Simply click on settings button and select /Users/UR_USERNAME/.ssh/config.<br /><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fkz5opoahaka46s%2Ff74e610b1afa6163c05b2dc0a07d0458fc51f217ae8c012611227bd54de51250%2FScreen_Shot_2022-08-25_at_9.51.16_AM.png' alt='Screen_Shot_2022-08-25_at_9.51.16_AM.pngNaN' width='484' height='223' /><br />Now you will see ur ssh configuration file.<br />Simply add &#34;  PasswordAuthentication yes&#34; to the file and save.<br /><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb6q0n1t11mg%2Fa7ae781e3b7c267cbb75f3c3b58aa4eb753a577a36470d691f03be0c6769e478%2FScreenshot_2023-01-13_at_4.02.00_PM.png' alt='Screenshot_2023-01-13_at_4.02.00_PM.png' width='488' height='235' /></p><p></p><p>Depending on your OS, follow the steps in the &#34;SSH Keys&#34; section of this link:</p><p><a href='https://www.rcac.purdue.edu/knowledge/scholar/all' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>https://www.rcac.purdue.edu/knowledge/scholar/all</a> </p><p></p><p>You&#39;ll know you followed these steps correctly if by testing the new key by SSH-ing to the server. The login should now complete without asking for a password.</p><ol></ol><p></p><p>- On you Scholar linux command window, type in</p><p></p><pre><code>ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C &#34;<em>your\_email@example.com</em>&#34;</code></pre><p>with “your_email@example.com” being the email you signed up on GitHub, <strong>NOT</strong> your Purdue email<br />- Next, the window should prompt something like this</p><p></p><pre><code>&gt; Enter a file in which to save the key (/c/Users/<em>you</em>/.ssh/id\_<em>algorithm</em>):</code></pre><p>Just press enter without typing anything, this will set ur SSH key file location to default.<br />- Then, the window should ask for your “passphrase”</p><p></p><pre><code>&gt; Enter passphrase (empty for no passphrase):  &gt; Enter same passphrase again:</code></pre><p>Type in a password you can remember easily. You will need this passphrase when trying to clone your Git later<br />- If everything went smoothly, something like this should pop up on your screen</p><p></p><pre>Your identification has been saved in /home/shay/a/yourPurdueUsername/.ssh/id\_ed25519. Your public key has been saved in /home/shay/a/yourPurdueUsername/.ssh/id\_ed25519.pub. The key fingerprint is: SHA256:&#34;a very long chain of Hex encoding&#34; yourGithHubEmail@example.com The key&#39;s randomart image is: &#43;--\[ED25519 256\]--&#43; |                 | |                 | |                 | |       Some      | |      Random     | |       Image     | |                 | |                 | |                 | &#43;----\[SHA256\]-----&#43;</pre><p>- Copy the part where it says</p><p></p><pre>/home/shay/a/yourPurdueUsername/.ssh/id\_ed25519.pub</pre><p>- Type in “cd” and press enter in the window<br />- Type in “cat”, then paste in the address you copied from above<br /><strong></strong><br /><strong>Make sure to have .pub at the end</strong><strong>!</strong> <br />Using the address without the .pub extension will not give you the correct information!<br />- The console should spit back something like this:</p><p></p><pre>ssh-ed25519 &#34;Extremely long base64 encoded (I think?) chain of letters&#34; yourGitHubEmail@example.com</pre><p>Copy the <strong>ENTIRE THING</strong>, not just the encoded chain of letters! Including the emails too<br />- Next, go to your GitHub account settings on your browser. It should be the second last thing of the drop-down menu after you click on your profile picture<br /><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb43l3d7g3ia%2F1ac820ba732a73d63df376e4aa79ec573e93ecb8ef4fd1996102120fadb207bb%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' width='177' height='458' /><br />- Next, there should be a section that says “SSH and GPG Keys” to the left of the screen. Click on that<br /><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb43l3d7g3ia%2F38c60379970d6bb9d9a1ca5bda91bdb320a1457fe7d0bdb94e6be4b86409f55c%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' width='234' height='339' /><br />- Click on the “New SSH key” button in green at the top of the screen<br /><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb43l3d7g3ia%2Fa1c12f26876f576706f8993136504119a173163d946eb92cdfd1798e8710884f%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' width='689' height='115' /><br />- Your screen should look something like this<br /><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb43l3d7g3ia%2F05b603a29b4acab0a696d4f1fd2ad619e736a88272f96ff66a851b1829c3798f%2Fimage.png' alt='image.png' width='466' height='299' /><br />Paste in the &#34;ssh-ed25519 “Extremely long chain of letters yourGitHubEmail@example.com” to the Key section. Again, make sure to paste in the <strong>ENTIRE </strong>phrase, including the ssh-ed25519 at the front and email at the end<br />- Name the title whatever you wish it to be, then click “Add SSH key”<br />- Go back to your Scholar cluster console and try cloning the Git repository again. You can do so by typing</p><p></p><pre>git clone git@github.com:ECEDataScience/homework-1-s23-yourusername.git</pre><p>You can also get the “git@github…” link by copying it from your HW1 Git repository’s code dropdown menu<br /><img src='/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&amp;prefix=paste%2Fktnb43l3d7g3ia%2Fb0f44c1d2e1fef48b8a2d6d40339d0af8a1fd7e47598eee3490211610449bceb%2Fimage.png' alt='image.pngNaN' width='507' height='227' /><br /><strong>Make sure to use the SSH link! Not using the SSH version of the link will make your life more</strong> <strong>troublesome</strong><br />- Enter the passphrase you set earlier when you are prompted to do so. If everything goes smooth, the console should say something like this</p><p></p><pre>remote: Enumerating objects: 11, done. remote: Counting objects: 100% (11/11), done. remote: Compressing objects: 100% (9/9), done. remote: Total 11 (delta 0), reused 9 (delta 0), pack-reused 0 Receiving objects: 100% (11/11), 9.57 KiB | 0 bytes/s, done.</pre><p></p>""", meta={'folders': ['logistics'], 'title': 'VSCode Remote-SSH Scholar Setup Guide', 'timestamp': '2023-01-13T21:51:53Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['logistics', 'student'], 'likes': 14, 'views': 241}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Do we have to create a release/tag or just pushing with a comment is sufficient?</p> Answer: Just push""", meta={'folders': ['logistics'], 'title': 'Do we have to create a release?', 'timestamp': '2023-01-13T20:14:35Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['logistics', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 188}),
	Document(content="""Note: <p>Hi Class!</p><p></p><p>*Important Note: Please fill out the GitHub user google form: <a href='https://forms.gle/NquvovH7e9fu4zyi6'><strong>https://forms.gle/NquvovH7e9fu4zyi6</strong></a></p><p></p><p><strong>IF WE DO NOT HAVE YOUR GITHUB INFO, THE AUTOGRADER WILL AUTOMATICALLY GIVE YOU A 0</strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p><b>*Additional note, Problem 1 in problems.py has a comment that mentions &#34;election year&#34; it should read &#34;leap year&#34;. Follow the instructions in the README. </b></p><p><br />Homework 1 has been released on GitHub classroom. Please use the link in the post to accept the assignment and get started with the first homework for the course. Note that Homework 1 is due on the 20th of January at 11:59pm. Moreover, you can also take benefit of the TA lab hours (in-person and virtual) to get help for the current and all future homeworks. <br /><br /></p><p>Homework 1: <a href='https://classroom.github.com/a/2xc43z70' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>https://classroom.github.com/a/2xc43z70</a><br />*Follow the link, you will get access to the homework. The homework will provide instructions on how to submit the homework. This class does not have the students added the github classroom. <strong>Use the same github account that you documented in the git hub user google form survey! </strong></p><p></p><p dir='ltr'>TA Lab Hours Info:<br />Virtual lab hours (Discord): T-F 9-11 am ET, 1-2 pm ET, and 5-8 pm ET. Discord link: <a href='https://discord.gg/vU94QaeacS'><strong>https://discord.gg/vU94QaeacS</strong></a></p><p dir='ltr'>Limited in-person lab hours (maximum of 10 people per half hour slot) :<br />BHEE 206(primary - go here first) &amp; 207 (overflow) T-F 5pm-8pm ET <br /><br /><br /><br /></p><p><br /><br /></p><p></p>""", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'H1 Released', 'timestamp': '2023-01-13T17:11:52Z', 'user': 'kskmxecspaq4i1', 'tags': ['hw1', 'instructor-note'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 326}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Don’t want to rush things but I have not yet been added to github classroom and some extra time over the weekend would be nice to work on the hw.</p> Answer: <p>You will not be &#34;added&#34; to the github classroom. Every week we will have a piazza post with the link that you will be able to retrieve the homework from github classroom. The first homework has instructions on how to properly submit the homework (note 13): <a href='/class/lcj9rez4czg6zj/post/13' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>https://piazza.com/class/lcj9rez4czg6zj/post/13</a></p><p></p>""", meta={'folders': ['logistics'], 'title': 'Still not added to github classroom?', 'timestamp': '2023-01-13T15:57:22Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['logistics', 'student'], 'likes': 8, 'views': 219}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>I was looking through the syllabus and noticed a Scholar cluster mentioned. I&#39;ve never heard of this, and was wondering if I could receive some clarification on this topic? Are we supposed to download a specific IDE from this cluster? </p> Answer: The Scholar cluster (https://www.rcac.purdue.edu/compute/scholar) is a computer cluster that you will have access to as a part of this class. You can make use of it (more instructions on the website!) to write and test your homework/project code. While you can (and it is good that you do) set up Python for your personal computer, you can also use Scholar to run your programs (and you don&#39;t have to download any particular IDE, or anything really, to make use of Scholar).<div><div>That aside, to ensure consistency in grading, we ask that your code must run on the versions of Python in the Scholar cluster. </div><div><br /></div></div>""", meta={'folders': ['logistics'], 'title': 'Scholar Cluster?', 'timestamp': '2023-01-12T17:30:18Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['logistics', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 242}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>What day during the week will homework normally be due?</p> Answer: Fri""", meta={'folders': ['logistics'], 'title': 'Homework due date', 'timestamp': '2023-01-11T23:56:10Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['logistics', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 261}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Will lectures be recorded and uploaded on brightspace after class? Or will class slides be posted for us?</p> Answer: <p>the slides will be posted.</p><p></p>""", meta={'folders': ['other'], 'title': 'Lecture recordings', 'timestamp': '2023-01-11T19:30:43Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['other', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 230}),
	Document(content="""Question: are we supposed to have access to the github classroom now ? I don&#39;t yet. Answer: You have to fill out the survey and then wait for the administrators to grant you access to the GitHub. So no. I don’t have it yet either. The first homework is not due until next week, so you should start worrying if you don’t have it by Friday.""", meta={'folders': ['logistics', 'other'], 'title': 'Github classroom', 'timestamp': '2023-01-10T20:42:37Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['logistics', 'other', 'student'], 'likes': 5, 'views': 285}),
	Document(content="""Question: <p>Hello, </p><p></p><p>First of all, I hope you had a nice winter break. I am very excited to start this semester and take this course. It sounds very interesting and important for my future studies. My name is Ata Ulas Guler. I&#39;m a sophomore from Turkey, studying computer engineering. I went back home for this Christmas break, so I am currently in Turkey. My flight will arrive on Tuesday, so unfortunately I will be missing my classes on Monday and Tuesday. These include ECE 20875 26452-004. I wanted to post a question here so that you are aware of my absence. I have read the syllabus and will be checking any announcement you have made or will be making in the next couple of days. Is there anything you want me to do for this absence? I would appreciate your answers, and I wish everyone a great semester :)</p><p></p><p>Thank you for your time and understanding,</p><p></p><p>Ata Ulas Guler</p> Answer: <p>Since there is a small fraction of your grade that depends on attendance, your absence on Tuesday will be recorded. But one absence alone is unlikely to affect your overall grade. You can catch up on the content of the first lecture by reading the Brightspace materials. If you have further questions about this, please contact the TAs.</p>""", meta={'folders': ['logistics', 'other'], 'title': 'Absence due to flight (section 004 Tuesday lecture)', 'timestamp': '2023-01-09T11:07:37Z', 'user': 'ktnb68csasm6k1', 'tags': ['logistics', 'other', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 27}),
